{"title_page": "Fanny Rice", "text_new": "''(for the later Ziegfeld star of similar name see [[Fanny Brice]])''\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Fanny Rice\n| image = Fanny Rice, stage actress (SAYRE 8806).jpg\n| caption = Fanny Rice  circa 1892\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = February 7, 1859\n| birth_place = [[Lowell, Massachusetts]], (Middlesex County)  USA\n| death_date = July 10, 1936\n| death_place = [[Bronx, New York]]\n| restingplace = Franklin Cemetery, [[Franklin, New Hampshire]] ([[Merrimack County, New Hampshire|Merrimack County]])\n| restingplacecoordinates =\n| othername = Fannie Rice\n| occupation = actress, singer\n| yearsactive = 1880s-1920\n| spouse = Warren H. Purdy<br>G. W. Purdy\n| children =\n}}\n'''Fanny Rice''' (1859-1936)<ref>''American and British Theatrical Biography'', p.785 c.1979 by J. P. Wearing {{ISBN|0-8108-1201-0}}</ref> was an American singer, comedienne and actress of stage and screen. She was born to Edward C. Rice and Ianthe Rice (''nee'' Blanchard).  She had two siblings an older brother Henry who died as a child and two older sisters Clara and Laura.<ref>[http://findagrave.com/memorial/131359324/fanny-purdy  Fanny Rice at findagrave.com]</ref>\n\nBeginning her career in the 1880s she appeared on stage with many stage luminaries of the day like [[Francis Wilson (actor)|Francis Wilson]], [[Jefferson De Angelis]], [[Joseph Jefferson]] and [[Louisa Lane Drew|Mrs. John Drew]] all costarring in a popular revival of Sheridan''s ''[[The Rivals (play)|The Rivals]]''.<ref>''Pictorial History of the American Theatre:1860-1970'', p.47 c.1969 3rd Edition by Daniel Blum {{ISBN|0-517-01095X}}</ref>\n\nHer tenure in films was brief making three [[silent film|silent]] films between 1919 and 1920.<ref>[http://catalog.afi.com/Person/50710-Fanny-Rice?sid=4dc78cb6-1ed4-4df1-9e13-2d3538540ef0&sr=11.646261&cp=1&pos=0&isMiscCredit=false Fanny Rice at AFI Catalog of Feature Films  1893-1993]</ref>\n\nShe died in July 1936 and is interred under her married name of Purdy.<ref>see..findagrave.com</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n*''The Moonshine Trail'' (1919)\n*''Dawn'' (1919)\n*''[[My Husband's Other Wife]]'' (1920)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://imdb.com/name/nm0723421/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1  Fanny Rice at IMDb.com]\n*[https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/search/index?utf8=%E2%9C%93&keywords=fanny+rice Fanny Rice portraits](NYPublic Library, Billy Rose collection)\n*[http://worthpoint.com/worthopedia/cabinet-photo-fanny-rice-baby-snooks-509072665 Sarony portrait of Fanny Rice], with description and text attributed to the later Fanny Brice(archived)\n*[http://worthpoint.com/worthopedia/1890s-cabinet-card-stage-film-actress-1903533735 Fanny Rice] in portrait by ''Newsboy'' photographer's studio(archived)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rice, Fanny}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:19th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People from Lowell, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "''(for the later Ziegfeld star of similar name see [[Fanny Brice]])''\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Fanny Rice\n| image = Fanny Rice, stage actress (SAYRE 8806).jpg\n| caption = Fanny Rice  circa 1892\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = February 7, 1859\n| birth_place = [[Lowell, Massachusetts]], (Middlesex County)  USA\n| death_date = July 10, 1936\n| death_place = [[Bronx, New York]]\n| restingplace = Franklin Cemetery, [[Franklin, New Hampshire]] ([[Merrimack County, New Hampshire|Merrimack County]])\n| restingplacecoordinates =\n| othername = Fannie Rice\n| occupation = actress, singer\n| yearsactive = 1880s-1920\n| spouse = Warren H. Purdy<br>G. W. Purdy\n| children =\n}}\n'''Fanny Rice''' (1859-1936)<ref>''American and British Theatrical Biography'', p.785 c.1979 by J. P. Wearing {{ISBN|0-8108-1201-0}}</ref> was an American singer, comedienne and actress of stage and screen. She was born to Edward C. Rice and Ianthe Rice (''nee'' Blanchard).  She had two siblings an older brother Henry who died as a child and two older sisters Clara and Laura.<ref>[http://findagrave.com/memorial/131359324/fanny-purdy  Fanny Rice at findagrave.com]</ref>\n\nBeginning her career in the 1880s she appeared on stage with many stage luminaries of the day like [[Francis Wilson (actor)|Francis Wilson]], [[Jefferson De Angelis]], [[Joseph Jefferson]] and [[Louisa Lane Drew|Mrs. John Drew]] all costarring in a popular revival of Sheridan''s ''[[The Rivals (play)|The Rivals]]''.<ref>''Pictorial History of the American Theatre:1860-1970'', p.47 c.1969 3rd Edition by Daniel Blum {{ISBN|0-517-01095X}}</ref>\n\nHer tenure in films was brief making three [[silent film|silent]] films between 1919 and 1920.<ref>[http://catalog.afi.com/Person/50710-Fanny-Rice?sid=4dc78cb6-1ed4-4df1-9e13-2d3538540ef0&sr=11.646261&cp=1&pos=0&isMiscCredit=false Fanny Rice at AFI Catalog of Feature Films  1893-1993]</ref>\n\nShe died in July 1936 and is interred under her married name of Purdy.<ref>see..findagrave.com</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n*''The Moonshine Trail'' (1919)\n*''Dawn'' (1919)\n*''[[My Husband's Other Wife]]'' (1920)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://imdb.com/name/nm0723421/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1  Fanny Rice at IMDb.com]\n*[https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/search/index?utf8=%E2%9C%93&keywords=fanny+rice Fanny Rice portraits](NYPublic Library, Billy Rose collection)\n*[http://worthpoint.com/worthopedia/cabinet-photo-fanny-rice-baby-snooks-509072665 Sarony portrait of Fanny Rice], with description and text attributed to the later Fanny Brice(archived)\n*[http://worthpoint.com/worthopedia/1890s-cabinet-card-stage-film-actress-1903533735 Fanny Rice] in portrait by ''Newsboy'' photographer's studio(archived)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rice, Fanny}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:19th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People from Lowell, Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:American silent film actressestoCategory:20th-century American actressesusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fanny_Rice"}
{"title_page": "Louise Rial", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Louise Rial\n| image =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Louise Grover\n| birth_date = 1850\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = August 9, 1940\n| death_place = [[New York City]], New York ([[Manhattan County]])\n| restingplace = [[Kensico Cemetery]], [[Valhalla, New York]] ([[Westchester County, New York]])\n| restingplacecoordinates =\n| othername = Louise Briehl\n| occupation = actress\n| yearsactive = 1880s-1919\n| spouse = James Grove Rial (aka Jay Rial)<ref>''Silent Film Necrology'', p.442 2nd Edition c.2001 Eugene M. Vazzana ..ISBN 0-7864-1059-0</ref>\n| children = Vira Rial (aka Vera Rial)\n}}\n'''Louise Rial''' (c.1850-1940)<ref>''American and British Theatrical Biography'' c. 1979 by J. P. Wearing..{{ISBN|0-8108-1201-0}}</ref> was an American stage and film actress. Her parents were Thomas C. Grover and Caroline Grover (''nee'' Chamberlin). She had four siblings Burr, Leonard, Lucien and Julia Grover. She started in the theatre in the Victorian era in a version of ''Uncle Tom's Cabin'' 1878 and had a long stage career before entering [[silent films|silent]] films in 1915 with the early [[Fox Film Corporation]].\n\nShe lived until 1940 and is buried in an actor's plot at [[Kensico Cemetery]] Valhalla New York.<ref>[http://findagrave.com/memorial/11262079/louise-rial Louise Rial at findagrave.com]</ref>  Her daughter Vira Rial(1873-1950) is buried with her in the plot.\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[Sin (1915 film)|Sin]]'' (1915)\n*''The Marble Heart'' (1916)\n*''[[A Wife's Sacrifice]]'' (1916)\n*''The Spider and the Fly'' (1916)\n*''[[A Daughter of the Gods]]'' (1916)\n*''[[Tangled Lives]]'' (1917)\n*''[[My Little Sister (1919 film)|My Little Sister]]'' (1919)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://imdb.com/name/nm0722675/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1 Louise Rial at IMDb.com]\n*[http://ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/louise-rial-68611 Louise Rial at IBDb.com]\n*[http://worthpoint.com/worthopedia/antique-actress-louise-rial-autograph-1889019711 portrait](archived)\n*[http://picclickimg.com/00/s/MTA3OVgxNTk1/z/jGoAAOSwjlBaPDM-/$/RARE-Advertising-Trade-Card-Set-1881-Uncle-Toms-_57.jpg  Louise and Jay Rial] 1881 poster for \"Uncle Tom's Cabin\"\n*[http://archive.org/details/pictorialhistoryof00blum/page/106  Louise Rial ] with Robert B. Mantell and Genevieve Hamper in Fox's \"A Wife's Sacrifice\" 1916 page 107\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rial, Louise}}\n[[Category:1850s births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Louise Rial\n| image =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Louise Grover\n| birth_date = 1850\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = August 9, 1940\n| death_place = [[New York City]], New York ([[Manhattan County]])\n| restingplace = [[Kensico Cemetery]], [[Valhalla, New York]] ([[Westchester County, New York]])\n| restingplacecoordinates =\n| othername = Louise Briehl\n| occupation = actress\n| yearsactive = 1880s-1919\n| spouse = James Grove Rial (aka Jay Rial)<ref>''Silent Film Necrology'', p.442 2nd Edition c.2001 Eugene M. Vazzana ..ISBN 0-7864-1059-0</ref>\n| children = Vira Rial (aka Vera Rial)\n}}\n'''Louise Rial''' (c.1850-1940)<ref>''American and British Theatrical Biography'' c. 1979 by J. P. Wearing..{{ISBN|0-8108-1201-0}}</ref> was an American stage and film actress. Her parents were Thomas C. Grover and Caroline Grover (''nee'' Chamberlin). She had four siblings Burr, Leonard, Lucien and Julia Grover. She started in the theatre in the Victorian era in a version of ''Uncle Tom's Cabin'' 1878 and had a long stage career before entering [[silent films|silent]] films in 1915 with the early [[Fox Film Corporation]].\n\nShe lived until 1940 and is buried in an actor's plot at [[Kensico Cemetery]] Valhalla New York.<ref>[http://findagrave.com/memorial/11262079/louise-rial Louise Rial at findagrave.com]</ref>  Her daughter Vira Rial(1873-1950) is buried with her in the plot.\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[Sin (1915 film)|Sin]]'' (1915)\n*''The Marble Heart'' (1916)\n*''[[A Wife's Sacrifice]]'' (1916)\n*''The Spider and the Fly'' (1916)\n*''[[A Daughter of the Gods]]'' (1916)\n*''[[Tangled Lives]]'' (1917)\n*''[[My Little Sister (1919 film)|My Little Sister]]'' (1919)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://imdb.com/name/nm0722675/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1 Louise Rial at IMDb.com]\n*[http://ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/louise-rial-68611 Louise Rial at IBDb.com]\n*[http://worthpoint.com/worthopedia/antique-actress-louise-rial-autograph-1889019711 portrait](archived)\n*[http://picclickimg.com/00/s/MTA3OVgxNTk1/z/jGoAAOSwjlBaPDM-/$/RARE-Advertising-Trade-Card-Set-1881-Uncle-Toms-_57.jpg  Louise and Jay Rial] 1881 poster for \"Uncle Tom's Cabin\"\n*[http://archive.org/details/pictorialhistoryof00blum/page/106  Louise Rial ] with Robert B. Mantell and Genevieve Hamper in Fox's \"A Wife's Sacrifice\" 1916 page 107\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rial, Louise}}\n[[Category:1850s births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:American silent film actressestoCategory:20th-century American actressesusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louise_Rial"}
{"title_page": "Kathleen O'Connor (actress)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kathleen O'Connor\n| image              = Kathleen_O'Connor_-_Jan_1922_EH.jpg\n| birth_name         = Kathleen Mavourneen O'Connor\n| birth_date         = July 7, 1894\n| birth_place        = Dayton, Ohio, USA\n| death_date         = June 24, 1957\n| death_place        = Los Angeles, California, USA\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = \n| spouse             = [[Lynn Reynolds]] (m. 1921)<br>\n}}\n\n'''Kathleen O'Conner''' (sometimes credited as '''Kathleen Conners''') was an American actress active in Hollywood during the silent era.\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early life ===\nKathleen was born in Dayton, Ohio, to John O'Connor (a police officer) and Elizabeth Kinney.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/397465000/?terms=%22kathleen+o%27connor%22+actress|title=Kathleen O'Connor, Dayton Girl, Wins Fame and Fortune|last=|first=|date=13 Dec 1918|website=The Dayton Daily News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> Her parents were both Irish immigrants.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/471017556/?terms=%22kathleen+o%27connor%22+actress|title=The Lion's Man Stirring Serial at Dreamland|last=|first=|date=9 Oct 1920|website=The Edmonton Journal|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> She graduated from high school and began working as a telephone operator in Toledo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/605936349/?terms=%22kathleen+o%27connor%22+actress|title=Kathleen O'Connor|last=|first=|date=15 Jul 1921|website=The Fairview Republican|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Hollywood career ===\nAfter touring with a local stock company, she convinced her parents to let her go to Hollywood around 1917 to seek her fortune in the movies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/96066629/?terms=%22kathleen+o%27connor%22+actress|title=Kathleen O'Connor and Jack Perrin|last=|first=|date=3 Jul 1920|website=The Salina Evening Journal|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> Early on, she secured work as an extra in [[Mack Sennett]] comedies,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/501537979/?terms=%22kathleen+o%27connor+reynolds%22|title=Former Leading Lady Dies at 60|last=|first=|date=26 Jun 1957|website=The Province|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> but she was soon discovered by [[Tom Mix]] and selected to be the cowboy's leading lady. She became known as a leading lady in 1920s Westerns.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Death of Lynn Reynolds ===\nShe married prolific directer [[Lynn Reynolds]] in 1921. Reynolds committed suicide in front of Kathleen and a handful of guests at a dinner party in 1927. Witnesses report that Reynolds had beaten Kathleen before retrieving the gun.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/101393159/?terms=%22kathleen+o%27connor%22+actress|title=S.F. Film Man Beats Wife, Kills Self|last=|first=|date=25 Feb 1927|website=The Oakland Tribune|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Later life ===\nO'Connor withdrew from the film industry after Lynn Reynolds's death. She later married Clark Reynolds (no relation to Lynn). She died in 1957 after a long illness.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n\n*''[[Dark Stairways]]'' (1924)\n*''[[Wild Bill Hickok (film)|Wild Bill Hickok]]'' (1923)\n*[[The Old Homestead (1922 film)|''The Old Homestead'']] (1922)\n*''[[The Married Flapper]]'' (1922)\n*''[[The Trouper]]'' (1922)\n*''[[Life's Darn Funny]]'' (1921)\n*''[[Sunset Jones]]'' (1921)\n*''[[Prairie Trails]]'' (1920)\n*''[[The Path She Chose]]'' (1920)\n*''[[Bullet Proof (1920 film)|Bullet Proof]]'' (1920)\n*''[[The Lion Man (serial)|The Lion Man]]'' (1919)\n*''[[A Gun Fightin' Gentleman]]'' (1919)\n*''[[The Midnight Man (1919 film)|The Midnight Man]]'' (1919)\n*''[[Hell-Roarin' Reform]]'' (1919)\n*''[[Fame and Fortune (film)|Fame and Fortune]]'' (1918)\n*''[[Mr. Logan, U.S.A.]]'' (1918)\n*''[[Missing (1918 film)|Missing]]'' (1918)\n*''[[Ace High (1919 film)|Ace High]]'' (1918)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:O'Connor, Kathleen)}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1957 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Dayton, Ohio]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kathleen O'Connor\n| image              = Kathleen_O'Connor_-_Jan_1922_EH.jpg\n| birth_name         = Kathleen Mavourneen O'Connor\n| birth_date         = July 7, 1894\n| birth_place        = Dayton, Ohio, USA\n| death_date         = June 24, 1957\n| death_place        = Los Angeles, California, USA\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = \n| spouse             = [[Lynn Reynolds]] (m. 1921)<br>\n}}\n\n'''Kathleen O'Conner''' (sometimes credited as '''Kathleen Conners''') was an American actress active in Hollywood during the silent era.\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early life ===\nKathleen was born in Dayton, Ohio, to John O'Connor (a police officer) and Elizabeth Kinney.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/397465000/?terms=%22kathleen+o%27connor%22+actress|title=Kathleen O'Connor, Dayton Girl, Wins Fame and Fortune|last=|first=|date=13 Dec 1918|website=The Dayton Daily News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> Her parents were both Irish immigrants.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/471017556/?terms=%22kathleen+o%27connor%22+actress|title=The Lion's Man Stirring Serial at Dreamland|last=|first=|date=9 Oct 1920|website=The Edmonton Journal|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> She graduated from high school and began working as a telephone operator in Toledo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/605936349/?terms=%22kathleen+o%27connor%22+actress|title=Kathleen O'Connor|last=|first=|date=15 Jul 1921|website=The Fairview Republican|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Hollywood career ===\nAfter touring with a local stock company, she convinced her parents to let her go to Hollywood around 1917 to seek her fortune in the movies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/96066629/?terms=%22kathleen+o%27connor%22+actress|title=Kathleen O'Connor and Jack Perrin|last=|first=|date=3 Jul 1920|website=The Salina Evening Journal|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> Early on, she secured work as an extra in [[Mack Sennett]] comedies,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/501537979/?terms=%22kathleen+o%27connor+reynolds%22|title=Former Leading Lady Dies at 60|last=|first=|date=26 Jun 1957|website=The Province|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> but she was soon discovered by [[Tom Mix]] and selected to be the cowboy's leading lady. She became known as a leading lady in 1920s Westerns.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Death of Lynn Reynolds ===\nShe married prolific directer [[Lynn Reynolds]] in 1921. Reynolds committed suicide in front of Kathleen and a handful of guests at a dinner party in 1927. Witnesses report that Reynolds had beaten Kathleen before retrieving the gun.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/101393159/?terms=%22kathleen+o%27connor%22+actress|title=S.F. Film Man Beats Wife, Kills Self|last=|first=|date=25 Feb 1927|website=The Oakland Tribune|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Later life ===\nO'Connor withdrew from the film industry after Lynn Reynolds's death. She later married Clark Reynolds (no relation to Lynn). She died in 1957 after a long illness.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n\n*''[[Dark Stairways]]'' (1924)\n*''[[Wild Bill Hickok (film)|Wild Bill Hickok]]'' (1923)\n*[[The Old Homestead (1922 film)|''The Old Homestead'']] (1922)\n*''[[The Married Flapper]]'' (1922)\n*''[[The Trouper]]'' (1922)\n*''[[Life's Darn Funny]]'' (1921)\n*''[[Sunset Jones]]'' (1921)\n*''[[Prairie Trails]]'' (1920)\n*''[[The Path She Chose]]'' (1920)\n*''[[Bullet Proof (1920 film)|Bullet Proof]]'' (1920)\n*''[[The Lion Man (serial)|The Lion Man]]'' (1919)\n*''[[A Gun Fightin' Gentleman]]'' (1919)\n*''[[The Midnight Man (1919 film)|The Midnight Man]]'' (1919)\n*''[[Hell-Roarin' Reform]]'' (1919)\n*''[[Fame and Fortune (film)|Fame and Fortune]]'' (1918)\n*''[[Mr. Logan, U.S.A.]]'' (1918)\n*''[[Missing (1918 film)|Missing]]'' (1918)\n*''[[Ace High (1919 film)|Ace High]]'' (1918)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:O'Connor, Kathleen)}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1957 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Dayton, Ohio]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:American silent film actressestoCategory:20th-century American actressesusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kathleen_O%27Connor_(actress)"}
{"title_page": "Mary McIvor", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mary McIvor\n| birth_name         = Mary Ellsworth McKeever\n| birth_date         = August 31, 1897\n| birth_place        = Barnesville, Ohio, USA\n| death_date         = February 28, 1941\n| death_place        = Los Angeles, California, USA\n| occupation         = Actress\n| spouse             = [[William Desmond (actor)|William Desmond]]\n}}\n\n'''Mary McIvor''' (born '''Mary McKeever''') was an American actress who was active during Hollywood's [[silent era]]. She was married to serial star [[William Desmond (actor)|William Desmond]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Langman|first=Larry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LXYwCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA202&lpg=PA202&dq=%22mary+mcivor%22+actress&source=bl&ots=nZjif25qnp&sig=ACfU3U0_I_91CgdciYm8-D-vJ3S3olx4hA&hl=en&ppis=_c&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj0jMCCj6PoAhXW7Z4KHdsjBScQ6AEwEHoECA0QAQ#v=onepage&q=%22mary%20mcivor%22%20actress&f=false|title=The Media in the Movies: A Catalog of American Journalism Films, 1900-1996|date=2015-07-11|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-0925-6|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c88qAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA27-PP9&lpg=RA27-PP9&dq=%22mary+mcivor%22+actress&source=bl&ots=jvCLa9ydrc&sig=ACfU3U1zJQP66PJXq2GBB5YgjtvkLXpSJw&hl=en&ppis=_c&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjzv5L9j6PoAhXUv54KHab2DdA4FBDoATAJegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=%22mary%20mcivor%22%20actress&f=false|title=The Moving Picture World|date=1917|publisher=World Photographic Publishing Company|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nMary was born in [[Barnesville, Ohio]], to Elmer McKeever and Bertha Bentley.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/380400587/?terms=%22mary+mckeever%22|title=William Desmond Weds Secretary|last=|first=|date=23 Mar 1919|website=The Los Angeles Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Her father died when she was young.\n\nAfter moving west, she found work in Hollywood as an actress in Westerns at [[Triangle Film Corporation|Triangle]], eventually becoming the leading lady for [[William S. Hart]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/80007414/?terms=%22mary+mcivor%22|title=Mary McIvor Back After Illness|last=|first=|date=14 Dec 1917|website=The Bourbon News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> She married her co-star, William Desmond, in 1919, after becoming his personal secretary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/637007504/?terms=%22mary+mcivor%22|title=William Desmond Is Dead|last=|first=|date=4 Nov 1949|website=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/288618893/?terms=%22mary+mcivor%22|title=About Shows and Pictures and Players|last=|first=|date=8 Mar 1919|website=Salt Lake Telegram|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Mary more or less retired from acting in 1920, the year the couple's first daughter Mary was born.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/380429248/?terms=%22mary+mcivor%22|title=Desmond a Papa|last=|first=|date=8 Apr 1920|website=The Los Angeles Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Katchmer|first=George A.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VnGeCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=%22mary+mcivor%22+actress&source=bl&ots=YxLLLXmNmj&sig=ACfU3U1JIt2RisGE-kXEvHnW0AjDTQrTRg&hl=en&ppis=_c&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj0jMCCj6PoAhXW7Z4KHdsjBScQ6AEwEXoECA4QAQ#v=onepage&q=%22mary%20mcivor%22%20actress&f=false|title=A Biographical Dictionary of Silent Film Western Actors and Actresses|date=2015-05-20|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-0905-8|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U3hJAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1193&lpg=PA1193&dq=%22mary+mcivor%22+actress&source=bl&ots=kHojJSgjn6&sig=ACfU3U39p0giA066mdD9iAsNxUq5iy2emw&hl=en&ppis=_c&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj0jMCCj6PoAhXW7Z4KHdsjBScQ6AEwE3oECBkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22mary%20mcivor%22%20actress&f=false|title=Motography|date=1917|language=en}}</ref>\n\nMcIvor's health began to sharply decline around 1930. As a result, the family spent time at a beach cottage in her home state in 1932; during their trip, McIvor wandered off and was reported missing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/400723549/?terms=%22mary+desmond%22|title=Actress Is Found|last=|first=|date=3 Jan 1932|website=Dayton Daily News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> In April 1939, Desmond reported his wife missing again from their apartment in Los Angeles; she was found wandering the streets of Hollywood nine days later and subsequently treated by doctors for amnesia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/414357043/?terms=%22mary+mcivor%22|title=Missing Ex-Actress Found in Los Angeles|last=|first=|date=8 Apr 1939|website=The Montgomery Advertiser|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/161427498/?terms=%22mary+mcivor%22|title=Former Movie Actress Treated for Amnesia|last=|first=|date=8 Apr 1939|website=The News Journal|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2006/scene/people-news/femmes-framed-by-old-stereotypes-1200335198/|title=Femmes framed by old stereotypes|last=Guider|first=Elizabeth|last2=Guider|first2=Elizabeth|date=2006-04-23|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> The pair remained married until her death in 1941 of a heart attack.\n\n== References ==\n\n* ''[[The Burning Trail]]'' (1925)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/287190473/?terms=%22mary+mcivor%22|title=Gem Today|last=|first=|date=20 Sep 1930|website=The Newark Advocate|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Right Man (1925 film)|The Right Man]]'' (1929)\n* ''[[In His Brother's Place]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[Chasing Rainbeaux]]'' (1919)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/119543060/?terms=%22mary+mcivor%22|title=Mary McIvor Brilliant in 'Chasing Rainbeaux'|last=|first=|date=10 Aug 1919|website=The Tennessean|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Mints of Hell]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[Gambling in Souls]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[The Sudden Gentleman]]'' (1917)\n* ''[[A Phantom Husband]]'' (1917)\n* ''[[Flying Colors (1917 film)|Flying Colors]]'' (1917) \n* ''[[The Square Deal Man]]'' (1917) \n* ''Paddy O'Hara'' (1917)\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McIvor, Mary}}\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mary McIvor\n| birth_name         = Mary Ellsworth McKeever\n| birth_date         = August 31, 1897\n| birth_place        = Barnesville, Ohio, USA\n| death_date         = February 28, 1941\n| death_place        = Los Angeles, California, USA\n| occupation         = Actress\n| spouse             = [[William Desmond (actor)|William Desmond]]\n}}\n\n'''Mary McIvor''' (born '''Mary McKeever''') was an American actress who was active during Hollywood's [[silent era]]. She was married to serial star [[William Desmond (actor)|William Desmond]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Langman|first=Larry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LXYwCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA202&lpg=PA202&dq=%22mary+mcivor%22+actress&source=bl&ots=nZjif25qnp&sig=ACfU3U0_I_91CgdciYm8-D-vJ3S3olx4hA&hl=en&ppis=_c&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj0jMCCj6PoAhXW7Z4KHdsjBScQ6AEwEHoECA0QAQ#v=onepage&q=%22mary%20mcivor%22%20actress&f=false|title=The Media in the Movies