{"title_page": "Betty May (actress)", "text_new": "{{short description|American silent-film actress}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Betty May\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Betty May, American film actress.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = Elizabeth Jane May\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1904|06|22}}\n| birth_place      = [[Cripple Creek, Colorado]], U.S.\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1949|11|13|1904|06|22}}\n| death_place      = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = \n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| home_town        = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| partner          = \n| awards           = \n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = \n| module           = \n}}\n'''Betty May''' (born Elizabeth Jane May; 1904\u20131949), was an actress during the silent film era in America.\n\n==Biography==\n\nBorn in [[Cripple Creek, Colorado]] on 22 June 1904, May worked in cinema from the early 1920s until 1936, appearing in at least sixteen films.\n\nMay made her first appearance for Century Comedy (also known as Century Comedies), a production company founded by [[Abe Stern|Abe]] and [[Julius Stern (producer)|Julius Stern]]. She was signed to a long term contract by Julius Stern in 1922.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |title=\"Betty May Leading for Century\" |url=https://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor57july/page/n6 |accessdate=1 January 2020 |work=Moving Picture World |date=August 26, 1922 |ref=p.668}}</ref> She was described in trade publications at the time as \"the Century beauty\" who was cast in ingenue roles but who \"shows the ability to do more ambitious roles.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHer debut was in the 1922 film ''Upper and Lower'', a comedy directed by [[Alf Goulding]].<ref>{{Citation|title=East Side - West Side|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0014012/|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref> With Century Comedy Films, she appeared in several film with [[Lee Moran]] as the lead, as well as several starring \"Queenie The Human Horse.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1310219/|title=Queenie the Horse|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref> By 1923 she had been contracted by Principal Pictures Corporations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.org/details/movpicwor62movi/page/166|title=Sol Lesser Joins Will Hays' National Body|last=|first=|date=1923-05-12|work=Moving Picture World|access-date=2020-01-01|url-status=live|page=166}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.org/details/movpicwor62movi/page/496|title=Principal Pictures Starts Drive|last=|first=|date=1923-06-09|work=Moving Picture World|access-date=2020-01-01|url-status=live|page=496}}</ref>\n\nAfter 1931, May tended to only appear in small, often un-credited, roles. In 1937 she was interviewed by the San Bernardino Sun for an article about breaking into acting in Hollywood, where she mentions she is studying voice and diction in hopes of getting more roles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=SBS19370307.1.32&e=--1921---1947--en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22Betty+May%22+actress-------1|title=Youth Trying to \"Crash\" into Movies, Has One Chance in 100,000 to Succeed, But Still they Try, Try Again.|last=Lockett|first=Doris|date=1937-03-07|work=San Bernardino Sun|access-date=2020-01-01|url-status=live|page=32}}</ref>\n\nShe died in Los Angeles on November 13, 1949 at the age of 45.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n*[[:it:Upper_and_Lower|Upper and Lower]] (1922)\n*[[:it:Ten_Seconds|Ten Seconds]] (1922)\n*[[:it:True_Blue_(film_1922)|True Blue]] (1922)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor58sept/page/600|title=What Century Offers|last=|first=|date=1922-10-14|work=Moving Picture World|access-date=2020-01-01|url-status=live|page=600}}</ref>\n* Me and My Mule (1922)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor58sept/page/600|title=Newsy Notes|last=|first=|date=1922-10-14|work=Moving Picture World|access-date=2020-01-01|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor57july/page/672|title=Finish Horse Comedy Begin Another|last=|first=|date=1922-08-26|work=|access-date=|url-status=live|page=672}}</ref>\n*[[:it:The_American_Plan|The American Plan]] (1923)\n*[[:it:The_Home_Plate|The Home Plate]] (1923)\n*[[:it:Game_Hunters|Game Hunters]] (1923)\n*[[East Side - West Side]] (1923)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor61mara/page/945|title=East Side West Side Principal Pictures Corporation Can Well be Proud of This Clever Irving Cummings Special|last=Ferri|first=Roger|date=1923-04-28|work=Moving Picture World|access-date=2020-01-01|url-status=live|page=945}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=EAST SIDE - WEST SIDE (SILENT FILM, 1923)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mPUUVWLyM8U|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n* Love on the Rio Grande (1925)\n*[[Flaming Fury (1926 film)|Flaming Fury]] (1926)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://catalog.afi.com/Film/9088-FLAMING-FURY?cxt=filmography|title=AFI{{!}}Catalog|website=catalog.afi.com|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref>\n*[[Night Nurse (1931 film)|Night Nurse]] (1931)\n*[[Sisters Under the Skin]] (1934)\n*[[Whom the Gods Destroy (1934 film)|Whom the Gods Destroy]] (1934)\n*[[Broadway Bill]] (1934)\n*[[Love Me Forever]] (1935)\n*[[Case of the Missing Man]] (1935)\n*[[Dangerous Intrigue]] (1936)\n*[[Sisters Under the Skin]] (1934)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:May, Betty}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:1904 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Cripple Creek, Colorado]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American silent-film actress}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Betty May\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Betty May, American film actress.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = Elizabeth Jane May\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1904|06|22}}\n| birth_place      = [[Cripple Creek, Colorado]], U.S.\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1949|11|13|1904|06|22}}\n| death_place      = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = \n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| home_town        = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| partner          = \n| awards           = \n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = \n| module           = \n}}\n'''Betty May''' (born Elizabeth Jane May; 1904\u20131949), was an actress during the silent film era in America.\n\n==Biography==\n\nBorn in [[Cripple Creek, Colorado]] on 22 June 1904, May worked in cinema from the early 1920s until 1936, appearing in at least sixteen films.\n\nMay made her first appearance for Century Comedy (also known as Century Comedies), a production company founded by [[Abe Stern|Abe]] and [[Julius Stern (producer)|Julius Stern]]. She was signed to a long term contract by Julius Stern in 1922.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |title=\"Betty May Leading for Century\" |url=https://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor57july/page/n6 |accessdate=1 January 2020 |work=Moving Picture World |date=August 26, 1922 |ref=p.668}}</ref> She was described in trade publications at the time as \"the Century beauty\" who was cast in ingenue roles but who \"shows the ability to do more ambitious roles.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHer debut was in the 1922 film ''Upper and Lower'', a comedy directed by [[Alf Goulding]].<ref>{{Citation|title=East Side - West Side|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0014012/|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref> With Century Comedy Films, she appeared in several film with [[Lee Moran]] as the lead, as well as several starring \"Queenie The Human Horse.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1310219/|title=Queenie the Horse|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref> By 1923 she had been contracted by Principal Pictures Corporations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.org/details/movpicwor62movi/page/166|title=Sol Lesser Joins Will Hays' National Body|last=|first=|date=1923-05-12|work=Moving Picture World|access-date=2020-01-01|url-status=live|page=166}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.org/details/movpicwor62movi/page/496|title=Principal Pictures Starts Drive|last=|first=|date=1923-06-09|work=Moving Picture World|access-date=2020-01-01|url-status=live|page=496}}</ref>\n\nAfter 1931, May tended to only appear in small, often un-credited, roles. In 1937 she was interviewed by the San Bernardino Sun for an article about breaking into acting in Hollywood, where she mentions she is studying voice and diction in hopes of getting more roles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=SBS19370307.1.32&e=--1921---1947--en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22Betty+May%22+actress-------1|title=Youth Trying to \"Crash\" into Movies, Has One Chance in 100,000 to Succeed, But Still they Try, Try Again.|last=Lockett|first=Doris|date=1937-03-07|work=San Bernardino Sun|access-date=2020-01-01|url-status=live|page=32}}</ref>\n\nShe died in Los Angeles on November 13, 1949 at the age of 45.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n*[[:it:Upper_and_Lower|Upper and Lower]] (1922)\n*[[:it:Ten_Seconds|Ten Seconds]] (1922)\n*[[:it:True_Blue_(film_1922)|True Blue]] (1922)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor58sept/page/600|title=What Century Offers|last=|first=|date=1922-10-14|work=Moving Picture World|access-date=2020-01-01|url-status=live|page=600}}</ref>\n* Me and My Mule (1922)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor58sept/page/600|title=Newsy Notes|last=|first=|date=1922-10-14|work=Moving Picture World|access-date=2020-01-01|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor57july/page/672|title=Finish Horse Comedy Begin Another|last=|first=|date=1922-08-26|work=|access-date=|url-status=live|page=672}}</ref>\n*[[:it:The_American_Plan|The American Plan]] (1923)\n*[[:it:The_Home_Plate|The Home Plate]] (1923)\n*[[:it:Game_Hunters|Game Hunters]] (1923)\n*[[East Side - West Side]] (1923)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.org/details/movingpicturewor61mara/page/945|title=East Side West Side Principal Pictures Corporation Can Well be Proud of This Clever Irving Cummings Special|last=Ferri|first=Roger|date=1923-04-28|work=Moving Picture World|access-date=2020-01-01|url-status=live|page=945}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=EAST SIDE - WEST SIDE (SILENT FILM, 1923)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mPUUVWLyM8U|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n* Love on the Rio Grande (1925)\n*[[Flaming Fury (1926 film)|Flaming Fury]] (1926)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://catalog.afi.com/Film/9088-FLAMING-FURY?cxt=filmography|title=AFI{{!}}Catalog|website=catalog.afi.com|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref>\n*[[Night Nurse (1931 film)|Night Nurse]] (1931)\n*[[Sisters Under the Skin]] (1934)\n*[[Whom the Gods Destroy (1934 film)|Whom the Gods Destroy]] (1934)\n*[[Broadway Bill]] (1934)\n*[[Love Me Forever]] (1935)\n*[[Case of the Missing Man]] (1935)\n*[[Dangerous Intrigue]] (1936)\n*[[Sisters Under the Skin]] (1934)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:May, Betty}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:1904 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Cripple Creek, Colorado]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:American silent film actressestoCategory:20th-century American actressesusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Betty_May_(actress)"}
{"title_page": "1916 Texas hurricane", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|Category 4 Atlantic hurricane in 1916}}\n{{Infobox hurricane\n| Name=1916 Texas hurricane\n| Type=hurricane\n| Year=1916\n| Basin=Atl\n| Image location=Hurricane Six surface analysis 18 Aug 1916.jpg\n| Image name=[[Surface weather analysis]] of the hurricane nearing landfall upon Texas on August&nbsp;18\n| Image alt=A map of the hurricane and its isobars in the western Gulf of Mexico\n| Formed={{start date|August&nbsp;12, 1916}}\n| Dissipated={{end date|August&nbsp;20, 1916}}\n| 1-min winds=115\n| Pressure=932\n| Pressurepost=Estimated\n| Damages=11.8\n| Fatalities=37 <small>(Jamaica: 17, Texas: 20)</small>\n| Areas={{flatlist|\n*[[Lesser Antilles]]\n*[[Jamaica]]\n*[[Cayman Islands]]\n*[[Mexico]]\n*[[Texas]]\n}}\n| Hurricane season=[[1916 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n}}\nThe '''1916 Texas hurricane''' was an intense and quick-moving [[tropical cyclone]] that caused widespread damage in [[Jamaica]] and [[South Texas]] in August&nbsp;1916. A [[List of Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes|Category&nbsp;4 hurricane]] upon [[landfall (meteorology)|landfall]] in Texas, it was the strongest tropical cyclone to strike the United States in three decades. Throughout its eight-day trek across the [[Caribbean Sea]] and [[Gulf of Mexico]], the hurricane caused 37&nbsp;fatalities and inflicted $11.8&nbsp;million in damage.{{#tag:ref|All monetary values are in 1916&nbsp;[[United States dollar]]s unless otherwise noted.|group=nb}}\n\nWeather observations were limited for most of the storm's history, so much of its evolution has been inferred from scant data analyzed by the [[Atlantic hurricane reanalysis project]] in 2008. The precursor disturbance organized into a small [[tropical storm]] by August&nbsp;12, shortly before crossing the [[Lesser Antilles]] into the Caribbean Sea. The storm skirted the southern coast of Jamaica as a hurricane on August&nbsp;15, killing 17&nbsp;people. No banana plantation was left unscathed by the hours-long onslaught of strong winds. Coconut and cocoa trees also sustained severe losses. The southern [[Parishes of Jamaica|parishes]] saw the severest effects, incurring extensive damage to crops and buildings; damage in Jamaica amounted to $10&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|10|1916|r=0}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}). The storm then traversed the [[Yucat\u00e1n Channel]] into the Gulf of Mexico and intensified further into the equivalent of a [[major hurricane]] on the modern-day [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale]].{{#tag:ref|A major hurricane is a storm that ranks as Category&nbsp;3 or higher on the [[Saffir\u2013Simpson hurricane scale]].<ref name=BASIC>{{cite book|last1=Goldenburg|first1=Stan|chapter=A3) What is a super-typhoon? What is a major hurricane? What is an intense hurricane?|type=FAQ|title=Frequently Asked Questions|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/tcfaqHED.html|chapterurl=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/A3.html|date=June 1, 2018|publisher=[[Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory]]|accessdate=August 2, 2019|version=4.11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060615212545/http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/tcfaqHED.html|archive-date=June 15, 2006|url-status=live}}</ref>|group=\"nb\"}}\n\nOn the evening of August&nbsp;16, the hurricane struck South Texas near [[Baffin Bay, Texas|Baffin Bay]] with [[maximum sustained wind|winds]] of 130&nbsp;mph (215&nbsp;km/h). Buildings were razed at many coastal cities, with the worst impacts felt in [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]] and surrounding communities. Beachfront structures were destroyed by a {{convert|9.2|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=on}} [[storm surge]]. Strong gusts and heavy rainfall spread farther inland across mainly rural sectors of South Texas, damaging towns and their outlying agricultural districts alike. Railroads and other public utilities were disrupted across the region, with widespread [[power outage]]s. Eight locations set 24-hour rainfall records; among them was [[Harlingen, Texas|Harlingen]], which recorded the storm's rainfall maximum with {{cvt|6|in|mm}} of precipitation. The deluge wrought havoc on military camps along the U.S.-[[Mexico]] border, forcing 30,000&nbsp;garrisoned militiamen to evacuate. Aggregate property damage across Texas reached $1.8&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|1.8|1916|r=0}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}), and 20&nbsp;people were killed. The hurricane quickly weakened over southwestern Texas and dissipated near [[New Mexico]] by August&nbsp;20.\n\n==Meteorological history==\n{{storm path|1916 Atlantic hurricane 6 track.png|alt=Map showing the track of the storm, beginning east of the Lesser Antilles and ending over Texas}}\nAccording to the [[National Weather Service|U.S. Weather Bureau]], the {{nowrap|1916 Texas hurricane}} \"followed an average course for the type of August hurricanes that pass through the [[Yucat\u00e1n Channel]]\",<ref name=\"MWR_1916\">{{cite journal |last1=Weightman |first1=Richard Hanson |title=Hurricanes of 1916 and Notes on Hurricanes of 1912\u20131915 |journal=[[Monthly Weather Review]] |date=December 1916 |volume=44 |issue=12 |page=686 |doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1916)44<686:HOANOH>2.0.CO;2 |url=ftp://ftp.library.noaa.gov/docs.lib/htdocs/rescue/mwr/044/mwr-044-12-0686.pdf |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |publisher=[[American Meteorological Society]] |location=[[Boston, Massachusetts]] |bibcode=1916MWRv...44..686W}} {{open access}}</ref> but maintained an unusually brisk forward speed throughout its life.<ref name=\"Roth_TX\">{{cite web |last1=Roth |first1=David M. |title=Texas Hurricane History |url=https://origin.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/research/txhur.pdf |publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |location=[[Camp Springs, Maryland]] |pages=36\u201337 |date=February 3, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721231821/http://origin.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/research/txhur.pdf |archive-date=July 21, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> A possible precursor disturbance may have originated as early as August&nbsp;8 near Africa, but observations were inconclusive in determining the [[tropical cyclogenesis|formation]] of a [[tropical cyclone]].<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> The hurricane was first definitively detected as a [[tropical storm]] east of [[Barbados]] on August&nbsp;12,<ref name=\"MWR_Atlantic\">{{cite journal |title=Weather Conditions Over the North Atlantic Ocean During August, 1916 |journal=Monthly Weather Review |date=August 1917 |volume=45 |issue=8 |pages=429\u2013431 |doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1917)45<429:WCOTNA>2.0.CO;2 |url=ftp://ftp.library.noaa.gov/docs.lib/htdocs/rescue/mwr/045/mwr-045-08-0429.pdf |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |publisher=American Meteorological Society |location=Boston, Massachusetts |bibcode=1917MWRv...45..429.}} {{open access}}</ref> based on a 40-mph (64&nbsp;km/h) wind measurement from a nearby ship.<ref name=\"Metadata\">{{cite web|last1=Landsea|first1=Chris|last2=Anderson|first2=Craig|last3=Bredemeyer|first3=William|last4=Carrasco|first4=Cristina|last5=Charles|first5=Noel|last6=Chenoweth|first6=Michael|last7=Clark|first7=Gil|last8=Delgado|first8=Sandy|last9=Dunion|first9=Jason|last10=Ellis|first10=Ryan|last11=Fernandez-Partagas|first11=Jose|last12=Feuer|first12=Steve|last13=Gamanche|first13=John|last14=Glenn|first14=David|last15=Hagen|first15=Andrew|last16=Hufstetler|first16=Lyle|last17=Mock|first17=Cary|last18=Neumann|first18=Charlie|last19=Perez Suarez|first19=Ramon|last20=Prieto|first20=Ricardo|last21=Sanchez-Sesma|first21=Jorge|last22=Santiago|first22=Adrian|last23=Sims|first23=Jamese|last24=Thomas|first24=Donna|last25=Lenworth|first25=Woolcock|last26=Zimmer|first26=Mark|authorlink1=Christopher Landsea|title=Documentation of Atlantic Tropical Cyclones Changes in HURDAT|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/metadata_master.html|website=Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=July 31, 2019|date=May 2015|location=[[Miami, Florida]]|type=Metadata|at=1916/06 - 2008 Revision|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604063810/http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/metadata_master.html|archive-date=June 4, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> There were no additional observations of similarly gusty winds or low [[barometric pressure|air pressures]] over the next three days while the system traced out the southern periphery of the [[Azores High]] westward into the eastern [[Caribbean Sea]].{{Atlantic hurricane best track}}<ref name=\"Metadata\" /><ref name=\"NHRP3\">{{cite report |last1=Schoner |first1=R. W. |last2=Molansky |first2=S. |title=Rainfall Associated with Hurricanes (And Other Tropical Disturbances) |chapter=Storms in the South Atlantic Coastal Region |issue=3 |url=https://www.aoml.noaa.gov/general/lib/TM/NHRP_03_1956.pdf |publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |accessdate=June 23, 2019 |location=[[Washington, D.C.]] |page=100 |format=PDF |date=July 1956 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521100141/http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/general/lib/TM/NHRP_03_1956.pdf |archivedate=May 21, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Steady intensification was inferred during this period by the [[Atlantic hurricane reanalysis project]] in 2008,<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> which estimated that the storm strengthened into a hurricane on August&nbsp;15 while located south of [[Hispaniola]].{{Atlantic hurricane best track}}<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> Concurrently, the hurricane curved slightly towards the west-northwest, bringing it just south of [[Jamaica]] that day with winds of 85&nbsp;mph (135&nbsp;km/h).<ref name=\"Metadata\" /><ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\">{{cite journal |last1=Henry |first1=Alfred J. |title=Forecasts and Warnings |journal=Monthly Weather Review |date=August 1916 |volume=44 |issue=8 |pages=461\u2013463 |doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1916)44<461:FAWFA>2.0.CO;2 |url=ftp://ftp.library.noaa.gov/docs.lib/htdocs/rescue/mwr/044/mwr-044-08-0461.pdf |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |publisher=American Meteorological Society |location=Boston, Massachusetts |bibcode=1916MWRv...44..461H}} {{open access}}</ref> Near the [[Cayman Islands]], a vessel recorded 55-mph (89&nbsp;km/h) winds, ultimately proving to be the strongest offshore winds sampled in connection with the cyclone.<ref name=\"MWR_Atlantic\" /> Continuing to intensify, the hurricane emerged into the [[Gulf of Mexico]] through the Yucat\u00e1n Channel on the morning of August&nbsp;17.<ref name=\"Metadata\" /><ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" />\n\nWeather observations remained scant in the open waters of the Gulf of Mexico, with the strongest observed winds limited to marginal gales. The storm reached [[major hurricane]] intensity just north of the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]] on August&nbsp;17, and reports on the developing hurricane proliferated as the storm neared the [[Texas]] coast.<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> By August&nbsp;18, the hurricane reached [[List of Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes|{{nowrap|Category 4 intensity}}]] in the western Gulf of Mexico;{{Atlantic hurricane best track}} the first [[rainband|outer band]]s began reaching the coast near [[Corpus Christi, Texas]], early that morning.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> During the evening hours, the center of the hurricane made [[landfall (meteorology)|landfall]] near [[Baffin Bay, Texas]], with [[maximum sustained wind]]s of {{convert|130|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} and a central pressure of 932&nbsp;[[bar (unit)|mbar]] ([[pascal (unit)|hPa]]; 27.52&nbsp;[[inches of mercury|inHg]]).<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> These parameters made it the strongest hurricane of the [[1916 Atlantic hurricane season]].{{Atlantic hurricane best track}} In terms of pressure, the 1916&nbsp;Texas hurricane was stronger than any other landfalling tropical cyclone in the United States since [[1886 Indianola hurricane|1886]].<ref name=E23>{{cite book|last1=Landsea|first1=Christopher|chapter=E23) What is the complete list of U.S. continental landfalling hurricanes?|type=FAQ|title=Frequently Asked Questions|chapter-url=https://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/E23.html|date=June 1, 2018|publisher=Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory|accessdate=July 19, 2019|version=4.11}}</ref> It was larger than average upon landfall, with a {{convert|29|mi|km|abbr=on}} [[radius of maximum wind]]. Neither the strongest winds nor lowest pressure were directly measured, and were instead extrapolated from peripheral data by the hurricane reanalysis project using [[Sea, Lake, and Overland Surge from Hurricanes|storm surge modelling]] and pressure to wind relationships. Several other researchers in the 20th century made similar analyses of the landfall, all concluding that Texas was impacted by a major hurricane.<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> Weakening ensued as the storm quickly progressed farther inland and into [[West Texas]];<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> by August&nbsp;19, the system was a weakening [[tropical depression]], opening into a [[trough (meteorology)|trough of low pressure]] the following day near the border between Texas and [[New Mexico]] within the valley of the [[Pecos River]].<ref name=\"Metadata\" /><ref name=\"MWR_WeatherMonth\" />\n\n==Preparations and impact==\n===Caribbean Sea===\n[[File:Hurricane Six surface analysis 15 Aug 1916.jpg|thumb|Surface weather analysis of the hurricane approaching Jamaica on August&nbsp;15|alt=Weather map of the storm and its isobars southeast of Jamaica]]\nCrossing the [[Lesser Antilles]] from August&nbsp;12\u201313,{{Atlantic hurricane best track}} the developing tropical cyclone produced breezy conditions; sustained winds peaked at 25&nbsp;mph (35&nbsp;km/h) on [[Antigua]] and reached low-end tropical storm intensity offshore. In [[San Fernando, Trinidad and Tobago]], a station recorded {{convert|0.42|in|mm|abbr=on}} of rain from the passing disturbance.<ref name=\"Observations\">{{cite web |title=Observations for 1916 Storm #6 |url=https://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/excelfiles_centerfix/191606.xls |website=Raw Tropical Storm/Hurricane Observations |publisher=Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |location=Miami, Florida |format=XLS |date=2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711190219/http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd//hurdat/excelfiles_centerfix/191606.xls |archive-date=July 11, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> A warning noting the likelihood of hurricane-force winds was issued for the Yucat\u00e1n Channel near [[Cuba]]'s [[Guanahacabibes Peninsula]] on August&nbsp;16,<ref name=HeadedTowardsTexas>{{cite news|title=Hurricane Headed Towards Texas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/891095/1916_texas_hurricane/?|accessdate=August 20, 2014|work=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|date=August 16, 1916|location=[[Charlotte, North Carolina]]|page=1|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140823105126/http://www.newspapers.com/clip/891095/1916_texas_hurricane/|archive-date=August 23, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> though ships resumed course to Cuban and Central American ports when the storm bypassed Cuba with no ill effects.<ref name=\"TropicalStormExpected\">{{cite news |title=Tropical Storm Expected |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34464081/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[Winfield Daily Courier]] |agency=Associated Press |issue=113 |volume=63 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=[[Winfield, Kansas]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nThe hurricane dealt a heavy blow to Jamaica when the storm passed south of the [[Crown colony]] on the night of August&nbsp;15,<ref name=\"RagingHurricane\">{{cite news |title=Raging Hurricane Struck Kingston After Six O'Clock Last Evening; Fate of Island Generally, Was Not Known Last Night |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=189 |volume=82 |date=August 16, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=1|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> killing 17&nbsp;people and leaving thousands homeless.<ref name=\"HurricanesFloodsJamaica\">{{cite web |title=History of Hurricanes and Floods in Jamaica |url=https://www.nlj.gov.jm/history-notes/History%20of%20Hurricanes%20and%20Floods%20in%20Jamaica.pdf |publisher=[[National Library of Jamaica]] |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=4 |format=PDF |date=n.d. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713094001/http://www.nlj.gov.jm/history-notes/History%20of%20Hurricanes%20and%20Floods%20in%20Jamaica.pdf |archive-date=July 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Although the U.S. Weather Bureau did not indicate a landfall,<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> reporting from [[The Gleaner (newspaper)|''The Daily Gleaner'']] suggested that the storm's calm [[eye (cyclone)|eye]] passed over [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]] and at least four of the island's southern parishes.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" /> Damage was consequently heaviest in the southern half of Jamaica, though some crops across the northern parishes were also affected;<ref name=\"RagingHurricane\" /> the overall damage toll was estimated at $10&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"TerrificStorm\">{{cite news |title=Terrific Storm in Jamaica |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34462075/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=Stevens Point Daily Journal |date=August 16, 1916 |location=[[Stevens Point, Wisconsin]] |page=6 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|10|1916|r=0}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}).{{Inflation/fn|US}} Among Jamaica's crops, banana cultivations were the most severely impacted; several communities and parishes documented a majority loss of their bananas, especially on the eastern half of the island.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" />{{rp|3}} According to the [[Jamaica\u2013United States relations|American consulate]], the entirety of Jamaica's banana crop was damaged to some extent.<ref name=JMBanana>{{cite news|title=Jamaica Banana Crop Destroyed|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/891057/1916_texas_hurricane/?|accessdate=August 20, 2014|work=The Evening Dispatch|date=August 17, 1916|location=[[Wilmington, North Carolina]]|page=1|via=Newspapers.com|volume=22|agency=Associated Press|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140823105124/http://www.newspapers.com/clip/891057/1916_texas_hurricane/|archive-date=August 23, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The eastern banana-growing belt sustained its worst losses since the [[1903 Jamaica hurricane]].<ref name=\"HeavyLossBath\">{{cite news |title=Heavy Loss Sustained Around Bath District |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=191 |volume=82 |date=August 16, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=1|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Five thousand mature banana trees were toppled before the storm's closest approach to [[Bath, Jamaica|Bath]], accounting for a near-total loss of the fruit there.<ref name=\"NewsOfStorm\">{{cite news |title=News of Storm |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=188 |volume=82 |date=August 15, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=1|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Sugar plantations also suffered greatly,<ref name=\"TerrificStorm\" /> as did coconut and cocoa trees in [[Portland Parish]].<ref name=\"GreatHurricaneJamaica\">{{cite news |title=Great Hurricane Struck and Devastated Every Part of the Island: Relief Steps by State|work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=191 |volume=82 |date=August 16, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |pages=1, 3|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>{{rp|1}} An estimated 30\u201350&nbsp;percent of the cocoa crop was damaged.<ref name=\"DamageByHurricaneJamaica\">{{cite news |title=Damage by Hurricane in Jamaica |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34463268/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Manchester Guardian]] |date=August 21, 1916 |location=[[London|London, England]] |page=6 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Winds peaked at {{convert|80|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} during the evening hours of August&nbsp;15 in [[Bowden, Jamaica|Bowden]], cutting telegraph communications and damaging many buildings and banana trees.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\">{{cite news |title=Jamaica Swept by a Hurricane on Tuesday, & Banana Industry is Crippled for Months to Come |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=190 |volume=82 |date=August 17, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |pages=1,3|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>{{rp|1}} Several hours of gusty winds downed telegraph lines and fruit trees of all varieties throughout [[Saint Thomas Parish, Jamaica|Saint Thomas Parish]].<ref name=\"HeavyDamageStThomas\">{{cite news |title=Heavy Damage in St. Thomas-Ye-Vale |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=191 |volume=82 |date=August 16, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=3|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Homes were unroofed and displaced in [[Annotto Bay]], constituting most of the property damage there.<ref name=\"GreatHurricaneJamaica\" />{{rp|3}} Heavy rainfall caused the Dry, Johnson, and [[Yallahs River|Yallahs]] rivers to rise above their banks, washing over bridges and rendering them impassable.<ref name=\"FourPaths\">{{cite news |title=First News From Four Paths |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=190 |volume=82 |date=August 17, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=3|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" />{{rp|3}}\n\nCommunications between Kingston and other parishes were cut off for 48&nbsp;hours after intense winds brought down telegraph and telephone lines,<ref name=\"RagingHurricane\" /><ref name=\"BananaCropDestroyed\">{{cite news |title=Banana Crop Destroyed by Hurricane |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34463217/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[Austin American-Statesman|The Austin American]] |issue=80 |volume=5 |location=Austin, Texas |page=2 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> making the dissemination of damage reports in Jamaica increasingly difficult.<ref name=StrikesJamaica /> The strongest sustained winds reached {{convert|72|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} in Kingston, attended by higher gusts estimated at {{convert|85|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" />{{rp|1}} One station in Kingston measured {{convert|1.56|in|mm|abbr=on}} of precipitation.<ref name=Observations /> Power was lost after falling trees struck critical electric wires, halting streetcars.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" />{{rp|1}} One woman was killed after being electrocuted by a falling electric wire.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" />{{rp|3}} The city was left in darkness overnight, forcing police to escort pedestrians off the streets. Most of the damage inflicted on property in Kingston and lower [[Saint Andrew Parish, Jamaica|Saint Andrew Parish]] was minor and confined to the most vulnerable structures.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" />{{rp|1}} Homes, fences, and signs were damaged in both residential and commercial districts of the metropolis.<ref name=\"RagingHurricane\" /> At wharves along the coast, iron-sheet roofs were torn away from sawmills.<ref name=\"RoyalMail\">{{cite news |title=Damage From Royal Mail |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=190 |volume=82 |date=August 17, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=3|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Debris littered roads, and in one case, a house was blown onto a highway.<ref name=\"RagingHurricane\" /> Rough surf generated by the strong winds sank or grounded vessels and [[Lighter (barge)|lighters]] on the shores of [[Kingston Harbour]],<ref name=StrikesJamaica>{{cite news|title=Hurricane Strikes Jamaica|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/890981/1916_texas_hurricane/?|accessdate=August 20, 2014|work=[[Star-News|The Wilmington Morning Star]]|date=August 16, 1916|location=Wilmington, North Carolina|page=1|via=Newspapers.com|volume=98|issue=147|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140823105122/http://www.newspapers.com/clip/890981/1916_texas_hurricane/|archive-date=August 23, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> with one wreck resulting in two fatalities.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" /> Substantial losses befell crops in [[Saint Catherine Parish]], including severe damage to banana and coconut trees between Kingston and [[Spanish Town]].<ref name=\"RagingHurricane\" /> In the hurricane's aftermath, the colonial government planned to assist growers in re-establishing damaged crops, and allocated [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]21,000&nbsp;to relief efforts.<ref name=\"HurricaneRuinsCrops\">{{cite news |title=Hurricane Ruins Crops in Jamaica |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34463520/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Van Nuys News ]]|issue=52 |volume=5 |date=August 25, 1916 |location=[[Van Nuys, California]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Owing to the widespread damage to banana crops, the reduced demand for rail service and subsequent cuts in revenue forced the Jamaica Railway Corporation to downsize.<ref name=\"TheRailway\">{{cite news |title=The Railway |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=193 |volume=82 |date=August 17, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=1|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n===Texas===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width: 250px; font-size: 95%; float: right;\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|-\n|+ Effects of the {{nowrap|1916 Texas hurricane}} by Texas community<ref name=\"InPath\">{{cite news |title=Corpus Christi in Path |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34477085/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=L'Observateur |issue=33 |volume=4 |date=August 26, 1916 |location=[[Reserve, Louisiana]] |page=2 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n!scope=\"col\"| Location\n!scope=\"col\"| Damage\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|[[Alice, Texas|Alice]]\n|{{ntsh|100000}} $100,000\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|[[Aransas Pass, Texas|Aransas Pass]]\n|{{ntsh|150000}} $150,000\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|[[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]]\n|{{ntsh|500000}} $500,000\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|[[Kingsville, Texas|Kingsville]]\n|{{ntsh|100000}} $100,000\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|[[Rockport, Texas|Rockport]]\n|{{ntsh|75000}} $75,000\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|[[San Diego, Texas|San Diego]]\n|{{ntsh|50000}} $50,000\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|[[Rio Grande Valley]]<br><small>(several towns)</small>\n|{{ntsh|300000}} $300,000\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|Other areas\n|{{ntsh|500000}} $500,000\n|-class=\"sortbottom\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"\n|'''Total'''\n|'''$1.8&nbsp;million'''\n|}\nGeneral information on the hurricane's location and movement for American interests was first issued by the [[United States Weather Bureau]] on the morning of August&nbsp;13, based on information from [[Saint Kitts]].<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /><ref name=\"GulfWarned\">{{cite news |title=Gulf Warned That a Storm is Coming |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/890887/ |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |work=[[Arkansas City Traveler]] |agency=Associated Press |issue=123 |volume=32 |date=August 14, 1916 |location=[[Arkansas City, Kansas]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Alerts to vessels in the path of the storm prompted 20&nbsp;steamers to anchor in [[New Orleans, Louisiana]]. Due to the storm's initially small size and the lack of data concerning it, the Weather Bureau lamented that \"the location of the center of the storm was [...] a very unsatisfactory manner\", as was the case with three other tropical cyclones monitored by the agency in August&nbsp;1916. On August&nbsp;18, as the storm neared Texas landfall, [[Tropical cyclone watches and warnings|hurricane warnings]] were first issued, advising residents between [[Cameron County, Texas|Cameron County]] and [[Calhoun County, Texas|Calhoun County]] by telegraph and telephone of the hurricane's imminent approach.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> Anticipating the hurricane's effects, prices closed 7\u20139&nbsp;points higher than the previous day at the [[New Orleans Cotton Exchange]] and advanced by 10\u201312&nbsp;points at the [[New York Cotton Exchange]].<ref name=\"CottonMarket\">{{cite news |title=Cotton Market |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34468520/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Austin Statesman |issue=227 |volume=45 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=Austin, Texas |page=6 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCottonMarket\">{{cite news |title=New York Cotton Market |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34468997/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Houston Post]] |agency=Associated Press |issue=136 |volume=31 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=11 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Galveston, Texas|Galveston]] residents evacuated for the mainland via [[interurban]] routes and special trains as seas began to rise, filling railcars to capacity;<ref name=\"CitizensLeavingGalveston\" /><ref name=\"FearingTropicHurricane\">{{cite news |title=Fearing Tropic Hurricane Galveston People Leave |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34469690/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Anniston Star|The Anniston Evening Star]] |agency=International News Service |issue=251 |volume=34 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=Anniston, Alabama |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> in total, thousands of people evacuated the insular city.<ref name=\"HurricaneHitsSouth\">{{cite news |title=Hurricane Hits South |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34469587/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=La Grande Evening Observer |issue=51 |volume=16 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=[[La Grande, Oregon]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Another set of [[Southern Pacific Transportation Company|Southern Pacific]] traincars was readied at [[Seabrook, Texas|Seabrook]] in case additional evacuations were required.<ref name=\"HoustonDistrict\">{{cite news |title=Houston District Escaped the Fury of Tropical Storm |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34473345/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=137 |volume=31 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |pages=1\u20132 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> A volunteer force with about 100&nbsp;automobiles was organized on the afternoon of August&nbsp;18 to move women and children from the vulnerable outskirts of Corpus Christi to the safer buildings of the business district, finding safe havens at banks, hotels, schools, and the city hall. However, many city residents did not take precautions in protecting their property, as conventional wisdom held that destructive storms did not affect Corpus Christi. Fearing a repeat of the [[1915 Galveston hurricane]], some visitors in Galveston headed toward Corpus Christi, only to be caught in the incoming storm.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /><ref name=\"Roth_TX\" /> The [[United States Coast Guard]] stationed at [[Brazos Island]] evacuated summer residents of [[Padre Island]] offshore [[Port Isabel, Texas|Port Isabel]]. Nearby ships were brought to the Port Isabel harbor.<ref name=\"SummerResidents\">{{cite news |title=Summer Residents Leave Padre Island |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34468114/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Austin Statesman |issue=227 |volume=45 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=Austin, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> \n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = vertical\n | width = 220\n | header = Storm damage in Corpus Christi\n | image1 = 1916MuchOfCityLostPower.jpg\n | alt1 = Utility poles downed by the hurricane\n | caption1 = Much of Corpus Christi was affected by power outages.\n | image2 = Building destroyed by the 1916 Texas Hurricane.jpg\n | alt2 = = A disheveled remains of a wooden building along the coast\n | caption2 = The waterfront was the city's hardest-hit area.\n}}\nThe coastal steamer ''Pilot Boy'' sank in the entrance to the harbor at [[Port Aransas, Texas|Port Aransas]] after being battered by the hurricane's rough seas, killing six of her crew.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> Water levels along the coast of Texas rose, with [[storm surge]] heights reaching {{convert|9.2|ft|m|abbr=on}} in Corpus Christi and {{convert|4|ft|m|abbr=on}} in Galveston.<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> Although the surge was attenuated by the hurricane's quick motion, the waves were nonetheless destructive, destroying every pier in [[Corpus Christi Bay]] and many boats.<ref name=\"Roth_TX\" /> A large segment of the Corpus Christi causeway was washed away.<ref name=\"CorpusCausewayGone\">{{cite news |title=Corpus Causeway Gone |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34474708/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Victoria Advocate|The Daily Advocate]] |issue=111 |volume=18 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=[[Victoria, Texas]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Outhouses and a dwelling at the [[Aransas Pass Light Station]] were undermined.<ref name=\"Roth_TX\" /> Driftwood was strewn across the coast of [[Laguna Madre (United States)|Laguna Madre]] for the first time in living memory.<ref name=\"Price\">{{cite book |last1=Price |first1=W. Armstrong |title=Hurricanes affecting the coast of Texas from Galveston to Rio Grande |date=March 1956 |publisher=[[Beach Erosion Board|United States Beach Erosion Board]] |location=Washington, D.C. |page=A-7 |chapter-url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.31210024971812&view=1up&seq=23 |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |chapter=Appendix A) Hurricane Chronicle|via=[[HathiTrust]]}}</ref>\n\nThe {{nowrap|Category 4 hurricane}} moved ashore near Baffin Bay at 5:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Central Time Zone|CST]] (22:00&nbsp;UTC) on August&nbsp;18,<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> roughly an hour earlier than forecast.<ref name=\"CitizensLeavingGalveston\">{{cite news |title=Citizens Leaving Galveston Hurriedly |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34469367/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Fort Wayne News]] |date=August 18, 1916 |location=[[Fort Wayne, Indiana]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Damage from the hurricane was inflicted over a wide expanse of southern Texas and maximized along the coast.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> The cities of [[Bishop, Texas|Bishop]], [[Kingsville, Texas|Kingsville]], and Corpus Christi sustained the greatest effects.<ref name=\"MWR_WeatherMonth\" /> All [[Western Union]] communication lines between [[San Antonio]] and [[Brownsville, Texas|Brownsville]] were severed by 1:30&nbsp;p.m. CST (18:30&nbsp;UTC) on August&nbsp;18, preventing the transmission of early reports from the region and accounting for $50,000&nbsp;in damage.<ref name=\"HitMorningHurricane\">{{cite news |title=Storm Strikes the Lower Gulf Coast|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47017124/|accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=The Daily Advocate |issue=36|volume=48|date=August 19, 1916 |location=[[Paris, Texas]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=\"FridayStorm\" /> At Corpus Christi, approximately 45&nbsp;mi (70&nbsp;km) northeast of the storm's point of landfall,<ref name=\"MWR_WeatherMonth\">{{cite journal |last1=Day |first1=P. C. |title=Weather and Data for the Month |journal=Monthly Weather Review |date=August 1916 |volume=44 |issue=8 |pages=486\u2013487 |doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1916)44<486:TWOTM>2.0.CO;2 |url=ftp://ftp.library.noaa.gov/docs.lib/htdocs/rescue/mwr/044/mwr-044-08-0486.pdf |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |publisher=American Meteorological Society |location=Boston, Massachusetts |bibcode=1916MWRv...44..486D}} {{open access}}</ref> winds reached at least {{convert|90|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} before the observing station's anemometer was knocked out of commission.<ref name=\"MWR_1916\" /><ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> Thunderstorms and [[squall]]s began affecting the city on the morning of August&nbsp;18, preceding the onset of hurricane-force winds that evening; light winds prevailed by August&nbsp;20. Damage was inflicted upon most buildings in the city.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> Summer cottages were destroyed and the business district incurred thousands of dollars in damage after it was entirely flooded.<ref name=\"HeavyWindWreckage\">{{cite news |title=Heavy Wind Made Wreckage of the Soldiers Camps|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34472732/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Austin Statesman |issue=228 |volume=45 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Austin, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=\"DowntownUnderWater\" /> Many [[Tamarix|salt cedar]] plants were blown down. The waterfront area endured the worst effects, including the destruction of all wharves and their ancillary buildings.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> All bathing pavilions collapsed and a [[pier#pleasure pier|pleasure pier]] was left in ruins.<ref name=\"StormLeavesRuin\">{{cite news |title=Storm Leaves Ruin in Path as Moves Inland |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34470859/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[Waxahachie Daily Light]] |issue=127 |volume=24 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=[[Waxahachie, Texas]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Much of a coastal apartment compound was reduced to rubble floating in the Corpus Christi Bay.<ref name=\"NotBadAsFeared\" />{{rp|1}} Corpus Christi also lost electricity during the storm, putting the city lights and other services out of commission.<ref name=\"SummerResorts\">{{cite news |title=Summer Resorts on Gulf Coast Hit by West Indies Storm|agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34473272/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=137 |volume=31 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Conservative estimates placed financial losses for the city between $250,000\u2013$500,000,<ref name=\"NotBadAsFeared\">{{cite news |title=Storm Not as Bad as Feared |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34476310/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=138 |volume=31 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |pages=1\u20132 |via=Newspapers.com}}\n*[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34476310/ \"Storm Not as Bad as Feared\", p. 1]\n*[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34476354/ \"Not Loss of Life Reported at Texas Coast Points\", p. 2]</ref>{{rp|1}} and three people drowned along the immediate coast.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> \n\nThe nearby communities of [[Aransas Pass, Texas|Aransas Pass]] and [[Rockport, Texas|Rockport]] sustained \"considerable\" damage.<ref name=\"DowntownUnderWater\" /> Nearly every building was affected and many were destroyed in Rockport, including the city hall.<ref name=\"RockportAransasPassAlso\">{{cite news |title=Rockport and Aransas Pass Were Also Hard Hit by Friday's Hurricane |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34496763/ |accessdate=August 2, 2019 |work=The Daily Advocate |issue=112 |volume=18 |date=August 21, 1916 |location=Victoria, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Many of Port Aransas's frame buildings, piers, and other coastal structures fell victim to the rough seas.<ref name=\"PortAndAransas\">{{cite news |title=Port and Aransas Pass Badly Damaged |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34497137/ |accessdate=August 2, 2019 |work=[[Corpus Christi Caller-Times|Corpus Christi Caller]] |issue=224 |volume=18 |date=August 22, 1916 |location=Corpus Christi, Texas |page=2 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Small shipping interests were hurt in [[Port Lavaca, Texas|Port Lavaca]], particularly the fish and oyster industry. Waterfront homes in the port city were destroyed.<ref name=\"DowntownUnderWater\">{{cite news |title=Corpus Christi Struck by Storm the Hardest; Downtown Under Water |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34474861/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Daily Advocate |issue=111 |volume=18 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Victoria, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> [[Port O'Connor]] and surrounding locales were impacted by 75-mph (120&nbsp;km/h) winds that damaged numerous homes and disloged the roof of a hotel. Strong winds also forced the sea inland, grounding boats and submerging the nearby grounds of the [[Epworth League]] in [[Seadrift, Texas|Seadrift]].<ref name=\"PortOConnorHighTide\">{{cite news |title=Port O'Connor Damaged by High Tide and Wind; Seadrift Also Suffers|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34475146/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Daily Advocate |issue=111 |volume=18 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Victoria, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> A relief train was sent from [[Austwell, Texas|Austwell]] to Port O'Connor to evacuate storm-stricken residents.<ref name=\"SixteenHourLaw\">{{cite news |title=Relief Train Up at Bloomington Because of Sixteen-Hour Law |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34475286/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Daily Advocate |issue=111 |volume=18 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Victoria, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Bay View College in [[Portland, Texas|Portland]] permanently closed following damage to its buildings.<ref name=\"BayView\">{{cite web |last1=Guthrie |first1=Keith |title=Bay View College |url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/kbb03 |website=Handbook of Texas Online |publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]] |accessdate=August 10, 2019 |location=Austin, Texas |date=June 12, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810201739/https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/kbb03 |archive-date=August 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Intense winds in Kingsville unroofed homes and businesses.<ref name=\"MaroonedPassengers\">{{cite news |title=Marooned Passengers from Storm-Swept Section Arrive |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34495625/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=138 |volume=31 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=3 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> A city garage's collapse crushed several cars beneath.<ref name=\"ImagesOfAmerica\">{{cite book |last1=Allison |first1=Pat |title=Kingsville|series=Images of America |date=2011 |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |location=[[Charleston, South Carolina]] |isbn=978-0-7385-8482-9 |pages=44\u201346 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3QBaJ720-20C&pg=PA45&lpg=PA45&dq=%221916%22+hurricane+texas+-wiki&source=bl&ots=9fOqwOUOOz&sig=ACfU3U1QscGakTzRDyV90TMtWhXqwPkQtg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjZ0_Dfr-DjAhURSK0KHUOpAxI4ChDoATALegQICBAB#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |chapter=Season of Problems|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> [[Governor of Illinois]] [[Edward Fitzsimmons Dunne]] was caught in the storm at Kingsville; he had been inspecting army camps along the Texas\u2013Mexico border in the days before they were ravaged by the storm.<ref name=\"EFDunne\">{{cite news |title=Hurricane Thrills Were Experienced by Gov. E. F. Dunne |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34475741/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=138 |volume=31 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Every house was damaged and most were destroyed in [[Riviera, Texas|Riviera]], located {{convert|15|mi|km|abbr=on}} south of Kingsville.<ref name=\"NotBadAsFeared\" />{{rp|2}} In the nearby resort town of Riviera Beach, the hurricane destroyed all businesses and amenities, as well as most of the residences, resulting in an exodus that led to the resort's demise.<ref name=\"RivieraBeach\">{{cite web |last1=Coalson |first1=George A. |title=Riviera Beach, TX |url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hrr24 |website=Handbook of Texas Online |publisher=Texas State Historical Association |accessdate=August 10, 2019 |location=Austin, Texas |date=June 15, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810201736/https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hrr24 |archive-date=August 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Farther north in Galveston, the hurricane produced 50-mph (80&nbsp;km/h) winds that destroyed two homes.<ref name=\"HurricaneHitsSouth\" /><ref name=\"TexasAgain\">{{cite news |title=Texas Again Threatened by Tropical Storm |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34468883/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Bryan-College Station Eagle|The Bryan Daily Eagle]] |agency=Associated Press |issue=197 |volume=30 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=[[Bryan, Texas]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:1916 Texas hurricane rainfall map.png|thumb|Storm rainfall totals in Texas|alt=Isohyet map of rainfall totals]]\nModerate to heavy rains spread across South Texas both ahead of the storm and to the right of the center's path. There were two foci of heavy rainfall: the first along the coast where a maximum of {{convert|6.0|in|mm|abbr=on}} was reported in [[Harlingen, Texas|Harlingen]], and a second borne of [[orographic lifting]] in the mountains of southwestern Texas.<ref name=\"NHRP3\" /> Eight towns, including Harlingen, set 24-hour rainfall records.<ref name=\"Roth_TX\" /> Crops were badly injured by the winds and rain,<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> with damage to cotton accounting for most of the financial loss.<ref name=\"Kilgore\">{{cite journal |last1=Kilgore |first1=Dan E. |title=Corpus Christi: A Quarter Century of Development, 1900\u20131925 |journal=The Southwestern Historical Quarterly |date=April 1972 |volume=75 |issue=4 |page=440 |publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]] |location=Austin, Texas|jstor=30236738 }} {{subscription required}}</ref> About one-third of the cotton crop around [[Shiner, Texas|Shiner]] was lost, and in some locations more than half of the pecans were blown off trees.<ref name=\"Cuero\">{{cite news |title=Pecans Damaged by Wind but Cotton Not Badly Hurt |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34495533/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=138 |volume=31 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=2 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=\"CottonBadlyDamaged\">{{cite news |title=Cotton Badly Damaged |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34495555/the_houston_post/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=138 |volume=31 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=2 |via=Newspapers.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802191454/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34495555/the_houston_post/ |archive-date=August 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, the storm proved beneficial for cotton harvesting in [[Victoria County, Texas|Victoria County]] by helping to clear excess foliage.<ref name=\"StormDamageCottonSmall\">{{cite news |title=Storm Damage to Cotton is Found Small |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34475379/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Daily Advocate |issue=111 |volume=18 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Victoria, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Many farm buildings and small structures were leveled in [[Beeville, Texas|Beeville]].<ref name=\"CorpusChristiBelievedSuffered\">{{cite news |title=Corpus Christi Believed to Have Suffered Heavily |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34471266/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=Waxahachie Daily Light |issue=127 |volume=24 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Waxahachie, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>  In Brownsville, plate glass windows were blown out and fences and trees were toppled.<ref name=\"IsolatedFromOutsideWorld\">{{cite news |title=Corpus Christi Isolated From Outside World |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34472035/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Marshall News Messenger|The Marshall Messenger]] |issue=284 |volume=26 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=[[Marshall, Texas]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Some militia camps were also deluged by the heavy rainfall in the Brownsville area,<ref name=\"HurricaneSantaCruz\">{{cite news |title=Hurricane |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34469891/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=Santa Cruz News |issue=94 |volume=18 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=[[Santa Cruz, California]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> destroying thousands of dollars worth of government equipment after perishable munitions were exposed to the elements.<ref name=\"StormLeavesRuin\" /> U.S. Army tents were flattened by the storm,<ref name=\"StormLeavesRuin\" /> injuring four militiamen.<ref name=\"FiveInchesOfRain\">{{cite news |title=Five Inches of Rain |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34472482/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Austin Statesman |issue=228 |volume=45 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Austin, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> All military encampments in the area were forced to be temporarily abandoned,<ref name=\"DestructiveTropicalStorm\">{{cite news |title=Destructive Tropical Storm Sweeps Texas Coast Towns |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34472944/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[El Paso Times|El Paso Morning Times]] |agency=Associated Press |location=[[El Paso, Texas]] |page=2 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> with 30,000&nbsp;people seeking refuge in public buildings in [[Mercedes, Texas|Mercedes]] and [[Mission, Texas|Mission]].<ref name=\"StormHasStruckLowerCoast\">{{cite news |title=Storm Has Struck Lower Coast |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34473144/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=137 |volume=31 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Similar damage occurred farther upstream along the [[Rio Grande Valley]] in [[Laredo, Texas|Laredo]], where the hurricane tore down small buildings and communication poles.<ref name=\"Laredo\">{{cite news |title=Telephone and Telegraph Poles and Soldier Tents Blown Down |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34495871/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=138 |volume=31 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=4 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Downed wires forced the city to shut down power for most of the municipality.<ref name=\"GulfStormSwept\">{{cite news |title=Gulf Storm Swept Corpus Christi Beach But No Loss of Life is Reported So Far |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34496296/ |accessdate=August 2, 2019 |work=[[Laredo Morning Times|Laredo Weekly Times]] |issue=10 |volume=36 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=[[Laredo, Texas]] |page=12 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Although damage was widespread, its overall magnitude along the Rio Grande remained slight.<ref name=\"OnlySlight\">{{cite news |title=Only Slight Damage Done Along the Rio Grande |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34471600/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=Waxahachie Daily Light |issue=127 |volume=24 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Waxahachie, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nSections of the [[San Antonio and Aransas Pass Railway]] and [[International\u2013Great Northern Railroad]] were put out of commission, with the former mangled and obstructed by debris.<ref name=\"CorpusChristiBelievedSuffered\" /><ref name=\"AllStateTroopsReportedSafe\">{{cite news |title=All States Troops Are Reported Safe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34471442/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=Waxahachie Daily Light |issue=127 |volume=24 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Waxahachie, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Other trains in the region were delayed by 12\u201318&nbsp;hours,<ref name=\"FiveInchesOfRain\" /> and the total cost of damage to railroads and other public utilities exceeded $300,000.<ref name=\"FridayStorm\">{{cite news |title=Railroads Were Badly Damaged by Friday's Storm |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34476037/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=138 |volume=31 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Over a thousand workers were dispatched by the afflicted railroad companies to repair the railways.<ref name=\"FridayStorm\" /> Wind damage was documented as far inland as [[Montell, Texas|Montell]] in [[Uvalde County, Texas|Uvalde County]] where frame homes were damaged and windmills collapsed.<ref name=\"MWR_WeatherMonth\" /> Strong winds and intermittent rainfall extended into the [[Austin, Texas|Austin]] area,<ref name=\"HeavyWindAustin\">{{cite news |title=Heavy Wind Felt Throughout Austin |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34472308/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=Austin American |agency=International News Service |issue=80 |volume=5 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Austin, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> while 68-mph (109&nbsp;km/h) winds swept through San Antonio.<ref name=\"MexicoGets\">{{cite news |title=Mexico Gets the Storm |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34472618/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Austin Statesman |issue=228 |volume=45 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Austin, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In total, twenty people were killed in Texas, and damage to property was estimated at $1.8&nbsp;million<ref name=\"Roth_TX\" /> (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|1.8|1916|r=0}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}).{{Inflation/fn|US}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n*[[List of Texas hurricanes (1900\u20131949)]]\n*[[Hurricane Bret (1999)]]&nbsp;\u2013 quickly intensified in the western Gulf of Mexico before making landfall on a relatively unpopulated extent of the Texas coast\n*[[1919 Florida Keys hurricane]]&nbsp;\u2013 deadly tropical cyclone that devastated areas of the Florida Keys and Texas, particularly in the Corpus Christi area\n*[[Hurricane Allen]]&nbsp;\u2013 struck South Texas after tracking across the Caribbean Sea\n*[[Hurricane Beulah]]&nbsp;\u2013 a Category&nbsp;5 hurricane which moved through the Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula before striking South Texas\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|1916 Texas hurricane}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=ORpFk-ls62oC&oi=fnd&pg=PA6&dq=1916+Corpus+Christi+hurricane+&ots=Xrr1vB4xWg&sig=MYF0y8ys2aqbcCWMYQ1hGvRAhkk#v=onepage ''Images of America: Corpus Christi'' by Scott Williams]\n*[http://www.atms.unca.edu/ibtracs/ibtracs_v04r00/index.php?name=v04r00-1916225N13305 The storm's entry in the International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship]\n\n{{1916 Atlantic hurricane season buttons}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1916 Texas Hurricane}}\n[[Category:1910s Atlantic hurricane seasons|*]]\n[[Category:Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Texas]]\n[[Category:1916 natural disasters in the United States|Texas Hurricane, 1916]]\n[[Category:1916 in Texas]]\n[[Category:1916 meteorology]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|Category 4 Atlantic hurricane in 1916}}\n{{Infobox hurricane\n| Name=1916 Texas hurricane\n| Type=hurricane\n| Year=1916\n| Basin=Atl\n| Image location=Hurricane Six surface analysis 18 Aug 1916.jpg\n| Image name=[[Surface weather analysis]] of the hurricane nearing landfall upon Texas on August&nbsp;18\n| Image alt=A map of the hurricane and its isobars in the western Gulf of Mexico\n| Formed={{start date|August&nbsp;12, 1916}}\n| Dissipated={{end date|August&nbsp;20, 1916}}\n| 1-min winds=115\n| Pressure=932\n| Pressurepost=Estimated\n| Damages=11.8\n| Fatalities=37 <small>(Jamaica: 17, Texas: 20)</small>\n| Areas={{flatlist|\n*[[Lesser Antilles]]\n*[[Jamaica]]\n*[[Cayman Islands]]\n*[[Mexico]]\n*[[Texas]]\n}}\n| Hurricane season=[[1916 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n}}\nThe '''1916 Texas hurricane''' was an intense and quick-moving [[tropical cyclone]] that caused widespread damage in [[Jamaica]] and [[South Texas]] in August&nbsp;1916. A [[List of Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes|Category&nbsp;4 hurricane]] upon [[landfall (meteorology)|landfall]] in Texas, it was the strongest tropical cyclone to strike the United States in three decades. Throughout its eight-day trek across the [[Caribbean Sea]] and [[Gulf of Mexico]], the hurricane caused 37&nbsp;fatalities and inflicted $11.8&nbsp;million in damage.{{#tag:ref|All monetary values are in 1916&nbsp;[[United States dollar]]s unless otherwise noted.|group=nb}}\n\nWeather observations were limited for most of the storm's history, so much of its evolution has been inferred from scant data analyzed by the [[Atlantic hurricane reanalysis project]] in 2008. The precursor disturbance organized into a small [[tropical storm]] by August&nbsp;12, shortly before crossing the [[Lesser Antilles]] into the Caribbean Sea. The storm skirted the southern coast of Jamaica as a hurricane on August&nbsp;15, killing 17&nbsp;people. No banana plantation was left unscathed by the hours-long onslaught of strong winds. Coconut and cocoa trees also sustained severe losses. The southern [[Parishes of Jamaica|parishes]] saw the severest effects, incurring extensive damage to crops and buildings; damage in Jamaica amounted to $10&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|10|1916|r=0}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}). The storm then traversed the [[Yucat\u00e1n Channel]] into the Gulf of Mexico and intensified further into the equivalent of a [[major hurricane]] on the modern-day [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale]].{{#tag:ref|A major hurricane is a storm that ranks as Category&nbsp;3 or higher on the [[Saffir\u2013Simpson hurricane scale]].<ref name=BASIC>{{cite book|last1=Goldenburg|first1=Stan|chapter=A3) What is a super-typhoon? What is a major hurricane? What is an intense hurricane?|type=FAQ|title=Frequently Asked Questions|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/tcfaqHED.html|chapterurl=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/A3.html|date=June 1, 2018|publisher=[[Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory]]|accessdate=August 2, 2019|version=4.11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060615212545/http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/tcfaqHED.html|archive-date=June 15, 2006|url-status=live}}</ref>|group=\"nb\"}}\n\nOn the evening of August&nbsp;16, the hurricane struck South Texas near [[Baffin Bay, Texas|Baffin Bay]] with [[maximum sustained wind|winds]] of 130&nbsp;mph (215&nbsp;km/h). Buildings were razed at many coastal cities, with the worst impacts felt in [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]] and surrounding communities. Beachfront structures were destroyed by a {{convert|9.2|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=on}} [[storm surge]]. Strong gusts and heavy rainfall spread farther inland across mainly rural sectors of South Texas, damaging towns and their outlying agricultural districts alike. Railroads and other public utilities were disrupted across the region, with widespread [[power outage]]s. Eight locations set 24-hour rainfall records; among them was [[Harlingen, Texas|Harlingen]], which recorded the storm's rainfall maximum with {{cvt|6|in|mm}} of precipitation. The deluge wrought havoc on military camps along the U.S.-[[Mexico]] border, forcing 30,000&nbsp;garrisoned militiamen to evacuate. Aggregate property damage across Texas reached $1.8&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|1.8|1916|r=0}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}), and 20&nbsp;people lost their lives. The hurricane quickly weakened over southwestern Texas and dissipated near [[New Mexico]] by August&nbsp;20.\n\n==Meteorological history==\n{{storm path|1916 Atlantic hurricane 6 track.png|alt=Map showing the track of the storm, beginning east of the Lesser Antilles and ending over Texas}}\nAccording to the [[National Weather Service|U.S. Weather Bureau]], the {{nowrap|1916 Texas hurricane}} \"followed an average course for the type of August hurricanes that passes {{sic}} through the [[Yucat\u00e1n Channel]]\",<ref name=\"MWR_1916\">{{cite journal |last1=Weightman |first1=Richard Hanson |title=Hurricanes of 1916 and Notes on Hurricanes of 1912\u20131915 |journal=[[Monthly Weather Review]] |date=December 1916 |volume=44 |issue=12 |page=686 |doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1916)44<686:HOANOH>2.0.CO;2 |url=ftp://ftp.library.noaa.gov/docs.lib/htdocs/rescue/mwr/044/mwr-044-12-0686.pdf |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |publisher=[[American Meteorological Society]] |location=[[Boston, Massachusetts]] |bibcode=1916MWRv...44..686W}} {{open access}}</ref> but maintained an unusually brisk forward speed throughout its life.<ref name=\"Roth_TX\">{{cite web |last1=Roth |first1=David M. |title=Texas Hurricane History |url=https://origin.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/research/txhur.pdf |publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |location=[[Camp Springs, Maryland]] |pages=36\u201337 |date=February 3, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721231821/http://origin.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/research/txhur.pdf |archive-date=July 21, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> A possible precursor disturbance may have originated as early as August&nbsp;8 near Africa, but observations were inconclusive in determining the [[tropical cyclogenesis|formation]] of a [[tropical cyclone]].<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> The hurricane was first definitively detected as a [[tropical storm]] east of [[Barbados]] on August&nbsp;12,<ref name=\"MWR_Atlantic\">{{cite journal |title=Weather Conditions Over the North Atlantic Ocean During August, 1916 |journal=Monthly Weather Review |date=August 1917 |volume=45 |issue=8 |pages=429\u2013431 |doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1917)45<429:WCOTNA>2.0.CO;2 |url=ftp://ftp.library.noaa.gov/docs.lib/htdocs/rescue/mwr/045/mwr-045-08-0429.pdf |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |publisher=American Meteorological Society |location=Boston, Massachusetts |bibcode=1917MWRv...45..429.}} {{open access}}</ref> based on a 40-mph (64&nbsp;km/h) wind measurement from a nearby ship.<ref name=\"Metadata\">{{cite web|last1=Landsea|first1=Chris|last2=Anderson|first2=Craig|last3=Bredemeyer|first3=William|last4=Carrasco|first4=Cristina|last5=Charles|first5=Noel|last6=Chenoweth|first6=Michael|last7=Clark|first7=Gil|last8=Delgado|first8=Sandy|last9=Dunion|first9=Jason|last10=Ellis|first10=Ryan|last11=Fernandez-Partagas|first11=Jose|last12=Feuer|first12=Steve|last13=Gamanche|first13=John|last14=Glenn|first14=David|last15=Hagen|first15=Andrew|last16=Hufstetler|first16=Lyle|last17=Mock|first17=Cary|last18=Neumann|first18=Charlie|last19=Perez Suarez|first19=Ramon|last20=Prieto|first20=Ricardo|last21=Sanchez-Sesma|first21=Jorge|last22=Santiago|first22=Adrian|last23=Sims|first23=Jamese|last24=Thomas|first24=Donna|last25=Lenworth|first25=Woolcock|last26=Zimmer|first26=Mark|authorlink1=Christopher Landsea|title=Documentation of Atlantic Tropical Cyclones Changes in HURDAT|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/metadata_master.html|website=Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=July 31, 2019|date=May 2015|location=[[Miami, Florida]]|type=Metadata|at=1916/06 - 2008 Revision|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604063810/http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/metadata_master.html|archive-date=June 4, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> There were no additional observations of similarly gusty winds or low [[barometric pressure|air pressures]] over the next three days while the system traced out the southern periphery of the [[Azores High]] westward into the eastern [[Caribbean Sea]].{{Atlantic hurricane best track}}<ref name=\"Metadata\" /><ref name=\"NHRP3\">{{cite report |last1=Schoner |first1=R. W. |last2=Molansky |first2=S. |title=Rainfall Associated with Hurricanes (And Other Tropical Disturbances) |chapter=Storms in the South Atlantic Coastal Region |issue=3 |url=https://www.aoml.noaa.gov/general/lib/TM/NHRP_03_1956.pdf |publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |accessdate=June 23, 2019 |location=[[Washington, D.C.]] |page=100 |format=PDF |date=July 1956 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521100141/http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/general/lib/TM/NHRP_03_1956.pdf |archivedate=May 21, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Steady intensification was inferred during this period by the [[Atlantic hurricane reanalysis project]] in 2008,<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> which estimated that the storm strengthened into a hurricane on August&nbsp;15 while located south of [[Hispaniola]].{{Atlantic hurricane best track}}<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> Concurrently, the hurricane curved slightly towards the west-northwest, bringing it just south of [[Jamaica]] that day with winds of 85&nbsp;mph (135&nbsp;km/h).<ref name=\"Metadata\" /><ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\">{{cite journal |last1=Henry |first1=Alfred J. |title=Forecasts and Warnings |journal=Monthly Weather Review |date=August 1916 |volume=44 |issue=8 |pages=461\u2013463 |doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1916)44<461:FAWFA>2.0.CO;2 |url=ftp://ftp.library.noaa.gov/docs.lib/htdocs/rescue/mwr/044/mwr-044-08-0461.pdf |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |publisher=American Meteorological Society |location=Boston, Massachusetts |bibcode=1916MWRv...44..461H}} {{open access}}</ref> Near the [[Cayman Islands]], a vessel recorded 55-mph (89&nbsp;km/h) winds, ultimately proving to be the strongest offshore winds sampled in connection with the cyclone.<ref name=\"MWR_Atlantic\" /> Continuing to intensify, the hurricane emerged into the [[Gulf of Mexico]] through the Yucat\u00e1n Channel on the morning of August&nbsp;17.<ref name=\"Metadata\" /><ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" />\n\nWeather observations remained scant in the open waters of the Gulf of Mexico, with the strongest observed winds limited to marginal gales. The storm reached [[major hurricane]] intensity just north of the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]] on August&nbsp;17, and reports on the developing hurricane proliferated as the storm neared the [[Texas]] coast.<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> By August&nbsp;18, the hurricane reached [[List of Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes|{{nowrap|Category 4 intensity}}]] in the western Gulf of Mexico;{{Atlantic hurricane best track}} the first [[rainband|outer band]]s began reaching the coast near [[Corpus Christi, Texas]], early that morning.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> During the evening hours, the center of the hurricane made [[landfall (meteorology)|landfall]] near [[Baffin Bay, Texas]], with [[maximum sustained wind]]s of {{convert|130|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} and a central pressure of 932&nbsp;[[bar (unit)|mbar]] ([[pascal (unit)|hPa]]; 27.52&nbsp;[[inches of mercury|inHg]]).<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> These parameters made it the strongest hurricane of the [[1916 Atlantic hurricane season]].{{Atlantic hurricane best track}} In terms of pressure, the 1916&nbsp;Texas hurricane was stronger than any other landfalling tropical cyclone in the United States since [[1886 Indianola hurricane|1886]].<ref name=E23>{{cite book|last1=Landsea|first1=Christopher|chapter=E23) What is the complete list of U.S. continental landfalling hurricanes?|type=FAQ|title=Frequently Asked Questions|chapter-url=https://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/E23.html|date=June 1, 2018|publisher=Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory|accessdate=July 19, 2019|version=4.11}}</ref> At landfall, the storm was larger than average, with a {{convert|29|mi|km|abbr=on}} [[radius of maximum wind]]. Neither the strongest winds nor lowest pressure were directly measured, and were instead extrapolated from peripheral data by the hurricane reanalysis project using [[Sea, Lake, and Overland Surge from Hurricanes|storm surge modelling]] and pressure to wind relationships. Several other researchers in the 20th century made similar analyses of the landfall, all concluding that Texas was impacted by a major hurricane.<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> Weakening ensued as the storm quickly progressed farther inland and into [[West Texas]];<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> by August&nbsp;19, the system was a weakening [[tropical depression]], opening into a [[trough (meteorology)|trough of low pressure]] the following day near the border between Texas and [[New Mexico]] within the valley of the [[Pecos River]].<ref name=\"Metadata\" /><ref name=\"MWR_WeatherMonth\" />\n\n==Preparations and impact==\n===Caribbean Sea===\n[[File:Hurricane Six surface analysis 15 Aug 1916.jpg|thumb|Surface weather analysis of the hurricane approaching Jamaica on August&nbsp;15|alt=Weather map of the storm and its isobars southeast of Jamaica]]\nCrossing the [[Lesser Antilles]] from August&nbsp;12\u201313,{{Atlantic hurricane best track}} the developing tropical cyclone produced breezy conditions; sustained winds peaked at 25&nbsp;mph (35&nbsp;km/h) on [[Antigua]] and reached low-end tropical storm intensity offshore. In [[San Fernando, Trinidad and Tobago]], a station recorded {{convert|0.42|in|mm|abbr=on}} of rain from the passing disturbance.<ref name=\"Observations\">{{cite web |title=Observations for 1916 Storm #6 |url=https://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/excelfiles_centerfix/191606.xls |website=Raw Tropical Storm/Hurricane Observations |publisher=Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |location=Miami, Florida |format=XLS |date=2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711190219/http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd//hurdat/excelfiles_centerfix/191606.xls |archive-date=July 11, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> A warning noting the likelihood of hurricane-force winds was issued for the Yucat\u00e1n Channel near [[Cuba]]'s [[Guanahacabibes Peninsula]] on August&nbsp;16,<ref name=HeadedTowardsTexas>{{cite news|title=Hurricane Headed Towards Texas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/891095/1916_texas_hurricane/?|accessdate=August 20, 2014|work=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|date=August 16, 1916|location=[[Charlotte, North Carolina]]|page=1|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140823105126/http://www.newspapers.com/clip/891095/1916_texas_hurricane/|archive-date=August 23, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> though ships resumed course to Cuban and Central American ports when the storm bypassed Cuba with no ill effects.<ref name=\"TropicalStormExpected\">{{cite news |title=Tropical Storm Expected |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34464081/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[Winfield Daily Courier]] |agency=Associated Press |issue=113 |volume=63 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=[[Winfield, Kansas]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nThe hurricane dealt a heavy blow to Jamaica when the storm passed south of the [[Crown colony]] on the night of August&nbsp;15,<ref name=\"RagingHurricane\">{{cite news |title=Raging Hurricane Struck Kingston After Six O'Clock Last Evening; Fate of Island Generally, Was Not Known Last Night |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=189 |volume=82 |date=August 16, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=1|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> killing 17&nbsp;people and leaving thousands homeless.<ref name=\"HurricanesFloodsJamaica\">{{cite web |title=History of Hurricanes and Floods in Jamaica |url=https://www.nlj.gov.jm/history-notes/History%20of%20Hurricanes%20and%20Floods%20in%20Jamaica.pdf |publisher=[[National Library of Jamaica]] |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=4 |format=PDF |date=n.d. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713094001/http://www.nlj.gov.jm/history-notes/History%20of%20Hurricanes%20and%20Floods%20in%20Jamaica.pdf |archive-date=July 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Although the U.S. Weather Bureau did not indicate a landfall,<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> reporting from [[The Gleaner (newspaper)|''The Daily Gleaner'']] suggested that the storm's calm [[eye (cyclone)|eye]] passed over [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]] and at least four of the island's southern parishes.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" /> Damage was consequently heaviest in the southern half of Jamaica, though some crops across the northern parishes were also affected;<ref name=\"RagingHurricane\" /> the overall damage toll was estimated at $10&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"TerrificStorm\">{{cite news |title=Terrific Storm in Jamaica |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34462075/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=Stevens Point Daily Journal |date=August 16, 1916 |location=[[Stevens Point, Wisconsin]] |page=6 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|10|1916|r=0}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}).{{Inflation/fn|US}} Among Jamaica's crops, banana cultivations were the most severely impacted; several communities and parishes documented a majority loss of their bananas, especially on the eastern half of the island.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" />{{rp|3}} According to the [[Jamaica\u2013United States relations|American consulate]], the entirety of Jamaica's banana crop was damaged to some extent.<ref name=JMBanana>{{cite news|title=Jamaica Banana Crop Destroyed|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/891057/1916_texas_hurricane/?|accessdate=August 20, 2014|work=The Evening Dispatch|date=August 17, 1916|location=[[Wilmington, North Carolina]]|page=1|via=Newspapers.com|volume=22|agency=Associated Press|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140823105124/http://www.newspapers.com/clip/891057/1916_texas_hurricane/|archive-date=August 23, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The eastern banana-growing belt sustained its worst losses since the [[1903 Jamaica hurricane]].<ref name=\"HeavyLossBath\">{{cite news |title=Heavy Loss Sustained Around Bath District |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=191 |volume=82 |date=August 16, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=1|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Five thousand mature banana trees were toppled before the storm's closest approach to [[Bath, Jamaica|Bath]], accounting for a near-total loss of the fruit there.<ref name=\"NewsOfStorm\">{{cite news |title=News of Storm |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=188 |volume=82 |date=August 15, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=1|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Sugar plantations also suffered greatly,<ref name=\"TerrificStorm\" /> as did coconut and cocoa trees in [[Portland Parish]].<ref name=\"GreatHurricaneJamaica\">{{cite news |title=Great Hurricane Struck and Devastated Every Part of the Island: Relief Steps by State|work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=191 |volume=82 |date=August 16, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |pages=1, 3|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>{{rp|1}} An estimated 30\u201350&nbsp;percent of the cocoa crop was damaged.<ref name=\"DamageByHurricaneJamaica\">{{cite news |title=Damage by Hurricane in Jamaica |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34463268/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Manchester Guardian]] |date=August 21, 1916 |location=[[London|London, England]] |page=6 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Winds peaked at {{convert|80|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} during the evening hours of August&nbsp;15 in [[Bowden, Jamaica|Bowden]], cutting telegraph communications and damaging many buildings and banana trees.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\">{{cite news |title=Jamaica Swept by a Hurricane on Tuesday, & Banana Industry is Crippled for Months to Come |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=190 |volume=82 |date=August 17, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |pages=1,3|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>{{rp|1}} Several hours of gusty winds downed telegraph lines and fruit trees of all varieties throughout [[Saint Thomas Parish, Jamaica|Saint Thomas Parish]].<ref name=\"HeavyDamageStThomas\">{{cite news |title=Heavy Damage in St. Thomas-Ye-Vale |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=191 |volume=82 |date=August 16, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=3|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Homes were unroofed and displaced in [[Annotto Bay]], constituting most of the property damage there.<ref name=\"GreatHurricaneJamaica\" />{{rp|3}} Heavy rainfall caused the Dry, Johnson, and [[Yallahs River|Yallahs]] rivers to rise above their banks, washing over bridges and rendering them impassable.<ref name=\"FourPaths\">{{cite news |title=First News From Four Paths |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=190 |volume=82 |date=August 17, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=3|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" />{{rp|3}}\n\nCommunications between Kingston and other parishes were cut off for 48&nbsp;hours after intense winds brought down telegraph and telephone lines,<ref name=\"RagingHurricane\" /><ref name=\"BananaCropDestroyed\">{{cite news |title=Banana Crop Destroyed by Hurricane |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34463217/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[Austin American-Statesman|The Austin American]] |issue=80 |volume=5 |location=Austin, Texas |page=2 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> making the dissemination of damage reports in Jamaica increasingly difficult.<ref name=StrikesJamaica /> The strongest sustained winds reached {{convert|72|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} in Kingston, attended by higher gusts estimated at {{convert|85|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" />{{rp|1}} One station in Kingston measured {{convert|1.56|in|mm|abbr=on}} of precipitation.<ref name=Observations /> Power was lost after falling trees struck critical electric wires, halting streetcars.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" />{{rp|1}} One woman was killed after being electrocuted by a falling electric wire.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" />{{rp|3}} The city was left in darkness overnight, forcing police to escort pedestrians off the streets. Most of the damage inflicted on property in Kingston and lower [[Saint Andrew Parish, Jamaica|Saint Andrew Parish]] was minor and confined to the most vulnerable structures.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" />{{rp|1}} Homes, fences, and signs were damaged in both residential and commercial districts of the metropolis.<ref name=\"RagingHurricane\" /> At wharves along the coast, iron-sheet roofs were torn away from sawmills.<ref name=\"RoyalMail\">{{cite news |title=Damage From Royal Mail |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=190 |volume=82 |date=August 17, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=3|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Debris littered roads, and in one case, a house was blown onto a highway.<ref name=\"RagingHurricane\" /> Rough surf generated by the strong winds sank or grounded vessels and [[Lighter (barge)|lighters]] on the shores of [[Kingston Harbour]],<ref name=StrikesJamaica>{{cite news|title=Hurricane Strikes Jamaica|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/890981/1916_texas_hurricane/?|accessdate=August 20, 2014|work=[[Star-News|The Wilmington Morning Star]]|date=August 16, 1916|location=Wilmington, North Carolina|page=1|via=Newspapers.com|volume=98|issue=147|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140823105122/http://www.newspapers.com/clip/890981/1916_texas_hurricane/|archive-date=August 23, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> with one wreck resulting in two fatalities.<ref name=\"JamaicaSwept\" /> Substantial losses befell crops in [[Saint Catherine Parish]], including severe damage to banana and coconut trees between Kingston and [[Spanish Town]].<ref name=\"RagingHurricane\" /> In the hurricane's aftermath, the colonial government planned to assist growers in re-establishing damaged crops, and allocated [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]21,000&nbsp;to relief efforts.<ref name=\"HurricaneRuinsCrops\">{{cite news |title=Hurricane Ruins Crops in Jamaica |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34463520/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Van Nuys News ]]|issue=52 |volume=5 |date=August 25, 1916 |location=[[Van Nuys, California]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Owing to the widespread damage to banana crops, the reduced demand for rail service and subsequent cuts in revenue forced the Jamaica Railway Corporation to downsize.<ref name=\"TheRailway\">{{cite news |title=The Railway |work=The Daily Gleaner |issue=193 |volume=82 |date=August 17, 1916 |location=Kingston, Jamaica |page=1|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n===Texas===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width: 250px; font-size: 95%; float: right;\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|-\n|+ Effects of the {{nowrap|1916 Texas hurricane}} by Texas community<ref name=\"InPath\">{{cite news |title=Corpus Christi in Path |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34477085/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=L'Observateur |issue=33 |volume=4 |date=August 26, 1916 |location=[[Reserve, Louisiana]] |page=2 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n!scope=\"col\"| Location\n!scope=\"col\"| Damage\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|[[Alice, Texas|Alice]]\n|{{ntsh|100000}} $100,000\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|[[Aransas Pass, Texas|Aransas Pass]]\n|{{ntsh|150000}} $150,000\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|[[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]]\n|{{ntsh|500000}} $500,000\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|[[Kingsville, Texas|Kingsville]]\n|{{ntsh|100000}} $100,000\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|[[Rockport, Texas|Rockport]]\n|{{ntsh|75000}} $75,000\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|[[San Diego, Texas|San Diego]]\n|{{ntsh|50000}} $50,000\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|[[Rio Grande Valley]]<br><small>(several towns)</small>\n|{{ntsh|300000}} $300,000\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"|Other areas\n|{{ntsh|500000}} $500,000\n|-class=\"sortbottom\" bgcolor=\"#e6e9ff\"\n|'''Total'''\n|'''$1.8&nbsp;million'''\n|}\nGeneral information on the hurricane's location and movement for American interests was first issued by the [[United States Weather Bureau]] on the morning of August&nbsp;13, based on information from [[Saint Kitts]].<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /><ref name=\"GulfWarned\">{{cite news |title=Gulf Warned That a Storm is Coming |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/890887/ |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |work=[[Arkansas City Traveler]] |agency=Associated Press |issue=123 |volume=32 |date=August 14, 1916 |location=[[Arkansas City, Kansas]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Alerts to vessels in the path of the storm prompted 20&nbsp;steamers to anchor in [[New Orleans, Louisiana]]. Due to the storm's initially small size and the lack of data concerning it, the Weather Bureau lamented that \"the location of the center of the storm was [...] a very unsatisfactory manner\", as was the case with three other tropical cyclones monitored by the agency in August&nbsp;1916. On August&nbsp;18, as the storm neared Texas landfall, [[Tropical cyclone watches and warnings|hurricane warnings]] were first issued, advising residents between [[Cameron County, Texas|Cameron County]] and [[Calhoun County, Texas|Calhoun County]] by telegraph and telephone of the hurricane's imminent approach.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> Anticipating the hurricane's effects, prices closed 7\u20139&nbsp;points higher than the previous day at the [[New Orleans Cotton Exchange]] and advanced by 10\u201312&nbsp;points at the [[New York Cotton Exchange]].<ref name=\"CottonMarket\">{{cite news |title=Cotton Market |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34468520/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Austin Statesman |issue=227 |volume=45 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=Austin, Texas |page=6 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCottonMarket\">{{cite news |title=New York Cotton Market |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34468997/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Houston Post]] |agency=Associated Press |issue=136 |volume=31 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=11 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Galveston, Texas|Galveston]] residents evacuated for the mainland via [[interurban]] routes and special trains as seas began to rise, filling railcars to capacity;<ref name=\"CitizensLeavingGalveston\" /><ref name=\"FearingTropicHurricane\">{{cite news |title=Fearing Tropic Hurricane Galveston People Leave |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34469690/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Anniston Star|The Anniston Evening Star]] |agency=International News Service |issue=251 |volume=34 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=Anniston, Alabama |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> in total, thousands of people evacuated the insular city.<ref name=\"HurricaneHitsSouth\">{{cite news |title=Hurricane Hits South |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34469587/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=La Grande Evening Observer |issue=51 |volume=16 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=[[La Grande, Oregon]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Another set of [[Southern Pacific Transportation Company|Southern Pacific]] traincars was readied at [[Seabrook, Texas|Seabrook]] in case additional evacuations were required.<ref name=\"HoustonDistrict\">{{cite news |title=Houston District Escaped the Fury of Tropical Storm |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34473345/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=137 |volume=31 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |pages=1\u20132 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> A volunteer force with about 100&nbsp;automobiles was organized on the afternoon of August&nbsp;18 to move women and children from the vulnerable outskirts of Corpus Christi to the safer buildings of the business district, finding safe havens at banks, hotels, schools, and the city hall. However, many city residents did not take precautions in protecting their property, as conventional wisdom held that destructive storms did not affect Corpus Christi. Fearing a repeat of the [[1915 Galveston hurricane]], some visitors in Galveston headed toward Corpus Christi, only to be caught in the incoming storm.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /><ref name=\"Roth_TX\" /> The [[United States Coast Guard]] stationed at [[Brazos Island]] evacuated summer residents of [[Padre Island]] offshore [[Port Isabel, Texas|Port Isabel]]. Nearby ships were brought to the Port Isabel harbor.<ref name=\"SummerResidents\">{{cite news |title=Summer Residents Leave Padre Island |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34468114/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Austin Statesman |issue=227 |volume=45 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=Austin, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> \n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = vertical\n | width = 220\n | header = Storm damage in Corpus Christi\n | image1 = 1916MuchOfCityLostPower.jpg\n | alt1 = Utility poles downed by the hurricane\n | caption1 = Much of Corpus Christi was affected by power outages.\n | image2 = Building destroyed by the 1916 Texas Hurricane.jpg\n | alt2 = = A disheveled remains of a wooden building along the coast\n | caption2 = The waterfront was the city's hardest-hit area.\n}}\nThe coastal steamer ''Pilot Boy'' sank in the entrance to the harbor at [[Port Aransas, Texas|Port Aransas]] after being battered by the hurricane's rough seas, killing six of her crew.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> Water levels along the coast of Texas rose, with [[storm surge]] heights reaching {{convert|9.2|ft|m|abbr=on}} in Corpus Christi and {{convert|4|ft|m|abbr=on}} in Galveston.<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> Although the surge was attenuated by the hurricane's quick motion, the waves were nonetheless destructive, destroying every pier in [[Corpus Christi Bay]] and many boats.<ref name=\"Roth_TX\" /> A large segment of the Corpus Christi causeway was washed away.<ref name=\"CorpusCausewayGone\">{{cite news |title=Corpus Causeway Gone |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34474708/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Victoria Advocate|The Daily Advocate]] |issue=111 |volume=18 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=[[Victoria, Texas]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Outhouses and a dwelling at the [[Aransas Pass Light Station]] were undermined.<ref name=\"Roth_TX\" /> Driftwood was strewn across the coast of [[Laguna Madre (United States)|Laguna Madre]] for the first time in living memory.<ref name=\"Price\">{{cite book |last1=Price |first1=W. Armstrong |title=Hurricanes affecting the coast of Texas from Galveston to Rio Grande |date=March 1956 |publisher=[[Beach Erosion Board|United States Beach Erosion Board]] |location=Washington, D.C. |page=A-7 |chapter-url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.31210024971812&view=1up&seq=23 |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |chapter=Appendix A) Hurricane Chronicle|via=[[HathiTrust]]}}</ref>\n\nThe {{nowrap|Category 4 hurricane}} moved ashore near Baffin Bay at 5:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Central Time Zone|CST]] (22:00&nbsp;UTC) on August&nbsp;18,<ref name=\"Metadata\" /> roughly an hour earlier than forecast.<ref name=\"CitizensLeavingGalveston\">{{cite news |title=Citizens Leaving Galveston Hurriedly |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34469367/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Fort Wayne News]] |date=August 18, 1916 |location=[[Fort Wayne, Indiana]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Damage from the hurricane was inflicted over a wide expanse of southern Texas and maximized along the coast.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> The cities of [[Bishop, Texas|Bishop]], [[Kingsville, Texas|Kingsville]], and Corpus Christi sustained the greatest effects.<ref name=\"MWR_WeatherMonth\" /> All [[Western Union]] communication lines between [[San Antonio]] and [[Brownsville, Texas|Brownsville]] were severed by 1:30&nbsp;p.m. CST (18:30&nbsp;UTC) on August&nbsp;18, preventing the transmission of early reports from the region and accounting for $50,000&nbsp;in damage.<ref name=\"HitMorningHurricane\">{{cite news |title=Storm Strikes the Lower Gulf Coast|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47017124/|accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=The Daily Advocate |issue=36|volume=48|date=August 19, 1916 |location=[[Paris, Texas]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=\"FridayStorm\" /> At Corpus Christi, approximately 45&nbsp;mi (70&nbsp;km) northeast of the storm's point of landfall,<ref name=\"MWR_WeatherMonth\">{{cite journal |last1=Day |first1=P. C. |title=Weather and Data for the Month |journal=Monthly Weather Review |date=August 1916 |volume=44 |issue=8 |pages=486\u2013487 |doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1916)44<486:TWOTM>2.0.CO;2 |url=ftp://ftp.library.noaa.gov/docs.lib/htdocs/rescue/mwr/044/mwr-044-08-0486.pdf |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |publisher=American Meteorological Society |location=Boston, Massachusetts |bibcode=1916MWRv...44..486D}} {{open access}}</ref> winds reached at least {{convert|90|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} before the observing station's anemometer was knocked out of commission.<ref name=\"MWR_1916\" /><ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> Thunderstorms and [[squall]]s began affecting the city on the morning of August&nbsp;18, preceding the onset of hurricane-force winds that evening; light winds prevailed by August&nbsp;20. Damage was inflicted upon most buildings in the city.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> Summer cottages were destroyed and the business district incurred thousands of dollars in damage after it was entirely flooded.<ref name=\"HeavyWindWreckage\">{{cite news |title=Heavy Wind Made Wreckage of the Soldiers Camps|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34472732/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Austin Statesman |issue=228 |volume=45 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Austin, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=\"DowntownUnderWater\" /> Many [[Tamarix|salt cedar]] plants were blown down. The waterfront area endured the worst effects, including the destruction of all wharves and their ancillary buildings.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> All bathing pavilions collapsed and a [[pier#pleasure pier|pleasure pier]] was left in ruins.<ref name=\"StormLeavesRuin\">{{cite news |title=Storm Leaves Ruin in Path as Moves Inland |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34470859/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[Waxahachie Daily Light]] |issue=127 |volume=24 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=[[Waxahachie, Texas]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Much of a coastal apartment compound was reduced to rubble floating in the Corpus Christi Bay.<ref name=\"NotBadAsFeared\" />{{rp|1}} Corpus Christi also lost electricity during the storm, putting the city lights and other services out of commission.<ref name=\"SummerResorts\">{{cite news |title=Summer Resorts on Gulf Coast Hit by West Indies Storm|agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34473272/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=137 |volume=31 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Conservative estimates placed financial losses for the city between $250,000\u2013$500,000,<ref name=\"NotBadAsFeared\">{{cite news |title=Storm Not as Bad as Feared |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34476310/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=138 |volume=31 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |pages=1\u20132 |via=Newspapers.com}}\n*[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34476310/ \"Storm Not as Bad as Feared\", p. 1]\n*[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34476354/ \"Not Loss of Life Reported at Texas Coast Points\", p. 2]</ref>{{rp|1}} and three people drowned along the immediate coast.<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> \n\nThe nearby communities of [[Aransas Pass, Texas|Aransas Pass]] and [[Rockport, Texas|Rockport]] sustained \"considerable\" damage.<ref name=\"DowntownUnderWater\" /> Nearly every building was affected and many were destroyed in Rockport, including the city hall.<ref name=\"RockportAransasPassAlso\">{{cite news |title=Rockport and Aransas Pass Were Also Hard Hit by Friday's Hurricane |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34496763/ |accessdate=August 2, 2019 |work=The Daily Advocate |issue=112 |volume=18 |date=August 21, 1916 |location=Victoria, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Many of Port Aransas's frame buildings, piers, and other coastal structures fell victim to the rough seas.<ref name=\"PortAndAransas\">{{cite news |title=Port and Aransas Pass Badly Damaged |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34497137/ |accessdate=August 2, 2019 |work=[[Corpus Christi Caller-Times|Corpus Christi Caller]] |issue=224 |volume=18 |date=August 22, 1916 |location=Corpus Christi, Texas |page=2 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Small shipping interests were hurt in [[Port Lavaca, Texas|Port Lavaca]], particularly the fish and oyster industry. Waterfront homes in the port city were destroyed.<ref name=\"DowntownUnderWater\">{{cite news |title=Corpus Christi Struck by Storm the Hardest; Downtown Under Water |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34474861/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Daily Advocate |issue=111 |volume=18 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Victoria, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> [[Port O'Connor]] and surrounding locales were impacted by 75-mph (120&nbsp;km/h) winds that damaged numerous homes and disloged the roof of a hotel. Strong winds also forced the sea inland, grounding boats and submerging the nearby grounds of the [[Epworth League]] in [[Seadrift, Texas|Seadrift]].<ref name=\"PortOConnorHighTide\">{{cite news |title=Port O'Connor Damaged by High Tide and Wind; Seadrift Also Suffers|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34475146/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Daily Advocate |issue=111 |volume=18 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Victoria, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> A relief train was sent from [[Austwell, Texas|Austwell]] to Port O'Connor to evacuate storm-stricken residents.<ref name=\"SixteenHourLaw\">{{cite news |title=Relief Train Up at Bloomington Because of Sixteen-Hour Law |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34475286/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Daily Advocate |issue=111 |volume=18 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Victoria, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Bay View College in [[Portland, Texas|Portland]] permanently closed following damage to its buildings.<ref name=\"BayView\">{{cite web |last1=Guthrie |first1=Keith |title=Bay View College |url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/kbb03 |website=Handbook of Texas Online |publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]] |accessdate=August 10, 2019 |location=Austin, Texas |date=June 12, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810201739/https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/kbb03 |archive-date=August 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Intense winds in Kingsville unroofed homes and businesses.<ref name=\"MaroonedPassengers\">{{cite news |title=Marooned Passengers from Storm-Swept Section Arrive |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34495625/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=138 |volume=31 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=3 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> A city garage's collapse crushed several cars beneath.<ref name=\"ImagesOfAmerica\">{{cite book |last1=Allison |first1=Pat |title=Kingsville|series=Images of America |date=2011 |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |location=[[Charleston, South Carolina]] |isbn=978-0-7385-8482-9 |pages=44\u201346 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3QBaJ720-20C&pg=PA45&lpg=PA45&dq=%221916%22+hurricane+texas+-wiki&source=bl&ots=9fOqwOUOOz&sig=ACfU3U1QscGakTzRDyV90TMtWhXqwPkQtg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjZ0_Dfr-DjAhURSK0KHUOpAxI4ChDoATALegQICBAB#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |chapter=Season of Problems|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> [[Governor of Illinois]] [[Edward Fitzsimmons Dunne]] was caught in the storm at Kingsville; he had been inspecting army camps along the Texas\u2013Mexico border in the days before they were ravaged by the storm.<ref name=\"EFDunne\">{{cite news |title=Hurricane Thrills Were Experienced by Gov. E. F. Dunne |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34475741/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=138 |volume=31 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Every house was damaged and most were destroyed in [[Riviera, Texas|Riviera]], located {{convert|15|mi|km|abbr=on}} south of Kingsville.<ref name=\"NotBadAsFeared\" />{{rp|2}} In the nearby resort town of Riviera Beach, the hurricane destroyed all businesses and amenities, as well as most of the residences, resulting in an exodus that led to the resort's demise.<ref name=\"RivieraBeach\">{{cite web |last1=Coalson |first1=George A. |title=Riviera Beach, TX |url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hrr24 |website=Handbook of Texas Online |publisher=Texas State Historical Association |accessdate=August 10, 2019 |location=Austin, Texas |date=June 15, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810201736/https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hrr24 |archive-date=August 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Farther north in Galveston, the hurricane produced 50-mph (80&nbsp;km/h) winds that destroyed two homes.<ref name=\"HurricaneHitsSouth\" /><ref name=\"TexasAgain\">{{cite news |title=Texas Again Threatened by Tropical Storm |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34468883/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Bryan-College Station Eagle|The Bryan Daily Eagle]] |agency=Associated Press |issue=197 |volume=30 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=[[Bryan, Texas]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:1916 Texas hurricane rainfall map.png|thumb|Storm rainfall totals in Texas|alt=Isohyet map of rainfall totals]]\nModerate to heavy rains spread across South Texas both ahead of the storm and to the right of the center's path. There were two foci of heavy rainfall: the first along the coast where a maximum of {{convert|6.0|in|mm|abbr=on}} was reported in [[Harlingen, Texas|Harlingen]], and a second borne of [[orographic lifting]] in the mountains of southwestern Texas.<ref name=\"NHRP3\" /> Eight towns, including Harlingen, set 24-hour rainfall records.<ref name=\"Roth_TX\" /> Crops were badly injured by the winds and rain,<ref name=\"MWR_ForecastsWarnings\" /> with damage to cotton accounting for most of the financial loss.<ref name=\"Kilgore\">{{cite journal |last1=Kilgore |first1=Dan E. |title=Corpus Christi: A Quarter Century of Development, 1900\u20131925 |journal=The Southwestern Historical Quarterly |date=April 1972 |volume=75 |issue=4 |page=440 |publisher=[[Texas State Historical Association]] |location=Austin, Texas|jstor=30236738 }} {{subscription required}}</ref> About one-third of the cotton crop around [[Shiner, Texas|Shiner]] was lost, and in some locations more than half of the pecans were blown off trees.<ref name=\"Cuero\">{{cite news |title=Pecans Damaged by Wind but Cotton Not Badly Hurt |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34495533/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=138 |volume=31 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=2 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=\"CottonBadlyDamaged\">{{cite news |title=Cotton Badly Damaged |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34495555/the_houston_post/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=138 |volume=31 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=2 |via=Newspapers.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802191454/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34495555/the_houston_post/ |archive-date=August 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, the storm proved beneficial for cotton harvesting in [[Victoria County, Texas|Victoria County]] by helping to clear excess foliage.<ref name=\"StormDamageCottonSmall\">{{cite news |title=Storm Damage to Cotton is Found Small |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34475379/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Daily Advocate |issue=111 |volume=18 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Victoria, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Many farm buildings and small structures were leveled in [[Beeville, Texas|Beeville]].<ref name=\"CorpusChristiBelievedSuffered\">{{cite news |title=Corpus Christi Believed to Have Suffered Heavily |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34471266/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=Waxahachie Daily Light |issue=127 |volume=24 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Waxahachie, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>  In Brownsville, plate glass windows were blown out and fences and trees were toppled.<ref name=\"IsolatedFromOutsideWorld\">{{cite news |title=Corpus Christi Isolated From Outside World |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34472035/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[The Marshall News Messenger|The Marshall Messenger]] |issue=284 |volume=26 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=[[Marshall, Texas]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Some militia camps were also deluged by the heavy rainfall in the Brownsville area,<ref name=\"HurricaneSantaCruz\">{{cite news |title=Hurricane |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34469891/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=Santa Cruz News |issue=94 |volume=18 |date=August 18, 1916 |location=[[Santa Cruz, California]] |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> destroying thousands of dollars worth of government equipment after perishable munitions were exposed to the elements.<ref name=\"StormLeavesRuin\" /> U.S. Army tents were flattened by the storm,<ref name=\"StormLeavesRuin\" /> injuring four militiamen.<ref name=\"FiveInchesOfRain\">{{cite news |title=Five Inches of Rain |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34472482/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Austin Statesman |issue=228 |volume=45 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Austin, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> All military encampments in the area were forced to be temporarily abandoned,<ref name=\"DestructiveTropicalStorm\">{{cite news |title=Destructive Tropical Storm Sweeps Texas Coast Towns |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34472944/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=[[El Paso Times|El Paso Morning Times]] |agency=Associated Press |location=[[El Paso, Texas]] |page=2 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> with 30,000&nbsp;people seeking refuge in public buildings in [[Mercedes, Texas|Mercedes]] and [[Mission, Texas|Mission]].<ref name=\"StormHasStruckLowerCoast\">{{cite news |title=Storm Has Struck Lower Coast |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34473144/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=137 |volume=31 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Similar damage occurred farther upstream along the [[Rio Grande Valley]] in [[Laredo, Texas|Laredo]], where the hurricane tore down small buildings and communication poles.<ref name=\"Laredo\">{{cite news |title=Telephone and Telegraph Poles and Soldier Tents Blown Down |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34495871/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=138 |volume=31 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=4 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Downed wires forced the city to shut down power for most of the municipality.<ref name=\"GulfStormSwept\">{{cite news |title=Gulf Storm Swept Corpus Christi Beach But No Loss of Life is Reported So Far |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34496296/ |accessdate=August 2, 2019 |work=[[Laredo Morning Times|Laredo Weekly Times]] |issue=10 |volume=36 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=[[Laredo, Texas]] |page=12 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Although damage was widespread, its overall magnitude along the Rio Grande remained slight.<ref name=\"OnlySlight\">{{cite news |title=Only Slight Damage Done Along the Rio Grande |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34471600/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=Waxahachie Daily Light |issue=127 |volume=24 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Waxahachie, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nSections of the [[San Antonio and Aransas Pass Railway]] and [[International\u2013Great Northern Railroad]] were put out of commission, with the former mangled and obstructed by debris.<ref name=\"CorpusChristiBelievedSuffered\" /><ref name=\"AllStateTroopsReportedSafe\">{{cite news |title=All States Troops Are Reported Safe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34471442/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=Waxahachie Daily Light |issue=127 |volume=24 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Waxahachie, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Other trains in the region were delayed by 12\u201318&nbsp;hours,<ref name=\"FiveInchesOfRain\" /> and the total cost of damage to railroads and other public utilities exceeded $300,000.<ref name=\"FridayStorm\">{{cite news |title=Railroads Were Badly Damaged by Friday's Storm |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34476037/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Houston Post |issue=138 |volume=31 |date=August 20, 1916 |location=Houston, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Over a thousand workers were dispatched by the afflicted railroad companies to repair the railways.<ref name=\"FridayStorm\" /> Wind damage was documented as far inland as [[Montell, Texas|Montell]] in [[Uvalde County, Texas|Uvalde County]] where frame homes were damaged and windmills collapsed.<ref name=\"MWR_WeatherMonth\" /> Strong winds and intermittent rainfall extended into the [[Austin, Texas|Austin]] area,<ref name=\"HeavyWindAustin\">{{cite news |title=Heavy Wind Felt Throughout Austin |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34472308/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=Austin American |agency=International News Service |issue=80 |volume=5 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Austin, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> while 68-mph (109&nbsp;km/h) winds swept through San Antonio.<ref name=\"MexicoGets\">{{cite news |title=Mexico Gets the Storm |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34472618/ |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=The Austin Statesman |issue=228 |volume=45 |date=August 19, 1916 |location=Austin, Texas |page=1 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In total, twenty people were killed in Texas, and damage to property was estimated at $1.8&nbsp;million<ref name=\"Roth_TX\" /> (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|1.8|1916|r=0}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}).{{Inflation/fn|US}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n*[[List of Texas hurricanes (1900\u20131949)]]\n*[[Hurricane Bret (1999)]]&nbsp;\u2013 quickly intensified in the western Gulf of Mexico before making landfall on a relatively unpopulated extent of the Texas coast\n*[[1919 Florida Keys hurricane]]&nbsp;\u2013 deadly tropical cyclone that devastated areas of the Florida Keys and Texas, particularly in the Corpus Christi area\n*[[Hurricane Allen]]&nbsp;\u2013 struck South Texas after tracking across the Caribbean Sea\n*[[Hurricane Beulah]]&nbsp;\u2013 a Category&nbsp;5 hurricane which moved through the Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula before striking South Texas\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|1916 Texas hurricane}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=ORpFk-ls62oC&oi=fnd&pg=PA6&dq=1916+Corpus+Christi+hurricane+&ots=Xrr1vB4xWg&sig=MYF0y8ys2aqbcCWMYQ1hGvRAhkk#v=onepage ''Images of America: Corpus Christi'' by Scott Williams]\n*[http://www.atms.unca.edu/ibtracs/ibtracs_v04r00/index.php?name=v04r00-1916225N13305 The storm's entry in the International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship]\n\n{{1916 Atlantic hurricane season buttons}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1916 Texas Hurricane}}\n[[Category:1910s Atlantic hurricane seasons|*]]\n[[Category:Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes]]\n[[Category:Hurricanes in Texas]]\n[[Category:1916 natural disasters in the United States|Texas Hurricane, 1916]]\n[[Category:1916 in Texas]]\n[[Category:1916 meteorology]]\n", "name_user": "TheAustinMan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Slight adjustments per FAC comments", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1916_Texas_hurricane"}
{"title_page": "Joe Exotic", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|American zookeeper and convict}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Joe Exotic\n| image              = Joe Exotic (Santa Rose County Jail).png\n| image_upright      =\n| image_size         =\n| alt                =\n| caption            = Joe Exotic's 2018 mugshot\n| birth_name         = Joseph Allen Schreibvogel\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1963|03|05|mf=y}} {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n| birth_place        = [[Garden City, Kansas]], U.S. {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n| death_cause        =\n| residence          =\n| nationality        =\n| other_names        = {{flatlist|\n* Joseph Allen Maldonado\n* Joseph Allen Maldonado-Passage\n* Joe Exotic\n* The Tiger King\n* Aarron Alex\n* Cody Ryan<ref name=\"Intelligencer\">{{cite news |last1=Moor |first1=Robert |title=American Animals Joe Exotic bred lions, tigers, and ligers at his roadside zoo. He was a modern Barnum who found an equally extraordinary nemesis. |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/joe-exotic-and-his-american-animals.html |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |website=[[Intelligencer (website)|Intelligencer]] |date=September 3, 2019}}</ref>}}\n| occupation         =\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Travis Maldonado|2015|2017|reason=died}}<br>{{marriage|Dillon Passage|2017}}\n| partner            = Brian Rhyne (1986\u20132001)<br>JC Hartpence (2002\u20132003)<br>John Finlay (2003\u20132014)\n| children           = Brandon Chappell\n| module             = {{Infobox criminal|child=yes\n| criminal_charge    = Murder for hire, animal abuse\n| conviction_penalty = 22 years\n| conviction_status  = Incarcerated at [[Federal Medical Center, Fort Worth]]\n| apprehended        = September 7, 2018\n| imprisoned         =\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Allen Maldonado-Passage''' (n\u00e9 '''Schreibvogel'''; born March 5, 1963), better known by his stage name '''Joe Exotic''', is an American former zoo operator, showman, internet personality, musician, and convicted felon. The former owner and operator of the [[Greater Wynnewood Exotic Animal Park]] (a.k.a. G.&nbsp;W. Zoo) in [[Wynnewood, Oklahoma|Wynnewood]], [[Oklahoma]], Maldonado-Passage had claimed to be the most prolific breeder of tigers in the United States.<ref name=\"Intelligencer\"/> Before working with animals he was a police officer\u2014briefly serving as the chief of police in [[Eastvale, Texas]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/joe-exotic-a-dark-journey-into-the-world-of-a-man-gone-wild/ |title=Joe Exotic: A Dark Journey into the World of a Man Gone Wild |last=Reigstad |first=Leif |date=March 13, 2019 |website=[[Texas Monthly]] |language=en |access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=DMN_3Apr20>{{cite news |last=Steele |first=Tom |date=April 3, 2020 |title=Before he was Joe Exotic, 'Tiger King' star owned Arlington pet stores  |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/2020/04/03/before-he-was-joe-exotic-tiger-king-star-owned-arlington-pet-store/ |url-access=limited |work=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |location=Dallas, Texas |access-date=April 3, 2020 }}</ref> He twice unsuccessfully ran for public office, first for [[President of the United States]] in [[2016 United States Presidential election|2016]] as an [[independent politician|independent]], and then for [[Governor of Oklahoma]] in [[2018 Oklahoma gubernatorial election|2018]] as a [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]].\n\nIn 2019, Maldonado-Passage was convicted on 17 federal charges of animal abuse (eight violations of the [[Lacey Act]] and nine of the [[Endangered Species Act]])<ref name=\"TWP\"/> and two counts of [[murder for hire]], for a plot to kill [[Big Cat Rescue]] CEO [[Carole Baskin]].<ref name=\"TWP\">{{cite news |last1=Brulliard |first1=Karin |title=Zookeeper who killed tigers and tried to have rival murdered is sentenced to 22 years in prison |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2020/01/22/joe-exotic-zookeeper-sentencing/ |accessdate=January 23, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> He is serving a 22-year sentence in [[federal prison]]. In 2020, [[Netflix]] released an eight-part documentary, ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', focused on Maldonado-Passage, his zoo, and his feud with Baskin.\n\n==Early life==\nMaldonado-Passage was born Joseph Allen Schreibvogel in [[Garden City, Kansas]], on March 5, 1963.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5807284/tiger-king-netflix-true-story/|title=The Wild Story Behind Netflix's New Docuseries 'Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness'|last=Gajanan|first=Mahita|date=March 24, 2020|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=The Time cited source verifies 1963, but does not say March 5 and does not refer to Garden City or Kansas}} He grew up on a working farm in [[Kansas]]. When he was five years old, he was raped by an older boy.<ref name=\"Intelligencer\"/> He and his family moved to [[Texas]] where he joined the [[Eastvale, Texas]], police department, soon becoming chief of the small department. He has said that after being outed to his parents as gay by one of his siblings, he attempted suicide by crashing his police cruiser into a bridge.<ref name=:0 /> His claims about the wreck have changed over time; in 1997, he told ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' that someone forced the car off the bridge during a police drug investigation. Local residents that were contacted had no recollection of the event.<ref name=DMN_3Apr20 />\n\n==Career==\n===Animals===\nSchreibvogel worked at various jobs before opening a pet store with his brother Garold in [[Arlington, Texas|Arlington]], Texas, in 1986.<ref name=\":0\" />  In 1997, after closing the first pet store and opening a new one nearby, Schreibvogel came into conflict with Arlington officials over repeated code violations for decorations and signs; he had been hanging [[gay pride]] symbols such as a [[United States flag]] with [[Rainbow flag (LGBT)|rainbow stripes]] in the store windows, and he accused city inspectors of [[homophobia]] and of targeting the business because of his sexual orientation.<ref name=DMN_3Apr20/> After his brother's death in a car accident in 1997, Schreibvogel sold the pet store and purchased a {{convert|16|acre|adj=on}} Oklahoma farm with his parents.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=DMN_3Apr20/> Two years after his brother's death, the farm opened as Garold Wayne Exotic Animal Memorial Park as a dedication to his brother.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"NYPN\">{{cite news|last1=Kaplan|first1=Michael|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/19/everything-you-need-to-know-about-netflixs-new-joe-exotic-doc-tiger-king/|title=Everything you need to know about Netflix's new Joe Exotic doc, 'Tiger King'|accessdate=March 20, 2020|work=[[New York Post]]|date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Two of Garold's pets were the zoo's first inhabitants.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn February 1999, animal-welfare investigators discovered a large number of neglected [[emu]]s in [[Red Oak, Texas|Red Oak]], Texas, and Schreibvogel volunteered to capture the animals and take them to his animal park.  However, Schreibvogel, local volunteers, and Red Oak police were quickly overwhelmed by the task of corralling the large and fast-running birds, several of which died. Schreibvogel and another man resorted to killing emus with shotguns and were accused of animal cruelty by police.  However, since the emus were considered [[livestock]], they could lawfully be killed humanely in Texas, and a [[Grand juries in the United States|grand jury]] declined to indict Schreibvogel.  Most surviving birds ultimately wound up at Texas ranches.<ref name=DMN_3Apr20/>\n\nIn 2000, Schreibvogel acquired his first tigers (two abandoned tigers).<ref name=\":0\" /> To feed his growing zoo of [[big cat]]s, he took in horses that were donated to him. He would shoot the horses and feed them whole to the tigers, lions, and other big cats.<ref name=\"Intelligencer\" />\n\nFor over 20 years, he was known as Joe Exotic, the owner and operator of the [[Greater Wynnewood Exotic Animal Park]] (a.k.a. G.&nbsp;W. Zoo), known for its big cats. He operated an online reality television show that he streamed from his zoo. Over the years, he operated sideshows around the country where he allowed people to pet tiger cubs. He also staged shows at fairs and in shopping malls.<ref name=\"NATGEO\"/>\n\nIn 2006, the G.&nbsp;W. Zoo was cited multiple times by the [[United States Department of Agriculture|USDA]] for violations of [[Animal Welfare Act of 1966|Animal Welfare Act]] standards.<ref name=\"USDA\">{{cite news |title=AWA Docket No. 05-0014 Consent Decision and Order |url=https://oalj.oha.usda.gov/sites/default/files/AWA_05-0014_012606.pdf |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |website=[[United States Department of Agriculture]] |date=January 26, 2006}}</ref> In 2011, [[Carole Baskin]], founder of [[Big Cat Rescue]] sanctuary in Florida, organized protests against his use of cubs in his shows. To retaliate, Maldonado-Passage used the Big Cat Rescue name and various identifying aspects of the sanctuary's branding in his own marketing. Baskin sued Maldonado-Passage for trademark infringement and eventually was ruled to be entitled to a $1 million in settlement compensation from him, although she was never able to collect most of it.<ref name=\"NATGEO\"/>\n\n===Music===\n{{See also|#Discography}}\nMaldonado-Passage was an aspiring [[country music|country]] singer. Under the pretense of obtaining music for a planned [[reality television]] series, he commissioned country songs from other artists, with his creative contributions reportedly being limited to suggesting song topics and singing some backing vocals. He then produced [[music video]]s for the songs and posted them on [[YouTube]], depicting himself as the main performer and taking full credit for the music, allegedly without having notified the actual artists.<ref name=\"Slate\">{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Sam |title=Behind the Music of the Tiger King |url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/03/netflixs-tiger-king-joe-exotics-music-isnt-even-by-joe-exotic.html |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> In 2015, he released a video for the song \"Here Kitty Kitty\", a [[diss track]] against Carole Baskin. In the video, he had a Baskin look-alike feeding her second husband, Don Lewis, to the tigers. [[Disappearance of Don Lewis|Lewis has been missing]] since 1997,<ref name=\"Esquire\">{{cite news |last1=Bruney |first1=Gabrielle |title=Joe Exotic's 'Here Kitty Kitty' Music Video Might Be the Best Part of Tiger King |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a31902648/joe-exotic-tiger-king-here-kitty-kitty-music-videos/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> and was declared dead in 2002.<ref name=\"WTSP\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nMaldonado-Passage ran as \"Joseph Allen Maldonado\" as an independent candidate in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 election for President of the United States]], attained ballot access in [[2016 United States presidential election in Colorado|Colorado]], and received 962 votes (including recorded write-ins) nationwide.<ref>https://transition.fec.gov/pubrec/fe2016/2016presgeresults.pdf</ref>\n\nHe then ran as \"Joe Exotic\" in the primary election for the [[Libertarian Party of Oklahoma|Libertarian party]] in the [[2018 Oklahoma gubernatorial election|2018 election for Governor of Oklahoma]]. He received 664 votes in the primary, finishing last among the three Libertarian candidates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/20180626_seb.html#LIBGOV |title=State Election Results, Statewide Primary Election, June 26, 2018 |publisher=Ok.gov |date= |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=oklahoman2019/><ref name=\"NATGEO\">{{cite news |last1=Guynup |first1=Sharon |title=Captive tigers in the U.S. outnumber those in the wild. It's a problem. |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2019/11/tigers-in-the-united-states-outnumber-those-in-the-wild-feature/?cmpid=org=ngp::mc=crm-email::src=ngp::cmp=editorial::add=Animals_20200123&rid=CC8D94CAC95F51BE9F5A4B4F2D84467D |accessdate=January 23, 2020 |work=[[National Geographic]] |date=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:2018 Oklahoma gubernatorial Libertarian primary.svg|thumb|Initial primary results by county:\n{{collapsible list\n| title = Chris Powell\n|{{legend|#554400|100%}}\n|{{legend|#aa8800|80\u201390%}}\n|{{legend|#d4aa00|70\u201380%}}\n|{{legend|#ffcc00|60\u201370%}}\n|{{legend|#ffd42a|50\u201360%}}\n|{{legend|#ffdd55|40\u201350%}}\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| title = Powell/Lawhorn tie\n|{{legend|#cccccc|<40%}}\n|{{legend|#b3b3b3|40\u201350%}}\n|{{legend|#999999|50%}}\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| title = Rex L. Lawhorn\n|{{legend|#55ddff|40\u201350%}}\n|{{legend|#2ad4ff|50\u201360%}}\n|{{legend|#00ccff|60\u201370%}}\n|{{legend|#00aad4|70\u201380%}}\n|{{legend|#004455|100%}}\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| title = Joe Exotic\n|{{legend|#55ff55|40\u201350%}}\n|{{legend|#00d400|70\u201380%}}\n|{{legend|#005500|100%}}\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| title = No votes\n|{{legend|#000000|No Votes}}\n}}\n]]\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = 2018 Libertarian gubernatorial primary<ref name=primaryresults>https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/ok_results_seb.html</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Chris Powell\n| party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| votes = 1,740\n| percentage = 48.9\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Rex L. Lawhorn\n| party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| votes = 1,154\n| percentage = 32.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Joe Exotic\n| party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| votes = 664\n| percentage = 18.7\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 3,558\n| percentage = 100%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Arrest and conviction==\n[[File:Carole Baskin September 2019.png|thumb|200px|[[Carole Baskin]] in 2019, the target of Maldonado-Passage's [[Contract killing|murder-for-hire]] plot.]]\nMaldonado-Passage was indicted for attempting to hire someone to murder [[Big Cat Rescue]] CEO [[Carole Baskin]].<ref>{{cite news|first1=Nolan|last1=Clay|first2=Josh|last2=Wallace|title=Joe Exotic, former Oklahoma gubernatorial candidate, indicted, accused in murder-for-hire plot|url=https://newsok.com/article/5607480/joe-exotic-former-oklahoma-gubernatorial-candidate-indicted-accused-in-murder-for-hire-plot|newspaper=[[The Oklahoman]]|date=September 7, 2018|access-date=August 10, 2019}}</ref> He had tried to hire an [[undercover]] [[FBI]] agent who was posing as a [[hitman]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} On September 7, 2018, he was arrested<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jailview.srso.net/SmartWebClient/Jail.aspx?preview=true&searchvalues=%7B%22FirstName%22:%22%22,%22MiddleName%22:%22%22,%22LastName%22:%22Maldonado-Passage%22,%22BeginBookDate%22:%22%22,%22EndBookDate%22:%22%22,%22BeginReleaseDate%22:%22%22,%22EndReleaseDate%22:%22%22,%22TypeJailSearch%22:%222%22,%22RecordsLoaded%22:1,%22SortOption%22:%220%22,%22SortOrder%22:%220%22,%22IsDefault%22:false%7D|title=Jail View|website=jailview.srso.net|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> in [[Gulf Breeze, Florida|Gulf Breeze]], Florida, and held at the Santa Rosa County Jail until September 19 when he was transferred to federal detention. He was later transferred to Grady County Jail in [[Chickasha, Oklahoma|Chickasha]], Oklahoma.<ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news |last1=Madani |first1=Doha |title=Wildlife park owner 'Joe Exotic' sentenced to 22 years in plot to kill animal rights activist |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/animal-news/wildlife-park-owner-joe-exotic-sentenced-22-years-plot-kill-n1120566 |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |website=[[NBC News]] |date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, 2019, Maldonado-Passage was convicted on two counts of [[murder for hire]], eight violations of the [[Lacey Act]], and nine violations of the [[Endangered Species Act]].<ref name=oklahoman2019>{{cite news|first=Nolan|last=Clay|title=Joe Exotic found guilty in murder-for-hire case|url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5627553/joe-exotic-found-guilty-in-murder-for-hire-case|newspaper=[[The Oklahoman]]|date=April 3, 2019|access-date=August 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"TWP\"/> On January 22, 2020, he was sentenced to 22 years in federal prison.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news |title='Joe Exotic' sentenced to 22 years in federal prison on murder-for-hire, wildlife charges |url=https://www.koco.com/article/joe-exotic-to-be-formally-sentenced-on-murder-for-hire-wildlife-charges/30625982 |accessdate=January 23, 2020 |publisher=ABC [[KOCO]] News 5 |date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> As of March 2020, he is incarcerated at [[Federal Medical Center, Fort Worth|FMC Fort Worth]].<ref>Federal Bureau of Prisons Inmate Locator ([https://www.bop.gov/inmateloc/ https://www.bop.gov/inmateloc/]); Register Number: 26154-017</ref> That same month, Maldonado-Passage began seeking a [[Federal pardons in the United States|presidential pardon]] from [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://stylecaster.com/tiger-king-season-2-netflix-release-date-spoilers-news/|title='Tiger King' Season 2 Will Be 'Just as Dramatic' as the First, According to the Producers.|first=Jason|last=Pham|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJoe Exotic is openly [[gay]]. He has referred to numerous partners as his husbands despite not being legally married.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/a31987795/john-finlay-travis-maldonado-joe-exotic-husband/|title=The Tiger King documentary left out information about Joe Exotic and his husbands|last=Turner|first=Laura Jane|date=April 1, 2020|website=Digital Spy|language=en-GB|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>  His first known partner was Brian Rhyne, who died of complications from [[HIV]] in 2001.<ref name=\"Intelligencer\"/>  The following year, he started a relationship with J.&nbsp;C. Hartpence, an event manager who aided Joe Exotic with his traveling animal show.  In mid-2003, John Finlay was hired as an employee of the G.&nbsp;W. Zoo, and within a month, had begun a relationship with Schreibvogel.  By this point, the relationship between Joe Exotic and Hartpence had deteriorated, due to drug and alcohol addiction.  It finally ended after Joe Exotic threatened to kill Hartpence and feed his remains to the zoo's largest tiger, and when Hartpence woke Schreibvogel up by putting a gun to his head, leading to his arrest by the local authorities. Hartpence was later convicted for child molestation and first-degree murder.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nTravis Maldonado arrived at the zoo in December 2013, and just like Finlay, rapidly began a relationship with Schreibvogel.<ref name=\":0\" /> Schreibvogel, Maldonado and Finlay were unofficially married to each other less than a month later in a three-partner wedding ceremony January 2014.<ref name=\":0\" /> Joe Exotic and Finlay eventually fell out, and following an incident in the zoo's back parking lot, Finlay was arrested and charged with assault and battery. In 2015, Joe Exotic legally wed Travis Maldonado, and his legal name became Joseph Maldonado.<ref name=\":0\" /> As revealed in ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', both John Finlay and Travis Maldonado were [[heterosexual]], and both had affairs; John Finlay had impregnated the zoo's receptionist, which was one of the reasons leading to his departure, and Travis Maldonado was regularly having sex with multiple women on the grounds of the zoo. On October 6, 2017, Travis Maldonado died in an accident involving a firearm,<ref name=\"OGLE\"/> which occurred at the zoo, in front of Joe Exotic's campaign manager.<ref name=\"GHM\">{{cite news |last1=Keeping |first1=Juliana |title=Shooting death at Wynnewood zoo under investigation |url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5567169/shooting-death-at-wynnewood-zoo-under-investigation |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Oklahoman]] |date=October 7, 2017}}</ref> On December 11, 2017, Joe Exotic married Dillon Passage; one of the witnesses was Travis Maldonado's mother.<ref name=\"OGLE\">{{cite news |last1=Patrick |title=Joe Exotic is getting married on Monday\u2026|url=https://www.thelostogle.com/2017/12/07/joe-exotic-is-getting-married-on-monday/ |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |publisher=The Lost Ogle |date=December 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/arts-and-culture/film-and-tv/tiger-king-netflix-what-happened-joe-exotics-husbands-john-finlay-and-travis-maldonado-2521104|title=Tiger King on Netflix: what happened to Joe Exotic's husbands John Finlay and Travis Maldonado?|website=www.yorkshirepost.co.uk}}</ref> Upon his marriage to Passage, Joe Exotic's legal surname became Maldonado-Passage.\n\n==Documentary==\nThe 2020 documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'' is centered on Maldonado-Passage.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness|url=https://www.netflix.com/title/81115994|website=[[Netflix]]|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Julie|last=Miller|title=Netflix's Wild Tiger King Is Your Next True Crime TV Obsession|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/03/netflix-tiger-king-trailer-joe-exotic|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=March 10, 2020|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> He had previously appeared in the [[Louis Theroux]] documentary ''[[America's Most Dangerous Pets]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amp.abc.net.au/article/10897204|title=Joe Exotic, tiger breeder who appeared in Louis Theroux documentary, facing trial over alleged murder plot |website=[[ABC Online|ABC News]] |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Lawsuit==\nOn March 17, 2020, Maldonado-Passage filed a lawsuit against the [[United States federal government]] at the [[Grady County, Oklahoma|Grady County]] Jail. In the lawsuit, he asks for $94 million from the [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]] (USFWS). He is also seeking a presidential pardon from [[Donald Trump]], and plans to represent himself in the lawsuit.<ref name=\"NYP\">{{cite news |last1=Denney |first1=Andrew |title='Tiger King' star Joe Exotic files $94M lawsuit, wants presidential pardon |url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/26/tiger-king-star-joe-exotic-files-94m-lawsuit-wants-presidential-pardon/ |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |website=[[New York Post]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The lawsuit specifies damages by the USFWS of $79 million for the loss of his tigers. He also demands $15 million for false imprisonment and a litany of other charges including the death of his mother, Shirley. The lawsuit also accuses his former business partner, Jeff Lowe, of switching his medicine with illegal drugs and ruining his property.<ref name=\"RSM\">{{cite news |last1=Martoccio |first1=Angie |title='Tiger King' Star Joe Exotic Sues Government Agencies, Former Business Partner |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/tiger-king-joe-exotic-files-lawsuit-973760/ |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PM\">{{cite news |last1=Pelisek |first1=Christine |title=Joe Exotic of Tiger King Files $94M Lawsuit from Prison, Claims Civil Rights Violations |url=https://people.com/crime/joe-exotic-of-tiger-king-files-94m-lawsuit-from-prison-claims-civil-rights-violations/ |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n*''I Saw A Tiger'' (2014)\n* ''Star Struck'' (2015)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Private zoo]]\n* [[Animal abuse]]\n* [[Noel Marshall]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|6352716}}\n* [https://bigcatrescue.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/2019-01-09-Order-denying-Mot-to-dismiss-either-count-1-or-count-2.pdf Indictment]\n* [[USDOJ]] [https://www.justice.gov/usao-wdok/pr/joe-exotic-convicted-murder-hire-and-violating-both-lacey-act-and-endangered-species Conviction Press release]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=7&v=SKr81L3-3LM&feature=emb_title Joe Exotic video montage]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lCgz9915wHw Here Kitty Kitty music video]\n* {{Netflix title|81115994}} {{subscription}}\n{{Tiger King}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Exotic, Joe}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2016 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:Gay men]]\n[[Category:LGBT media personalities]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Kansas]]\n[[Category:Zoo owners]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Animal breeders]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:American conspiracy theorists]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|American zookeeper and convict}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Joe Exotic\n| image              = Joe Exotic (Santa Rose County Jail).png\n| image_upright      =\n| image_size         =\n| alt                =\n| caption            = Joe Exotic's 2018 mugshot\n| birth_name         = Joseph Allen Schreibvogel\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1963|03|05|mf=y}} {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n| birth_place        = [[Garden City, Kansas]], U.S. {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n| death_cause        =\n| residence          =\n| nationality        =\n| other_names        = {{flatlist|\n* Joseph Allen Maldonado\n* Joseph Allen Maldonado-Passage\n* Joe Exotic\n* The Tiger King\n* Aarron Alex\n* Cody Ryan<ref name=\"Intelligencer\">{{cite news |last1=Moor |first1=Robert |title=American Animals Joe Exotic bred lions, tigers, and ligers at his roadside zoo. He was a modern Barnum who found an equally extraordinary nemesis. |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/joe-exotic-and-his-american-animals.html |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |website=[[Intelligencer (website)|Intelligencer]] |date=September 3, 2019}}</ref>}}\n| occupation         =\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Travis Maldonado|2015|2017|reason=died}}<br>{{marriage|Dillon Passage|2017}}\n| partner            = Brian Rhyne (1986\u20132001)<br>JC Hartpence (2002\u20132003)<br>John Finlay (2003\u20132014)\n| children           = Brandon Chappell\n| module             = {{Infobox criminal|child=yes\n| criminal_charge    = Murder for hire, animal abuse\n| conviction_penalty = 22 years\n| conviction_status  = Incarcerated at [[Federal Medical Center, Fort Worth]]\n| apprehended        = September 7, 2018\n| imprisoned         =\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Allen Maldonado-Passage''' (n\u00e9 '''Schreibvogel'''; born March 5, 1963), better known by his stage name '''Joe Exotic''', is an American former zoo operator, showman, internet personality, musician, and convicted felon. The former owner and operator of the [[Greater Wynnewood Exotic Animal Park]] (a.k.a. G.&nbsp;W. Zoo) in [[Wynnewood, Oklahoma|Wynnewood]], [[Oklahoma]], Maldonado-Passage had claimed to be the most prolific breeder of tigers in the United States.<ref name=\"Intelligencer\"/> Before working with animals he was a police officer\u2014briefly serving as the chief of police in [[Eastvale, Texas]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/joe-exotic-a-dark-journey-into-the-world-of-a-man-gone-wild/ |title=Joe Exotic: A Dark Journey into the World of a Man Gone Wild |last=Reigstad |first=Leif |date=March 13, 2019 |website=[[Texas Monthly]] |language=en |access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=DMN_3Apr20>{{cite news |last=Steele |first=Tom |date=April 3, 2020 |title=Before he was Joe Exotic, 'Tiger King' star owned Arlington pet stores  |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/2020/04/03/before-he-was-joe-exotic-tiger-king-star-owned-arlington-pet-store/ |url-access=limited |work=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |location=Dallas, Texas |access-date=April 3, 2020 }}</ref> He twice unsuccessfully ran for public office, first for [[President of the United States]] in [[2016 United States Presidential election|2016]] as an [[independent politician|independent]], and then for [[Governor of Oklahoma]] in [[2018 Oklahoma gubernatorial election|2018]] as a [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]].\n\nIn 2019, Maldonado-Passage was convicted on 17 federal charges of animal abuse (eight violations of the [[Lacey Act]] and nine of the [[Endangered Species Act]])<ref name=\"TWP\"/> and two counts of [[murder for hire]], for a plot to kill [[Big Cat Rescue]] CEO [[Carole Baskin]].<ref name=\"TWP\">{{cite news |last1=Brulliard |first1=Karin |title=Zookeeper who killed tigers and tried to have rival murdered is sentenced to 22 years in prison |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2020/01/22/joe-exotic-zookeeper-sentencing/ |accessdate=January 23, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> He is serving a 22-year sentence in [[federal prison]]. In 2020, [[Netflix]] released an eight-part documentary, ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', focused on Maldonado-Passage, his zoo, and his feud with Baskin.\n\n==Early life==\nMaldonado-Passage was born Joseph Allen Schreibvogel in [[Garden City, Kansas]], on March 5, 1963.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5807284/tiger-king-netflix-true-story/|title=The Wild Story Behind Netflix's New Docuseries 'Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness'|last=Gajanan|first=Mahita|date=March 24, 2020|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=The Time cited source verifies 1963, but does not say March 5 and does not refer to Garden City or Kansas}} He grew up on a working farm in [[Kansas]]. When he was five years old, he was raped by an older boy.<ref name=\"Intelligencer\"/> He and his family moved to [[Texas]] where he joined the [[Eastvale, Texas]], police department, soon becoming chief of the small department. He has said that after being outed to his parents as gay by one of his siblings, he attempted suicide by crashing his police cruiser into a bridge.<ref name=:0 /> His claims about the wreck have changed over time; in 1997, he told ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' that someone forced the car off the bridge during a police drug investigation. Local residents that were contacted had no recollection of the event.<ref name=DMN_3Apr20 />\n\n==Career==\n===Animals===\nSchreibvogel worked at various jobs before opening a pet store with his brother Garold in [[Arlington, Texas|Arlington]], Texas, in 1986.<ref name=\":0\" />  In 1997, after closing the first pet store and opening a new one nearby, Schreibvogel came into conflict with Arlington officials over repeated code violations for decorations and signs; he had been hanging [[gay pride]] symbols such as a [[United States flag]] with [[Rainbow flag (LGBT)|rainbow stripes]] in the store windows, and he accused city inspectors of [[homophobia]] and of targeting the business because of his sexual orientation.<ref name=DMN_3Apr20/> After his brother's death in a car accident in 1997, Schreibvogel sold the pet store and purchased a {{convert|16|acre|adj=on}} Oklahoma farm with his parents.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=DMN_3Apr20/> Two years after his brother's death, the farm opened as Garold Wayne Exotic Animal Memorial Park as a dedication to his brother.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"NYPN\">{{cite news|last1=Kaplan|first1=Michael|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/19/everything-you-need-to-know-about-netflixs-new-joe-exotic-doc-tiger-king/|title=Everything you need to know about Netflix's new Joe Exotic doc, 'Tiger King'|accessdate=March 20, 2020|work=[[New York Post]]|date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Two of Garold's pets were the zoo's first inhabitants.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn February 1999, animal-welfare investigators discovered a large number of neglected [[emu]]s in [[Red Oak, Texas|Red Oak]], Texas, and Schreibvogel volunteered to capture the animals and take them to his animal park.  However, Schreibvogel, local volunteers, and Red Oak police were quickly overwhelmed by the task of corralling the large and fast-running birds, several of which died. Schreibvogel and another man resorted to killing emus with shotguns and were accused of animal cruelty by police.  However, since the emus were considered [[livestock]], they could lawfully be killed humanely in Texas, and a [[Grand juries in the United States|grand jury]] declined to indict Schreibvogel.  Most surviving birds ultimately wound up at Texas ranches.<ref name=DMN_3Apr20/>\n\nIn 2000, Schreibvogel acquired his first tigers (two abandoned tigers).<ref name=\":0\" /> To feed his growing zoo of [[big cat]]s, he took in horses that were donated to him. He would shoot the horses and feed them whole to the tigers, lions, and other big cats.<ref name=\"Intelligencer\" />\n\nFor over 20 years, he was known as Joe Exotic, the owner and operator of the [[Greater Wynnewood Exotic Animal Park]] (a.k.a. G.&nbsp;W. Zoo), known for its big cats. He operated an online reality television show that he streamed from his zoo. Over the years, he operated sideshows around the country where he allowed people to pet tiger cubs. He also staged shows at fairs and in shopping malls.<ref name=\"NATGEO\"/>\n\nIn 2006, the G.&nbsp;W. Zoo was cited multiple times by the [[United States Department of Agriculture|USDA]] for violations of [[Animal Welfare Act of 1966|Animal Welfare Act]] standards.<ref name=\"USDA\">{{cite news |title=AWA Docket No. 05-0014 Consent Decision and Order |url=https://oalj.oha.usda.gov/sites/default/files/AWA_05-0014_012606.pdf |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |website=[[United States Department of Agriculture]] |date=January 26, 2006}}</ref> In 2011, [[Carole Baskin]], founder of [[Big Cat Rescue]] sanctuary in Florida, organized protests against his use of cubs in his shows. To retaliate, Maldonado-Passage used the Big Cat Rescue name and various identifying aspects of the sanctuary's branding in his own marketing. Baskin sued Maldonado-Passage for trademark infringement and eventually was ruled to be entitled to a $1 million in settlement compensation from him, although she was never able to collect most of it.<ref name=\"NATGEO\"/>\n\n===Music===\n{{See also|#Discography}}\nMaldonado-Passage was an aspiring [[country music|country]] singer. Under the pretense of obtaining music for a planned [[reality television]] series, he commissioned country songs from other artists, with his creative contributions reportedly being limited to suggesting song topics and singing some backing vocals. He then produced [[music video]]s for the songs and posted them on [[YouTube]], depicting himself as the main performer and taking full credit for the music, allegedly without having notified the actual artists.<ref name=\"Slate\">{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Sam |title=Behind the Music of the Tiger King |url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/03/netflixs-tiger-king-joe-exotics-music-isnt-even-by-joe-exotic.html |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> In 2015, he released a video for the song \"Here Kitty Kitty\", a [[diss track]] against Carole Baskin. In the video, he had a Baskin look-alike feeding her second husband, Don Lewis, to the tigers. [[Disappearance of Don Lewis|Lewis has been missing]] since 1997,<ref name=\"Esquire\">{{cite news |last1=Bruney |first1=Gabrielle |title=Joe Exotic's 'Here Kitty Kitty' Music Video Might Be the Best Part of Tiger King |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a31902648/joe-exotic-tiger-king-here-kitty-kitty-music-videos/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> and was declared dead in 2002.<ref name=\"WTSP\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nMaldonado-Passage ran as \"Joseph Allen Maldonado\" as an independent candidate in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 election for President of the United States]], attained ballot access in [[2016 United States presidential election in Colorado|Colorado]], and received 962 votes (including recorded write-ins) nationwide.<ref>https://transition.fec.gov/pubrec/fe2016/2016presgeresults.pdf</ref>\n\nHe then ran as \"Joe Exotic\" in the primary election for the [[Libertarian Party of Oklahoma|Libertarian party]] in the [[2018 Oklahoma gubernatorial election|2018 election for Governor of Oklahoma]]. He received 664 votes in the primary, finishing last among the three Libertarian candidates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/20180626_seb.html#LIBGOV |title=State Election Results, Statewide Primary Election, June 26, 2018 |publisher=Ok.gov |date= |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=oklahoman2019/><ref name=\"NATGEO\">{{cite news |last1=Guynup |first1=Sharon |title=Captive tigers in the U.S. outnumber those in the wild. It's a problem. |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2019/11/tigers-in-the-united-states-outnumber-those-in-the-wild-feature/?cmpid=org=ngp::mc=crm-email::src=ngp::cmp=editorial::add=Animals_20200123&rid=CC8D94CAC95F51BE9F5A4B4F2D84467D |accessdate=January 23, 2020 |work=[[National Geographic]] |date=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:2018 Oklahoma gubernatorial Libertarian primary.svg|thumb|Initial primary results by county:\n{{collapsible list\n| title = Chris Powell\n|{{legend|#554400|100%}}\n|{{legend|#aa8800|80\u201390%}}\n|{{legend|#d4aa00|70\u201380%}}\n|{{legend|#ffcc00|60\u201370%}}\n|{{legend|#ffd42a|50\u201360%}}\n|{{legend|#ffdd55|40\u201350%}}\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| title = Powell/Lawhorn tie\n|{{legend|#cccccc|<40%}}\n|{{legend|#b3b3b3|40\u201350%}}\n|{{legend|#999999|50%}}\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| title = Rex L. Lawhorn\n|{{legend|#55ddff|40\u201350%}}\n|{{legend|#2ad4ff|50\u201360%}}\n|{{legend|#00ccff|60\u201370%}}\n|{{legend|#00aad4|70\u201380%}}\n|{{legend|#004455|100%}}\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| title = Joe Exotic\n|{{legend|#55ff55|40\u201350%}}\n|{{legend|#00d400|70\u201380%}}\n|{{legend|#005500|100%}}\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| title = No votes\n|{{legend|#000000|No Votes}}\n}}\n]]\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = 2018 Libertarian gubernatorial primary<ref name=primaryresults>https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/ok_results_seb.html</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Chris Powell\n| party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| votes = 1,740\n| percentage = 48.9\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Rex L. Lawhorn\n| party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| votes = 1,154\n| percentage = 32.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Joe Exotic\n| party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| votes = 664\n| percentage = 18.7\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 3,558\n| percentage = 100%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Arrest and conviction==\n[[File:Carole Baskin September 2019.png|thumb|200px|[[Carole Baskin]] in 2019, the target of Maldonado-Passage's [[Contract killing|murder-for-hire]] plot.]]\nMaldonado-Passage was indicted for attempting to hire someone to murder [[Big Cat Rescue]] CEO [[Carole Baskin]].<ref>{{cite news|first1=Nolan|last1=Clay|first2=Josh|last2=Wallace|title=Joe Exotic, former Oklahoma gubernatorial candidate, indicted, accused in murder-for-hire plot|url=https://newsok.com/article/5607480/joe-exotic-former-oklahoma-gubernatorial-candidate-indicted-accused-in-murder-for-hire-plot|newspaper=[[The Oklahoman]]|date=September 7, 2018|access-date=August 10, 2019}}</ref> He had tried to hire an [[undercover]] [[FBI]] agent who was posing as a [[hitman]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} On September 7, 2018, he was arrested<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jailview.srso.net/SmartWebClient/Jail.aspx?preview=true&searchvalues=%7B%22FirstName%22:%22%22,%22MiddleName%22:%22%22,%22LastName%22:%22Maldonado-Passage%22,%22BeginBookDate%22:%22%22,%22EndBookDate%22:%22%22,%22BeginReleaseDate%22:%22%22,%22EndReleaseDate%22:%22%22,%22TypeJailSearch%22:%222%22,%22RecordsLoaded%22:1,%22SortOption%22:%220%22,%22SortOrder%22:%220%22,%22IsDefault%22:false%7D|title=Jail View|website=jailview.srso.net|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> in [[Gulf Breeze, Florida|Gulf Breeze]], Florida, and held at the Santa Rosa County Jail until September 19 when he was transferred to federal detention. He was later transferred to Grady County Jail in [[Chickasha, Oklahoma|Chickasha]], Oklahoma.<ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news |last1=Madani |first1=Doha |title=Wildlife park owner 'Joe Exotic' sentenced to 22 years in plot to kill animal rights activist |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/animal-news/wildlife-park-owner-joe-exotic-sentenced-22-years-plot-kill-n1120566 |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |website=[[NBC News]] |date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, 2019, Maldonado-Passage was convicted on two counts of [[murder for hire]], eight violations of the [[Lacey Act]], and nine violations of the [[Endangered Species Act]].<ref name=oklahoman2019>{{cite news|first=Nolan|last=Clay|title=Joe Exotic found guilty in murder-for-hire case|url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5627553/joe-exotic-found-guilty-in-murder-for-hire-case|newspaper=[[The Oklahoman]]|date=April 3, 2019|access-date=August 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"TWP\"/> On January 22, 2020, he was sentenced to 22 years in federal prison.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news |title='Joe Exotic' sentenced to 22 years in federal prison on murder-for-hire, wildlife charges |url=https://www.koco.com/article/joe-exotic-to-be-formally-sentenced-on-murder-for-hire-wildlife-charges/30625982 |accessdate=January 23, 2020 |publisher=ABC [[KOCO]] News 5 |date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> As of March 2020, he is incarcerated at [[Federal Medical Center, Fort Worth|FMC Fort Worth]].<ref>Federal Bureau of Prisons Inmate Locator ([https://www.bop.gov/inmateloc/ https://www.bop.gov/inmateloc/]); Register Number: 26154-017</ref> That same month, Maldonado-Passage began seeking a [[Federal pardons in the United States|presidential pardon]] from [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://stylecaster.com/tiger-king-season-2-netflix-release-date-spoilers-news/|title='Tiger King' Season 2 Will Be 'Just as Dramatic' as the First, According to the Producers.|first=Jason|last=Pham|date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJoe Exotic is openly [[gay]]. He has referred to numerous partners as his husbands despite not being legally married.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/a31987795/john-finlay-travis-maldonado-joe-exotic-husband/|title=The Tiger King documentary left out information about Joe Exotic and his husbands|last=Turner|first=Laura Jane|date=April 1, 2020|website=Digital Spy|language=en-GB|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>  His first known partner was Brian Rhyne, who died of complications from [[HIV]] in 2001.<ref name=\"Intelligencer\"/>  The following year, he started a relationship with J.&nbsp;C. Hartpence, an event manager who aided Joe Exotic with his traveling animal show.  In mid-2003, John Finlay was hired as an employee of the G.&nbsp;W. Zoo, and within a month, had begun a relationship with Schreibvogel.  By this point, the relationship between Joe Exotic and Hartpence had deteriorated, due to drug and alcohol addiction.  It finally ended after Joe Exotic threatened to kill Hartpence and feed his remains to the zoo's largest tiger, and when Hartpence woke Schreibvogel up by putting a gun to his head, leading to his arrest by the local authorities. Hartpence was later convicted for child molestation and first-degree murder.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nTravis Maldonado arrived at the zoo in December 2013, and just like Finlay, rapidly began a relationship with Schreibvogel.<ref name=\":0\" /> Schreibvogel, Maldonado and Finlay were unofficially married to each other less than a month later in a three-partner wedding ceremony January 2014.<ref name=\":0\" /> Joe Exotic and Finlay eventually fell out, and following an incident in the zoo's back parking lot, Finlay was arrested and charged with assault and battery. In 2015, Joe Exotic legally wed Travis Maldonado, and his legal name became Joseph Maldonado.<ref name=\":0\" /> As revealed in ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', both John Finlay and Travis Maldonado were [[heterosexual]], and both had affairs; John Finlay had impregnated the zoo's receptionist, which was one of the reasons leading to his departure, and Travis Maldonado was regularly having sex with multiple women on the grounds of the zoo. On October 6, 2017, Travis Maldonado died in an accident involving a firearm,<ref name=\"OGLE\"/> which occurred at the zoo, in front of Joe Exotic's campaign manager.<ref name=\"GHM\">{{cite news |last1=Keeping |first1=Juliana |title=Shooting death at Wynnewood zoo under investigation |url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5567169/shooting-death-at-wynnewood-zoo-under-investigation |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Oklahoman]] |date=October 7, 2017}}</ref> On December 11, 2017, Joe Exotic married Dillon Passage; one of the witnesses was Travis Maldonado's mother.<ref name=\"OGLE\">{{cite news |last1=Patrick |title=Joe Exotic is getting married on Monday\u2026|url=https://www.thelostogle.com/2017/12/07/joe-exotic-is-getting-married-on-monday/ |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |publisher=The Lost Ogle |date=December 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/arts-and-culture/film-and-tv/tiger-king-netflix-what-happened-joe-exotics-husbands-john-finlay-and-travis-maldonado-2521104|title=Tiger King on Netflix: what happened to Joe Exotic's husbands John Finlay and Travis Maldonado?|website=www.yorkshirepost.co.uk}}</ref> Upon his marriage to Passage, Joe Exotic's legal surname became Maldonado-Passage.\n\n==Documentary==\nThe 2020 documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'' is centered on Maldonado-Passage.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness|url=https://www.netflix.com/title/81115994|website=[[Netflix]]|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Julie|last=Miller|title=Netflix's Wild Tiger King Is Your Next True Crime TV Obsession|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/03/netflix-tiger-king-trailer-joe-exotic|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=March 10, 2020|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> He had previously appeared in the [[Louis Theroux]] documentary ''[[America's Most Dangerous Pets]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amp.abc.net.au/article/10897204|title=Joe Exotic, tiger breeder who appeared in Louis Theroux documentary, facing trial over alleged murder plot |website=[[ABC Online|ABC News]] |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Lawsuit==\nOn March 17, 2020, Maldonado-Passage filed a lawsuit against the [[United States federal government]] at the [[Grady County, Oklahoma|Grady County]] Jail. In the lawsuit, he asks for $94 million from the [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]] (USFWS). He is also seeking a presidential pardon from [[Donald Trump]], and plans to represent himself in the lawsuit.<ref name=\"NYP\">{{cite news |last1=Denney |first1=Andrew |title='Tiger King' star Joe Exotic files $94M lawsuit, wants presidential pardon |url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/26/tiger-king-star-joe-exotic-files-94m-lawsuit-wants-presidential-pardon/ |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |website=[[New York Post]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The lawsuit specifies damages by the USFWS of $79 million for the loss of his tigers. He also demands $15 million for false imprisonment and a litany of other charges including the death of his mother, Shirley. The lawsuit also accuses his former business partner, Jeff Lowe, of switching his medicine with illegal drugs and ruining his property.<ref name=\"RSM\">{{cite news |last1=Martoccio |first1=Angie |title='Tiger King' Star Joe Exotic Sues Government Agencies, Former Business Partner |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/tiger-king-joe-exotic-files-lawsuit-973760/ |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PM\">{{cite news |last1=Pelisek |first1=Christine |title=Joe Exotic of Tiger King Files $94M Lawsuit from Prison, Claims Civil Rights Violations |url=https://people.com/crime/joe-exotic-of-tiger-king-files-94m-lawsuit-from-prison-claims-civil-rights-violations/ |accessdate=March 29, 2020 |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n*''I Saw A Tiger'' (2014)\n* ''Star Struck'' (2015)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Private zoo]]\n* [[Animal abuse]]\n* [[Noel Marshall]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|6352716}}\n* [https://bigcatrescue.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/2019-01-09-Order-denying-Mot-to-dismiss-either-count-1-or-count-2.pdf Indictment]\n* [[USDOJ]] [https://www.justice.gov/usao-wdok/pr/joe-exotic-convicted-murder-hire-and-violating-both-lacey-act-and-endangered-species Conviction Press release]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=7&v=SKr81L3-3LM&feature=emb_title Joe Exotic video montage]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lCgz9915wHw Here Kitty Kitty music video]\n* {{Netflix title|81115994}}\n{{Tiger King}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Exotic, Joe}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2016 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:Gay men]]\n[[Category:LGBT media personalities]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Kansas]]\n[[Category:Zoo owners]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Animal breeders]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:American conspiracy theorists]]\n", "name_user": "Kirbanzo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Exotic"}
{"title_page": "Love Me, I Love You", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Love Me, I Love You\n| cover      = B'z LMILY.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[B'z]]\n| album      = [[Loose (B'z album)|Loose]]\n| released   = July 7, 1995\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hard rock]]\n| length     = 3:20\n| label      = [[BMG Japan]]\n| writer     = [[Koshi Inaba]], [[Tak Matsumoto]]\n| producer   = Tak Matsumoto\n| prev_title = [[Negai (B'z song)|Negai]]\n| prev_year  = 1995\n| next_title = [[Love Phantom]]\n| next_year  = 1995\n}}\n\"'''Love Me, I Love You'''\" is the seventeenth single by [[B'z]], released on July 7, 1995. This song is one of B'z many number-one singles in [[Oricon]] chart. It sold over 1,393,000 copies according to Oricon, giving their 10th million selling single. B'z became the first artist in Japan to have 10 million sellers consecutively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/ranking/22742/|title=B'z\u3001\u6b74\u4ee3No.1\u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8\u307e\u3067\u306e\u8ecc\u8de1\uff01|publisher=Oricon|date=2006-05-25|accessdate=2008-12-04|language=ja}}</ref> It was used as the drama ''[[Gehai Hiiragi Mata Sabur\u014d]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s theme song.\n\n== Track listing ==\n#Love Me, I Love You\n#{{nihongo|Tokyo|\u6771\u4eac}}\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://bz-vermillion.com/ B'z official website]\n\n{{B'z singles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Love Me I Love You}}\n[[Category:1995 singles]]\n[[Category:B'z songs]]\n[[Category:Oricon Weekly number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Japanese television drama theme songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tak Matsumoto]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Koshi Inaba]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Love Me, I Love You\n| cover      = B'z LMILY.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[B'z]]\n| album      = [[Loose (B'z album)|Loose]]\n| released   = July 7, 1995\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hard rock]]\n| length     = 3:20\n| label      = [[BMG Japan]]\n| writer     = [[Koshi Inaba]], [[Tak Matsumoto]]\n| producer   = Tak Matsumoto\n| prev_title = [[Negai (B'z song)|Negai]]\n| prev_year  = 1995\n| next_title = [[Love Phantom]]\n| next_year  = 1995\n}}\n\"'''Love Me, I Love You'''\" is the seventeenth single by [[B'z]], released on July 7, 1995. This song is one of B'z many number-one singles in [[Oricon]] chart. It sold over 1,393,000 copies according to Oricon, giving their 10th million selling single. B'z became the first artist in Japan to have 10 million sellers consecutively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/ranking/22742/|title=B'z\u3001\u6b74\u4ee3No.1\u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8\u307e\u3067\u306e\u8ecc\u8de1\uff01|publisher=Oricon|date=2006-05-25|accessdate=2008-12-04|language=ja}}</ref> It was used as the drama ''[[Gehai Hiiragi Mata Sabur\u014d]]'''s theme song.\n\n== Track listing ==\n#Love Me, I Love You\n#{{nihongo|Tokyo|\u6771\u4eac}}\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://bz-vermillion.com/ B'z official website]\n\n{{B'z singles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Love Me I Love You}}\n[[Category:1995 singles]]\n[[Category:B'z songs]]\n[[Category:Oricon Weekly number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Japanese television drama theme songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tak Matsumoto]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Koshi Inaba]]\n", "name_user": "Victor Lopes", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixing bold error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Love_Me,_I_Love_You"}
{"title_page": "Steve Ballmer", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman and investor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Steve Ballmer\n| image = Steve Ballmer 2014.jpg\n| caption = Ballmer in 2014\n| birth_name = Steven Anthony Ballmer\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1956|3|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n| education = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Stanford Graduate School of Business]]\n| net_worth = [[US$]]51.9 billion (October 2019)<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/steve-ballmer/?list=billionaires |title=Steve Ballmer|magazine=Forbes}}</ref>\n| spouse = {{marriage|Connie Snyder|1990}}\n| children = 3\n| awards = [[Legion of Honour]]<ref>{{YouTube|IYKjFfkqBmo|Sarkozy fait Steve Ballmer chevalier de la L\u00e9gion d'honneur}}, AFP</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Steven Anthony Ballmer''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u0254\u02d0|l|m|\u0259r}}; born March 24, 1956)<ref name=\"cnnbio\">{{cite web | url = http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/08/us/steve-ballmer-fast-facts/ | title= Steve Ballmer Fast Facts | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=March 11, 2015|accessdate= January 28, 2016}}</ref><!--CNN cite also verifies birth name Steven Anthony Ballmer--> is an [[United States|American]] businessman and investor who was the [[chief executive officer]] of [[Microsoft]] from January 13, 2000,<ref name=\"ms bio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.microsoft.com/presspass/exec/steve/default.mspx|title=Steve Ballmer: Chief Executive Officer|date=March 1, 2005|publisher=Microsoft|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080203132040/http://www.microsoft.com/Presspass/exec/steve/default.mspx|archivedate=February 3, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> to February 4, 2014,<ref name=\"cnnbio\" /> and is the current owner of the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). {{As of|2019|10|df=US}}, his personal wealth is estimated at US $51.9&nbsp;billion,<ref name=\"FSB\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/steve-ballmer/?list=billionaires|title=Steve Ballmer|work=Forbes|accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref> ranking him the 16th richest person in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/billionaires/list/#version:static|title=Forbes 400|work=Forbes|accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBallmer was hired by [[Bill Gates]] at Microsoft in 1980 and subsequently left the MBA program at [[Stanford University]]. He eventually became President in 1998, and replaced Gates as CEO in 2000. On February 4, 2014, Ballmer retired as CEO and resigned from the Board of Directors on August 19, 2014 to prepare for teaching a new class.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/press/2013/aug13/08-23announcementpr.aspx|title=Microsoft CEO Steve Ballmer to retire within 12 months.|last=|first=|date=August 23, 2013|website=|publisher=Microsoft|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824142520/http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/press/2013/aug13/08-23AnnouncementPR.aspx|archive-date=August 24, 2013|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"nadella\">{{cite web|url=https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/press/2014/feb14/02-04newspr.aspx|title=Microsoft Board names Satya Nadella as CEO|date=February 4, 2014|publisher=Microsoft|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204183103/http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/press/2014/feb14/02-04newspr.aspx|archive-date=February 4, 2014|url-status=}}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, 2014, Ballmer placed a bid of $2&nbsp;billion to purchase the NBA's Los Angeles Clippers after NBA commissioner [[Adam Silver]] forced [[Donald Sterling]] to sell the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2014/news/05/29/clippers-bids.ap/index.html|title=Report: Ex-Microsoft CEO Ballmer willing to pay $2B for Clips|publisher=NBA.com|date=May 29, 2014|accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> He became the Clippers owner on August 12, 2014; Microsoft co-founder [[Paul Allen]] was a fellow owner in the NBA, having owned the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] since 1988.\n\nHis [[Steve Ballmer#History with Microsoft|tenure and legacy as Microsoft CEO]] has received mixed reception, with the company tripling sales and doubling of profits, but losing its market dominance and missing out on [[21st century skills|21st-century technology trends]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/10/25/why-tim-cook-is-steve-ballmer/|title=Why Tim Cook is Steve Ballmer|date=October 26, 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/business/2012/08/microsoft-lost-mojo-steve-ballmer|title=How Microsoft Lost Its Mojo: Steve Ballmer and Corporate America's Most Spectacular Decline|first=Kurt|last=Eichenwald|website=The Hive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-microsoft-ballmer-newsmaker/steve-ballmer-ends-run-as-microsofts-relentless-salesman-idUSBRE97M0YV20130823|title=Steve Ballmer ends run as Microsoft's relentless salesman|first=Bill|last=Rigby|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBallmer was born in [[Detroit]]; he is the son of Beatrice Dworkin and Frederic Henry Ballmer (Fritz Hans Ballmer),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bernerzeitung.ch/basel/land/MicrosoftChef-Vorfahren-waren-Schweizer-die-in-Hoehlen-wohnten/story/20870798|title=Microsoft-Chef: Vorfahren waren Schweizer, \"die in H\u00f6hlen wohnten\"|date=October 12, 2009|website=Berner Zeitung|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401065424/http://www.bernerzeitung.ch/basel/land/MicrosoftChef-Vorfahren-waren-Schweizer-die-in-Hoehlen-wohnten/story/20870798|archivedate=April 1, 2015 |access-date=April 8, 2016}}</ref> a manager at the [[Ford Motor Company]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/internationaldir0000unse |url-access=registration |quote=Family: Son of Frederic Henry Ballmer (manager. |title=International directory of business biographies |authors=Neil Schlager, Vanessa Torrado-Caputo, Margaret Mazurkiewicz, and Schlager Group |publisher=St. James Press |date= |accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref> His father was a Swiss immigrant who predicted that his son, at eight years old, would attend Harvard. His mother was [[History of the Jews in Belarus|Belarusian Jewish]].<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Summary: Bad Boy Ballmer - Fredric Maxwell: The man who rules Microsoft|author=Publishing, B.N.|date=2013|publisher=Must Read Summaries|isbn=9782806224927|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qMmWzuB27uUC&pg=PT5|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>{{r|leibovich20001231}} Through his mother, Ballmer is a second cousin of actress and comedian [[Gilda Radner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19980125&slug=2730718|title=Business - Microsoft's Heir Apparent -- Steve Ballmer - Seattle Times Newspaper|publisher=}}</ref> Ballmer grew up in the affluent community of [[Farmington Hills, Michigan|Farmington Hills]], [[Michigan]]. Ballmer also lived in Brussels from 1964 to 1967, where he attended the [[International School of Brussels]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Ballmer lived in Brussels!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zvcPlwKrquM|accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> In 1973, he attended college prep and engineering classes at [[Lawrence Technological University]]. He graduated valedictorian from [[Detroit Country Day School]], a private [[university-preparatory school|college preparatory school]] in [[Beverly Hills, Michigan|Beverly Hills]], [[Michigan]], with a score of 800 on the mathematical section of the [[SAT]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.woopidoo.com/biography/steve-ballmer/index.htm |title=Steve Ballmer Biography - Microsoft CEO |publisher=Woopidoo.com |date=March 24, 1956 |accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/28/business/yourmoney/28ballmer.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | first=Steve | last=Lohr | title=Preaching From the Ballmer Pulpit | date=January 28, 2007}}</ref> and was a [[National Merit Scholarship Program|National Merit Scholar]].<ref name=\"nationalmerit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalmerit.org/s/1758/interior.aspx?sid=1758&gid=2&pgid=416 |title=National Merit Scholarship Corporation - Scholars You May Know |publisher=nationalmerit.org|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He now sits on the school's [[board of directors]]. In 1977, he graduated ''[[magna cum laude]]'' from [[Harvard College|Harvard University]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[applied mathematics]] and [[economics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.woopidoo.com/biography/steve-ballmer/ |title=Steve Ballmer Biography - Microsoft CEO |publisher=Woopidoo.com |accessdate=June 14, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/04/08/us/steve-ballmer-fast-facts/|title=\nSteve Ballmer Fast Facts|date=April 2, 2017|work=CNN Library|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nAt college, Ballmer was a manager for the [[Harvard Crimson football]] team and a member of the [[Fox Club (Harvard)|Fox Club]], worked on ''[[The Harvard Crimson]]'' newspaper as well as the ''[[Harvard Advocate]]'', and lived down the hall from fellow sophomore [[Bill Gates]]. He scored highly in the [[William Lowell Putnam Mathematical Competition]], an exam sponsored by the [[Mathematical Association of America]], scoring higher than Bill Gates.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/28/business/yourmoney/28ballmer.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first=Steve | last=Lohr | title=Preaching From the Ballmer Pulpit | date=January 28, 2007}}</ref> He then worked as an assistant product manager at [[Procter & Gamble]] for two years, where he shared an office with [[Jeffrey R. Immelt]], who later became CEO of [[General Electric]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/companies/management/2007-04-29-ballmer-ceo-forum-usat_N.htm|work=[[USA Today]]|title=CEO Forum: Microsoft's Ballmer having a 'great time{{'-}}|author=David Lieberman|date=April 29, 2007|quote=First job: Assistant product manager for [[Duncan Hines]]' Moist & Easy cakes and brownies. His cubicle mate was Jeffrey Immelt, now CEO of General Electric.}}</ref> After briefly trying to write screenplays in Hollywood,<ref name=\"leibovich20001231\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/2000/12/31/alter-egos/91b267b0-858c-4d4e-a4bd-48f22e015f70/ |title=Alter Egos |last=Leibovich |first=Mark |date=December 31, 2000 |work=Washington Post |access-date=June 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225224631/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/2000/12/31/alter-egos/91b267b0-858c-4d4e-a4bd-48f22e015f70/ |archive-date=December 25, 2016 |issn=0190-8286 | url-access=subscription}}</ref> in 1980 Ballmer dropped out of the [[Stanford Graduate School of Business]] to join Microsoft.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/02_24/b3787001.htm|work=[[BusinessWeek]]|title=Ballmer's Microsoft|first1=Jay |last1=Greene |first2=Steve |last2=Hamm |first3=Jim |last3=Kerstetter |date=June 17, 2002|quote=After two years, Ballmer headed for Stanford University's MBA program for a better grounding in business. When the fledgling Microsoft ran into problems in 1980, Gates persuaded his friend to drop out and give him a hand.}}</ref>\n\n==History with Microsoft==\nBallmer joined [[Microsoft]] on June 11, 1980, and became Microsoft's 30th employee, the first business manager hired by Gates.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Ballmer: Chief Executive Officer|url=https://www.microsoft.com/presspass/exec/steve/default.aspx?tab=biography}}</ref>\n\nBallmer was offered a salary of $50,000 as well as 5-10% of the company.{{r|leibovich20001231}} When Microsoft was incorporated in 1981, Ballmer owned 8% of the company. In 2003, Ballmer sold 39.3 million Microsoft shares equating to approximately $955 million, thereby reducing his ownership to 4%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2003/may/28/1|title=Microsoft chief calms investors after selling shares|newspaper=The Guardian|date=May 28, 2003|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref> The same year, he replaced Microsoft's [[employee stock option]]s program.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/2003/07/08/cx_aw_0708msft.html|title=Microsoft Loses Its Options|work=Forbes|date=July 8, 2003|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the 20 years following his hire, Ballmer headed several Microsoft divisions, including operations, operating systems development, and sales and support. From February 1992 onwards, he was Executive Vice President, Sales, and Support. Ballmer led Microsoft's development of the [[.NET Framework]]. Ballmer was then promoted to President of Microsoft, a title that he held from July 1998 to February 2001, making him the de facto number two in the company to the chairman and CEO, Bill Gates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/microsoft/10262853/Microsoft-the-ups-and-downs-of-the-Ballmer-era.html |title=Microsoft: the ups and downs of the Ballmer era |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=August 23, 2013 |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |location=London |first=Sophie |last=Curtis}}</ref>\n\n===Chief Executive Officer (2000\u20132014)===\n[[File:Steve Ballmer MWC 2010.jpg|thumb|upright|Steve Ballmer at Mobile World Congress 2010]]\n\nOn January 13, 2000, Ballmer was officially named the chief executive officer.<ref name=\"ms bio\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/602708.stm|title=Steve Ballmer, friend of Bill|work=BBC News|date=January 13, 2000|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref> As CEO, Ballmer handled company finances and daily operations, but Gates remained chairman of the board and still retained control of the \"technological vision\" as chief software architect.<ref>{{cite web|last=Farber|first=Dan|date=August 26, 2013|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-10805_3-57600098-75/bill-gates-steve-ballmer-and-the-parting-of-the-ways/|title=Bill Gates, Steve Ballmer and the Parting of the Ways|website=CNET News|accessdate=September 4, 2013}}</ref> Gates relinquished day-to-day activities when he stepped down as chief software architect in 2006, while staying on as chairman, and that gave Ballmer the autonomy needed to make major management changes at Microsoft.<ref name=\"businessweek1\">{{cite news|last=Vance |first=Ashlee |url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/steve-ballmer-reboots-01122012.html |title=Steve Ballmer Reboots |work=Businessweek |date=January 12, 2012 |accessdate=June 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhen Ballmer took over as CEO, the company was fighting an antitrust lawsuit brought on by the U.S. government and 20 states, plus class-action lawsuits and complaints from rival companies. While it was said that Gates would have continued fighting the suit, Ballmer made it his priority to settle these saying: \"Being the object of a lawsuit, effectively, or a complaint from your government is a very awkward, uncomfortable position to be in. It just has all downside. People assume if the government brought a complaint that there's really a problem, and your ability to say we're a good, proper, moral place is tough. It's actually tough, even though you feel that way about yourselves.\"<ref name=\"tech.fortune.cnn.com\">{{cite news| url=http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2013/12/11/for-steve-ballmer-a-lasting-touch-on-microsoft/?iid=SF_F_River | work=CNN | title=For Steve Ballmer, a lasting touch on Microsoft}}</ref>\n\nUpon becoming CEO, Ballmer required detailed business justification in order to approve of new products, rather than allowing hundreds of products that sounded potentially interesting or trendy. In 2005, he recruited [[B. Kevin Turner]] from [[Walmart]], who was the President and CEO of [[Sam's Club]], to become Microsoft's Chief Operating Officer.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lohr|first1=Steve|title=Microsoft Shops at Wal-Mart for an Operating Chief|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/05/technology/microsoft-shops-at-walmart-for-an-operating-chief.html|website=The New York Times|date=August 5, 2005}}</ref> Turner was hired at Microsoft to lead the company's sales, marketing and services group and to instill more process and discipline in the company's operations and salesforce.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bass|first1=Dina|title=Microsoft's Nadella Reshapes Top Management as Turner Leaves|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-07/microsoft-s-nadella-reshapes-management-team-as-turner-leaves|website=Bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\nSince Bill Gates' retirement, Ballmer oversaw a \"dramatic shift away from the company's PC-first heritage\", replacing most major division heads in order to break down the \"talent-hoarding fiefdoms\", and ''[[Businessweek]]'' said that the company \"arguably now has the best product lineup in its history\". Ballmer was instrumental in driving Microsoft's connected computing strategy, with acquisitions such as [[Skype]].<ref name=\"businessweek1\" />\n\nUnder Ballmer's tenure as CEO, Microsoft's share price stagnated.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.businessinsider.com/ballmer-era-stock-price-2013-8 | title=Microsoft's Stock Chart Under The Ballmer Era}}</ref> The lackluster stock performance occurred despite Microsoft's financial success at that time. The company's annual revenue surged from $25&nbsp;billion to $70&nbsp;billion, while its net income increased 215% to $23&nbsp;billion, and its gross profit of 75 cents on every dollar in sales is double that of [[Google]] or [[IBM]].<ref name=\"wsj2\"/> In terms of leading the company's total annual profit growth, Ballmer's tenure at Microsoft (16.4%) surpassed the performances of other well-known CEOs such as [[General Electric]]'s [[Jack Welch]] (11.2%) and [[IBM]]'s [[Louis V. Gerstner Jr.]] (2%).<ref name=\"businessweek1\"/> These gains came from the existing Windows and Office franchises, with Ballmer maintaining their profitability, fending off threats from competitors such as GNU/Linux and other open-source operating systems and Google Docs.<ref name=\"newyorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/johncassidy/2013/08/microsoft-steve-ballmer-and-the-art-of-monopoly.html |title=Steve Ballmer and the Art of Managing a Monopoly - The New Yorker |publisher=newyorker.com|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> Ballmer also built half a dozen new businesses,<ref name=\"wsj2\"/> such as the data centers division and the Xbox entertainment and devices division ($8.9&nbsp;billion),<ref>{{Cite news| url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-21/microsoft-unveils-new-xbox-in-widening-home-entertainment-battle.html |title= Microsoft Unveils New Xbox in Bid to Lead Home Entertainment|author1=Dina Bass |author2=Cliff Edwards |lastauthoramp=yes |publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] |date = May 21, 2013|url-access=subscription}}</ref> (which has prevented the Sony [[PlayStation]] and other gaming consoles from undermining Windows),<ref name=\"Fortune\">[http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2013/12/11/for-steve-ballmer-a-lasting-touch-on-microsoft/?iid=SF_F_River Fortune] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216195458/http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2013/12/11/for-steve-ballmer-a-lasting-touch-on-microsoft/?iid=SF_F_River |date=December 16, 2013 }}</ref> and oversaw the acquisition of [[Skype]]. Ballmer also constructed the company's $20&nbsp;billion Enterprise Business, consisting of new products and services such as Exchange, Windows Server, SQL Server, SharePoint, System Center, and Dynamics CRM, each of which initially faced an uphill battle for acceptance but have emerged as leading or dominant in each category.<ref name=\"Fortune\"/> This diversified product mix helped to offset the company's reliance on PCs and mobile computing devices as the company entered the [[Post-PC era]]; in reporting quarterly results during April 2013, while [[Windows Phone 8]] and [[Windows 8]] had not managed to increase their market share above single digits, the company increased its profit 19% over the previous quarter in 2012, as the Microsoft Business Division (including Office 365) and Server and Tools division (cloud services) are each larger than the Windows division.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bott |first=Ed |url=https://www.zdnet.com/apple-versus-microsoft-the-ticker-tape-tells-the-tale-7000014556/ |title=Apple versus Microsoft: the ticker tape tells the tale |work=ZDNet |date=April 26, 2013 |accessdate=June 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj2\">Ovide, Shira. (August 25, 2013) [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324906304579035141246779898 \"Next CEO's Biggest Job: Fixing Microsoft's Culture\"]. ''The Wall Street Journal''. Retrieved on September 4, 2013.</ref>\n\nBallmer attracted criticism for failing to capitalize on several new consumer technologies, forcing Microsoft to play catch-up in the areas of tablet computing, smartphones and music players with mixed results.<ref name=\"businessweek1\" /><ref name=\"wsj2\" /> Under Ballmer's watch, \"In many cases, Microsoft latched onto technologies like smartphones, touchscreens, 'smart' cars and wristwatches that read sports scores aloud long before Apple or Google did. But it repeatedly killed promising projects if they threatened its cash cows [Windows and Office].\"<ref name=\"wsj2\"/> Ballmer was even named one of the worst CEOs of 2013 by the BBC.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bbc.com/capital/story/20131212-the-worst-ceos-of-2013 | title=Worst CEOs of 2013}}</ref> As a result of these many criticisms, in May 2012, hedge fund manager [[David Einhorn (hedge fund manager)|David Einhorn]] called on Ballmer to step down as CEO of Microsoft. \"His continued presence is the biggest overhang on Microsoft's stock,\" Einhorn said in reference to Ballmer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hedge Fund Star Einhorn Calls for Microsoft's Ballmer to Go|agency=Reuters|publisher=Fox Business|url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/2011/05/26/hedge-fund-star-einhorn-calls-microsofts-ballmer/#ixzz27Bx2W6m5|accessdate=September 22, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116121416/http://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/2011/05/26/hedge-fund-star-einhorn-calls-microsofts-ballmer/#ixzz27Bx2W6m5|archivedate=January 16, 2013}}</ref> In a May 2012 column in ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine, Adam Hartung described Ballmer as \"the worst CEO of a large publicly traded American company\", saying he had \"steered Microsoft out of some of the fastest growing and most lucrative tech markets (mobile music, headsets and tablets)\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/adamhartung/2012/05/12/oops-5-ceos-that-should-have-already-been-fired-cisco-ge-walmart-sears-microsoft/3/ | work=Forbes | first=Adam | last=Hartung | title=Oops! Five CEOs Who Should Have Already Been Fired (Cisco, GE, WalMart, Sears, Microsoft) - Forbes}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, and for the first time since Bill Gates resigned from day-to-day management at Microsoft, Ballmer delivered the opening keynote at [[Consumer Electronics Show|CES]].<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2009/jan/08/steve-ballmer-ces-keynote |title=Ballmer unveils Windows 7 at CES |publisher=The Guardian |date=January 8, 2009 |accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Steve Ballmer - MIX 2008.jpg|thumb|Ballmer at MIX 08 in 2008]]\n\nAs part of his plans to expand on [[Computer hardware|hardware]], on June 19, 2012, Ballmer revealed Microsoft's first ever computer device, a tablet called [[Microsoft Surface (tablet)|Microsoft Surface]] at an event held in Hollywood, Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ericsavitz/2012/06/18/microsoft-live-from-hollywood | work=Forbes | first=Eric | last=Savitz | title=Microsoft: Live From Hollywood! Introducing Microsoft Surface Tablet (Updated)}}</ref> He followed this by announcing the company's purchase of [[Nokia]]'s mobile phone division in September 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.co.uk/information-technology/2017/06/microsoft-hardware-company-steve-ballmer/|title=Steve Ballmer: We should have turned Microsoft into a \"world-class hardware company\"|publisher=}}</ref> his last major acquisition for Microsoft as CEO.\n\nOn August 23, 2013, Microsoft announced that Ballmer would retire within the next 12 months. A special committee that included Bill Gates would decide on the next CEO.<ref>Chaudhuri, Saabira (August 23, 2013). [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324165204579030611858818656 \"Microsoft CEO Steve Ballmer to Retire Within 12 Months\"]. ''The Wall Street Journal''.</ref>\n\nThere was a list of potential successors to Ballmer as Microsoft CEO, but all had departed the company: [[Jim Allchin]], [[Brad Silverberg]], [[Paul Maritz]], [[Nathan Myhrvold]], [[Greg Maffei]], [[Pete Higgins (businessman)|Pete Higgins]], [[Jeff Raikes]], [[J. Allard]], [[Robbie Bach]], [[Bill Veghte]], [[Ray Ozzie]], [[Bob Muglia]] and [[Steven Sinofsky]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Woody|first=Leonhard|title=Microsoft's 13 worst missteps of all time|url=http://www.infoworld.com/d/microsoft-windows/microsofts-13-worst-missteps-of-all-time-210521|date=January 14, 2013 |work=InfoWorld|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Leonhard |first=Woody |url=http://www.infoworld.com/t/technology-business/game-of-thrones-the-men-who-would-be-ballmer-207313 |title=Game of thrones: The men who would be Ballmer|work=InfoWorld |date=November 19, 2012 |accessdate=June 14, 2013}}</ref> [[B. Kevin Turner]], Microsoft's [[Chief Operating Officer]] (COO), was considered by some to be a ''de facto'' number two to Ballmer, with Turner having a strong grasp of business and operations but lacking technological vision.<ref>Turner, Kevin. [http://money.cnn.com/gallery/technology/2013/08/26/microsoft-ceo-ballmer-replacements.fortune/6.html \"Who will succeed Steve Ballmer at Microsoft?\"] ''Fortune'' / CNN. Retrieved September 4, 2013.</ref> On February 4, 2014, [[Satya Nadella]] succeeded Ballmer as CEO.<ref name=nadella/>\n\n===Public image===\nAlthough as a child he was so shy that he would hyperventilate before [[Hebrew school]],<ref name=\"leibovich20001231\"/> Ballmer is known for his energetic and exuberant personality, which is meant to motivate employees and partners,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2009/09/11/ballmer_iphone_bing_win_7_ad|title=Ballmer garnishes Bing 2.0 with iPhone 'stomp': Return of the Kool-Aid kid|author=Gavin Clarke|year=2009|work=The Register|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> shouting so much that he needed surgery on his vocal cords.{{r|leibovich20001231}}\n\nBallmer's flamboyant stage appearances at Microsoft events are widely circulated on the Internet as [[viral video]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.onsoftware.com/the-best-and-worst-of-barmy-steve-balmer/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100603051704/http://en.onsoftware.com/the-best-and-worst-of-barmy-steve-balmer/|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 3, 2010|title=The best and worst of barmy Steve Balmer|author=Nicholas Mead|year=2010|accessdate=November 27, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/01/06/microsoft_slate|title=Ballmer readies slate PC for CES: Monkey boy to hurl spoiler at Apple?|author=John Oates|year=2010|work=The Register|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2385972,00.asp?kc=PCRSS03079TX1K0000585|title=Microsoft Needs to Check Itself|author=John C. Dvorak|work=PC Magazine|accessdate=June 12, 2011|date=May 26, 2011}}</ref> One of his earliest known viral videos was his promotion of [[Windows 1.0]] for a [[Crazy Eddie]] commercial in 1985, where he energetically shouts \"How much do YOU think this advanced operating environment is worth? WAIT just one minute before you answer\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.laptopmag.com/articles/steve-ballmers-9-craziest-moments|title=9 Craziest Steve Ballmer Moments|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/nov/15/microsoft-windows-system-apps|title=Has Microsoft's Windows had its day?|first=Charles|last=Arthur|date=November 15, 2010|website=the Guardian}}</ref> Ballmer and [[Brian Valentine]] repeated this in a spoof promotion of [[Windows XP]] later on.<ref>Avram Piltch, Laptop Mag; 9 Craziest Steve Ballmer Moments, https://www.laptopmag.com/articles/steve-ballmers-9-craziest-moments</ref>\n\nA widely circulated video was his entrance on stage at Microsoft's 25th anniversary event in September 2000,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wallstreetinsanity.com/steve-ballmers-top-11-craziest-moments/|title=Steve Ballmer's Top 11 Craziest Moments|website=wallstreetinsanity.com}}</ref> where he shouted and jumped across the stage, and saying \"I love this company\". It has been nicknamed 'monkey boy dance'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/microsoft/8041510/Who-is-Steve-Ballmer.html|title=Who is Steve Ballmer?|first=Claudine|last=Beaumont|date=October 5, 2010|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> Another well-known viral video was one captured at a [[Windows 2000]] developers' conference, featuring a perspiring Ballmer chanting the word \"[[software developer|developers]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Wakabayashi|first=Daisuke|title=Ballmer becomes lone voice at Microsoft's helm|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2008/06/29/us-microsoft-ballmer-idUSN2634300220080629|work=Reuters|accessdate=December 6, 2012|date=June 29, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2010/03/15/ballmers-visage-evoked-for-developers-developers-developers|title=Ballmer's visage evoked for 'developers, developers, developers' demo app on Windows Phone 7 Series|author=Chris Ziegler|year=2010|work=Engadget|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Relationship with Bill Gates===\nBallmer was Gates' [[best man]] at his wedding to [[Melinda French]], and the two men described their relationship as a marriage. They were so close for years that another Microsoft executive described it as a [[mind meld]]. Combative debates\u2014a part of Microsoft's corporate culture\u2014that many observers believed were personal arguments occurred within the relationship; while Gates was glad in 2000 that Ballmer was willing to become CEO so he could focus on technology,{{r|leibovich20001231}} the ''Wall Street Journal'' reported that there was tension surrounding the transition of authority. Things became so bitter that, on one occasion, Gates stormed out of a meeting in a huff after a shouting match in which Ballmer jumped to the defense of several colleagues, according to an individual present at the time. After the exchange, Ballmer seemed \"remorseful\", the person said. Once Gates leaves, \"I'm not going to need him for anything. That's the principle\", Ballmer said. \"Use him, yes, need him, no\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121261241035146237?mod=googlenews_wsj&apl=y&r=125394|title=Gates-Ballmer Clash Shaped Microsoft's Coming Handover|author=Robert A. Guth|work=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=June 5, 2008|date=June 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, a few months after Ballmer left his post at Microsoft, a ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' profile stated that Ballmer and Gates no longer talk to each other due to animosity over Ballmer's resignation.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=McLean|first1=Bethany|title=The Empire Reboots|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/business/2014/11/satya-nadella-bill-gates-steve-ballmer-microsoft#|magazine=Vanity Fair|accessdate=October 8, 2014}}</ref> In a November 2016 interview, Ballmer said he and Gates have \"drifted apart\" ever since, saying that they always had a \"brotherly relationship\" beforehand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/why-steve-ballmer-and-bill-gates-have-drifted-apart-2016-11|title=Steve Ballmer and Bill Gates have 'drifted apart' since Ballmer left Microsoft|publisher=}}</ref> He said that his push into the hardware business, specifically [[smartphone]]s, which Gates did not support, contributed to their relationship breakdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-11-04/steve-ballmer-says-smartphones-broke-his-relationship-with-bill-gates|title=Steve Ballmer Says Smartphones Strained His Relationship With Bill Gates|date=November 4, 2016|publisher=|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nAfter saying in 2008 that he intended to remain CEO for another decade, Ballmer announced his retirement in 2013, after losing billions of dollars in acquisitions and on the Surface tablet. Microsoft's stock price rebounded on the news.<ref>[https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/08/27/ballmer_time_to_go/ \"Why Teflon Ballmer had to go: He couldn't shift crud from Windows 8, Surface\"].</ref>\n\nBallmer says that he regretted the lack of focus on [[Windows Mobile]] in the early 2000s, leaving Microsoft a distant third in the current smartphone market.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-24178512 |title=Microsoft too slow on phones, admits boss Steve Ballmer |date=September 20, 2013 |work=BBC News|accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> Moreover, he attributed the success of the expensively-priced [[iPhone]]s to carrier subsidies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.recode.net/2016/11/7/13548032/steve-ballmer-apple-iphone-bloomberg|title=Steve Ballmer says Apple's iPhone succeeded because of carrier subsidies. He's wrong.|first=Ina|last=Fried|date=November 7, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> He went on to say,{{Quote|People like to point to this quote where I said iPhones will never sell, because the price at $600 or $700 was too high. And there was a business model innovation by Apple to get it essentially built into the monthly cellphone bill.}} He called the acquisition of the mobile phone division of [[Nokia]] as his \"toughest decision\" during his tenure, as it was overseeing the changing profile of Microsoft as it was expanding on hardware.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alphr.com/news/387415/ballmer-nokia-buy-was-hardest-decision-at-microsoft|title=Ballmer: Nokia buy was hardest decision at Microsoft|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nBallmer hosted his last company meeting in September 2013,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-24301733 |title=Microsoft boss Steve Ballmer dances at tearful send-off |date=September 27, 2013|work=BBC News|accessdate=September 27, 2013}}</ref> and stepped down from the company's board of directors, in August 2014.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alex |last=Wilhelm |title=Steve Ballmer Steps Down From Microsoft's Board |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/08/19/ballmer-steps-down-from-microsofts-board/?ncid=pushup |work=Techcrunch |date=August 19, 2014 |accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn December 24, 2014, the ''[[Seattle Times]]'' reported that the [[Microsoft v. Internal Revenue Service|IRS sued]] Ballmer, [[Craig Mundie]], [[Jeff Raikes]], [[Jim Allchin]], Orlando Ayala and David Guenther in an effort to compel them to testify in Microsoft's corporate tax audit. The IRS has been looking into how Microsoft and other companies deal with [[transfer pricing]].<ref name=\"seattletimes\">{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/businesstechnology/2025308578_microsoftirsxml.html|title=IRS demands Ballmer, other Microsoft leaders testify in corporate tax audit &#124; The Seattle Times|publisher=seattletimes.com|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Other positions==\nBallmer served as director of [[Accenture]] Ltd. and a general partner of Accenture SCA from 2001 to 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsroom.accenture.com/subjects/accenture-corporate/accenture-appoints-two-new-independent-directors-to-its-board.htm|title=Accenture Appoints Two New Independent Directors to Its Board|publisher=Accenture|date=February 2, 2006|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==On competing companies and software==\n\n===Apple===\nIn 2007, Ballmer said \"There's no chance that the <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> [[iPhone]] is going to get any significant market share. No chance.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/heres-what-steve-ballmer-thought-about-the-iphone-five-years-ago-2012-6#ixzz2gnjXZ4wo |title=Here's What Steve Ballmer Thought About The iPhone Five Years Ago |website=Business Insider |date=June 29, 2012 |accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking at a conference in NYC in 2009, Ballmer criticized Apple's pricing, saying, \"Now I think the tide has turned back the other direction (against Apple). The economy is helpful. Paying an extra $500 for a computer in this environment\u2014same piece of hardware\u2014paying $500 more to get a logo on it? I think that's a more challenging proposition for the average person than it used to be.\"<ref name=\"slashgear\">{{cite news|url=http://www.slashgear.com/ballmer-critiques-apple-500-more-to-get-a-logo-2038377|title=Apple is no more than a $500 logo|date=March 20, 2009|accessdate=August 3, 2009}} [[SlashGear]]</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Ballmer called Microsoft's decision to invest in Apple to save it from [[bankruptcy]] in 1997 as the \"craziest thing we ever did\". By 2015, Apple was the world's most valuable company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/microsofts-biggest-mistake-investing-apple-was-craziest-thing-we-ever-did-1525752|title=Microsoft's biggest mistake: Investing in Apple was the 'craziest thing we ever did'|first=James|last=Billington|date=October 26, 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Ballmer did an interview with Bloomberg where Ballmer added context to his [[iPhone]] statement, saying \"People like to point to this quote...but the reason I said that was the price of $600-$700 was too high\", he says he did not realize the business model innovation that Apple was going to deploy, using the carriers to subsidize the phones by building the cost into the customer's monthly bill.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qFe0S3F389w</ref>\n\n===Free and open source software===\nIn July 2000, Ballmer called the [[free software]] [[Linux kernel]] \"[[communism]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2000/07/31/ms_ballmer_linux_is_communism/|title=MS' Ballmer: Linux is communism|publisher=}}</ref> and further claimed that it infringed with Microsoft's intellectual property.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/ballmer-linux-infringes-our-intellectual-property/|title=Ballmer: Linux \"Infringes our intellectual property\" - ZDNet|first=Adrian|last=Kingsley-Hughes|publisher=}}</ref> In June 2001 he called Linux a \"cancer that attaches itself in an intellectual property sense to everything it touches\".<ref name=\"viral\">{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20011211130654/http://www.suntimes.com/output/tech/cst-fin-micro01.html |date=December 11, 2001 |title=Microsoft CEO takes launch break with the Sun-Times }}, ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', June 1, 2001; archived from the [http://www.suntimes.com/output/tech/cst-fin-micro01.html original] on December 11, 2001; retrieved December 18, 2009.</ref> Ballmer used the notion of [[viral license|\"viral\" licensing terms]] to express his concern over the fact that the [[GNU General Public License]] (GPL) employed by such software requires that all derivative software be under the GPL or a compatible license. In April 2003 he even interrupted his skiing holiday in [[Switzerland]] to personally plead with the mayor of [[Munich]] not to switch to GNU/Linux.<ref name=\"Munich1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/munich-breaks-with-windows-for-linux/|title=Munich breaks with Windows for Linux|newspaper=CNET|access-date=November 23, 2016}}</ref> But he did not succeed with this and Munich switched to [[LiMux]], despite his offering a 35% discount at his [[lobbying|lobbying visit]].<ref name=\"Munich2\">{{Cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/industries/technology/2003-07-13-microsoft-linux-munich_x.htm|title=Linux took on Microsoft, and won big in Munich|newspaper=USAtoday|access-date=November 28, 2016}}</ref> Munich has since backtracked on using LiMux; in November 2017, the Munich City Council resolved to reverse the migration and return to Microsoft Windows-based software by 2020.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Heath|first1=Nick|title=Linux pioneer Munich supports Windows 10 rollout from 2020 in key vote|url=https://www.techrepublic.com/article/linux-pioneer-munich-supports-windows-10-rollout-from-2020-in-key-vote/|website=TechRepublic|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=March 13, 2018|date=November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Ballmer changed his stance on Linux, saying that he supports his successor [[Satya Nadella]]'s [[Open-source model|open source]] commitments. He maintained that his comments in 2001 were right at the time but that times have changed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.informationweek.com/software/ballmer-linux-no-longer-a-cancer--/d/d-id/1324661|title=Ballmer: Linux No Longer A Cancer - InformationWeek|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.silicon.co.uk/software/open-source/steve-ballmer-linux-microsoft-187802?inf_by=5a088e9d671db8d83d8b4959|title=Steve Ballmer: Linux Is No Longer 'A Cancer'|date=March 11, 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Google===\nIn 2005, Microsoft sued Google for hiring one of its previous vice presidents, [[Kai-Fu Lee]], claiming it was in violation of his one-year non-compete clause in his contract. [[Mark Lucovsky]], who left for Google in 2004, alleged in a sworn statement to a Washington state court that Ballmer became enraged upon hearing that Lucovsky was about to leave Microsoft for [[Google]], picked up his chair, and threw it across his office, and that, referring to then Google Executive Chairman [[Eric Schmidt]] (who had previously worked for competitors Sun and Novell), Ballmer vowed to \"kill Google.\"<ref name=\"Heats up\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/4213466.stm | work=BBC News | title=Microsoft-Google battle heats up | date=September 4, 2005}}</ref> Lucovsky reports:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2005/09/05/chair_chucking/|title=Microsoft's Ballmer: Chair-tossing potty-mouth|work=The Register|author=John Oates|date=September 5, 2005|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|At some point in the conversation Mr. Ballmer said: \"Just tell me it's not Google.\" I told him it was Google. At that point, Mr. Ballmer picked up a chair and threw it across the room hitting a table in his office. Mr. Ballmer then said: \"Fucking Eric Schmidt is a fucking pussy. I'm going to fucking bury that guy, I have done it before, and I will do it again. I'm going to fucking kill Google.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/08/24/top_10_steve_ballmer_quotes_from_microsoft_history/|title=Top 10 Steve Ballmer quotes: '%#&@!!' and so much more|website=The Register|date=August 24, 2013|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nBallmer then resumed attempting to persuade Lucovsky to stay at Microsoft. Ballmer has described Lucovsky's account of the incident as a \"gross exaggeration of what actually took place\".<ref name=\"Heats up\" />\n\nDuring the 2011 [[Web 2.0 Summit]] in San Francisco, he said: \"You don't need to be a computer scientist to use a Windows Phone and you do to use an Android phone&nbsp;... It is hard for me to be excited about the Android phones.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://androidandme.com/2011/10/news/steve-ballmer-android-is-for-computer-science-geeks/ |title=Steve Ballmer: Android is for computer science geeks |publisher=Android and Me |date=October 19, 2011 |accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MTX1e-pMN6E |title=Microsoft's Ballmer mocks Android phone |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Ballmer said that Google was a \"[[monopoly]]\" that should be pressured from market competition authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/9/20/4751516/ballmer-calls-google-a-monopoly|title=Ballmer calls Google a 'monopoly' that authorities should control|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nBallmer sadly died after juju'ing on that beat.\n\n==Sports==\nOn March 6, 2008, [[List of mayors of Seattle|Seattle mayor]] [[Greg Nickels]] announced that a local ownership group involving Ballmer made a \"game-changing\" commitment to invest $150&nbsp;million in cash toward a proposed $300&nbsp;million renovation of [[KeyArena]] and were ready to purchase the [[Seattle SuperSonics]] from the [[Professional Basketball Club LLC]] in order to keep the team in Seattle. However, this initiative failed, and the SuperSonics [[Seattle SuperSonics relocation to Oklahoma City|relocated]] to [[Oklahoma City]], [[Oklahoma]], where they now play as the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.seattle.gov/news/detail.asp?ID=8243&dept=40 |title=Mayor Nickels announces local effort to buy Sonics, renovate KeyArena |publisher=Seattle.gov |date= |accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, Ballmer was an investor in [[Chris R. Hansen]]'s [[Sonics Arena|proposal to build a new arena]] in the [[SoDo, Seattle|SoDo neighborhood]] of Seattle and bring the SuperSonics back to Seattle.<ref>{{cite news | last = Thompson | first = Lynn and Young, Bob | title = Ballmer, Nordstroms part of Seattle arena investor group | pages = | newspaper = The Seattle Times | date = June 13, 2012 | url = http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2018421214_arena14m.html}}</ref> On January 9, 2013, Ballmer and Hansen led a group of investors in an attempt to purchase the [[Sacramento Kings]] from the [[Maloof family]] and [[Failed Relocation of the Sacramento Kings#Seattle|relocate]] them to Seattle for an estimated $650&nbsp;million. However, this attempt also fell through.<ref>espn.com, [http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/11005695/seattle-bid-nba-team-dealt-blow-steve-ballmer-agrees-purchase-los-angeles-clippers Clippers name has to go with Sterling], accessed May 30, 2014.</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Donald Sterling#Racial remarks and lifetime ban|Donald Sterling scandal]] in May 2014, Ballmer was the highest bidder in an attempt to purchase the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] for a reported price of $2&nbsp;billion, which is the second highest bid for a sports franchise in North American sports history (after the $2.15&nbsp;billion sale of the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] in 2012). After a California court confirmed the authority of [[Shelly Sterling]] to sell the team, it was officially announced on August 12, 2014, that Ballmer would become the Los Angeles Clippers owner.<ref name=\"nbcnews\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/sports/steve-ballmer-takes-over-ownership-los-angeles-clippers-n178761 |title=Steve Ballmer Takes Over Ownership of Los Angeles Clippers - NBC News |publisher=nbcnews.com|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2014, Ballmer said he would bar the team from using [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] products such as [[iPad]]s, and replace them with Microsoft products.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/nba/2014/9/25/6844451/steve-ballmer-clippers-apple-ban-policy-microsoft-nba-2014|title=Ballmer wants Clippers to ban Apple products|publisher=}}</ref> It has been reported that he had previously also barred his family from using iPhones.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Maddaus |first1=Gene |title=Steve Ballmer To Ban L.A. Clippers From Using Apple Products |url=https://www.laweekly.com/steve-ballmer-to-ban-l-a-clippers-from-using-apple-products/ |website=LA Weekly |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |date=September 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Ballmer agreed to buy [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]] in [[Inglewood, California]].<ref name=\"The Forum\">{{cite web |last1=Greif |first1=Andrew |title=Clippers buy Forum for $400 million, clearing way for new arena construction |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/clippers/story/2020-03-24/ballmer-clippers-buy-forum-from-msg-for-400-million-dollars |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The purchase would allow him to build a new arena for the Clippers in the nearby area since plans for a new Clippers' arena were opposed by the former owners of The Forum.<ref name=\"The Forum\" />\n\n==Wealth==\nBallmer was the second person after [[Roberto Goizueta]] to become a [[billionaire]] in U.S. dollars based on [[employee stock option|stock options]] received as an employee of a [[corporation]] in which he was neither a founder nor a relative of a founder. {{as of|2017|12|11|df=US}}, his personal wealth is estimated at US$37.1&nbsp;billion.<ref name=FSB /> While CEO of Microsoft in 2009, Ballmer earned a total compensation of $1,276,627, which included a base salary of $665,833, a cash bonus of $600,000, no stock or options, and other compensation of $10,794.\n\n==Philanthropy==\nOn November 12, 2014, it was announced that Ballmer and his wife Connie donated $50&nbsp;million to the [[University of Oregon]]. Connie Ballmer is a University of Oregon alumna and serves on the institution's [[Board of Trustees of the University of Oregon|board of trustees]]. The funds will go towards the university's $2&nbsp;billion fundraising effort, and will focus towards scholarships, public health research and advocacy, and external branding/communications.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Klinger|first1=Tobin|title=UO announces $50 million gift to fundraising campaign|url=http://around.uoregon.edu/content/uo-announces-50-million-gift-fundraising-campaign|publisher=AroundtheO|accessdate=November 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn November 13, 2014, it was announced that Ballmer would provide a gift, estimated at $60 million, to Harvard University's computer science department. The gift would allow the department to hire new faculty, and hopefully increase the national stature of the program. Ballmer previously donated $10 million to the same department in 1994, in a joint-gift with [[Bill Gates]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shu|first1=Catherine|title=Steve Ballmer's Harvard Donation Will Allow It To Add 12 New Computer Science PROFESSORS PROFESSORS PROFESSORS|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/11/12/steve-ballmer-harvard/|accessdate=November 14, 2014|work=TechCrunch}}</ref>\n\nBallmer serves on the World Chairman's Council of the [[Jewish National Fund]], which means he has donated US$1 million or more to the JNF.<ref name=\"jnfworldschairmancouncil\">{{cite web|title=World's Chairman Council|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912093518/http://www.jnf.org/assets/pdf/world-chairman-s-council-ad.pdf |website=Jewish National Fund}}</ref>\n\n==USAFacts==\nBallmer launched [[USAFacts.org]] in 2017, a non-profit organization whose goal is to allow people to understand US government revenue, spending and societal impact. He is reported to have contributed $10 million to fund teams of researchers who populated the website's database with official data.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/steve-ballmers-usafacts-site-surfaces-government-spending/|title=Steve Ballmer's USAFacts Site Surfaces Government Spending|last=Goldman|first=Joshua|website=CNet|accessdate=April 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/21/we-need-more-projects-like-usafacts/|title=Steve Ballmer's US data trove isn't the first, but may be the best|work=Engadget|access-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/editorials/sd-steve-ballmer-website-usafacts-20170808-story.html|title=Steve Ballmer has a website that could change government|last=Board|first=The San Diego Union-Tribune Editorial|work=sandiegouniontribune.com|access-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1990, Ballmer married Connie Snyder;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailyentertainmentnews.com/?p=14842|title=Steve Ballmer and wife Connie Ballmer|publisher=Daily Entertainment News|date=March 1, 2013}}</ref> they have three sons.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/jun/27/microsoft.microsoft The Guardian: \"Loyalty is his number one strength. He still drives Ford cars because his father used to work for the company\" by Bobbie Johnson] June 28, 2008</ref>\n\nThe Ballmers live in [[Hunts Point, Washington]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/102032526#|title=Former Microsoft CEO and LA Clippers Owner Steve Ballmer Speaks with CNBC's Josh Lipton Today | first=Josh | last=Lipton | publisher=[[CNBC]] | date=September 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/exec/steve/default.aspx Corporate biography]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7lhlKF6MECs, CS50 Lecture by Steve Ballmer at [[Harvard University]], November 2014]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110430024247/http://streaming.scmp.com/podcasting/upload/tech_may24.mp3 South China Morning Post audio interview]\n* [http://web.mit.edu/echemi/www/ballmer.html Steve Ballmer Playlist] Appearance on WMBR's ''[http://web.mit.edu/echemi/www/index.html Dinnertime Sampler]'' radio show February 23, 2005\n* [https://www.forbes.com/profile/steve-ballmer/ Forbes Profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Bill Gates]] | title = Chief Executive Officer of [[Microsoft]] | years = 2000\u20132014 | after = [[Satya Nadella]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Microsoft}}\n{{Los Angeles Clippers}}\n{{NBAOwners}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Sports}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ballmer, Steve}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American chief operating officers]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American Internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:American people of Belarusian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Swiss descent]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Seattle]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Detroit Country Day School alumni]]\n[[Category:Directors of Microsoft]]\n[[Category:Harvard Crimson alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Advocate alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Clippers owners]]\n[[Category:Microsoft employees]]\n[[Category:People from Farmington Hills, Michigan]]\n[[Category:People from Hunts Point, Washington]]\n[[Category:Stanford University students]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman and investor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Steve Ballmer\n| image = Steve Ballmer 2014.jpg\n| caption = Ballmer in 2014\n| birth_name = Steven Anthony Ballmer\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1956|3|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n| education = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Stanford Graduate School of Business]]\n| net_worth = [[US$]]51.9 billion (October 2019)<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/steve-ballmer/?list=billionaires |title=Steve Ballmer|magazine=Forbes}}</ref>\n| spouse = {{marriage|Connie Snyder|1990}}\n| children = 3\n| awards = [[Legion of Honour]]<ref>{{YouTube|IYKjFfkqBmo|Sarkozy fait Steve Ballmer chevalier de la L\u00e9gion d'honneur}}, AFP</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Steven Anthony Ballmer''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u0254\u02d0|l|m|\u0259r}}; born March 24, 1956)<ref name=\"cnnbio\">{{cite web | url = http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/08/us/steve-ballmer-fast-facts/ | title= Steve Ballmer Fast Facts | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=March 11, 2015|accessdate= January 28, 2016}}</ref><!--CNN cite also verifies birth name Steven Anthony Ballmer--> is an [[United States|American]] businessman and investor who was the [[chief executive officer]] of [[Microsoft]] from January 13, 2000,<ref name=\"ms bio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.microsoft.com/presspass/exec/steve/default.mspx|title=Steve Ballmer: Chief Executive Officer|date=March 1, 2005|publisher=Microsoft|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080203132040/http://www.microsoft.com/Presspass/exec/steve/default.mspx|archivedate=February 3, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> to February 4, 2014,<ref name=\"cnnbio\" /> and is the current owner of the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). {{As of|2019|10|df=US}}, his personal wealth is estimated at US $51.9&nbsp;billion,<ref name=\"FSB\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/steve-ballmer/?list=billionaires|title=Steve Ballmer|work=Forbes|accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref> ranking him the 16th richest person in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/billionaires/list/#version:static|title=Forbes 400|work=Forbes|accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBallmer was hired by [[Bill Gates]] at Microsoft in 1980 and subsequently left the MBA program at [[Stanford University]]. He eventually became President in 1998, and replaced Gates as CEO in 2000. On February 4, 2014, Ballmer retired as CEO and resigned from the Board of Directors on August 19, 2014 to prepare for teaching a new class.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/press/2013/aug13/08-23announcementpr.aspx|title=Microsoft CEO Steve Ballmer to retire within 12 months.|last=|first=|date=August 23, 2013|website=|publisher=Microsoft|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824142520/http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/press/2013/aug13/08-23AnnouncementPR.aspx|archive-date=August 24, 2013|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"nadella\">{{cite web|url=https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/press/2014/feb14/02-04newspr.aspx|title=Microsoft Board names Satya Nadella as CEO|date=February 4, 2014|publisher=Microsoft|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204183103/http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/press/2014/feb14/02-04newspr.aspx|archive-date=February 4, 2014|url-status=}}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, 2014, Ballmer placed a bid of $2&nbsp;billion to purchase the NBA's Los Angeles Clippers after NBA commissioner [[Adam Silver]] forced [[Donald Sterling]] to sell the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2014/news/05/29/clippers-bids.ap/index.html|title=Report: Ex-Microsoft CEO Ballmer willing to pay $2B for Clips|publisher=NBA.com|date=May 29, 2014|accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> He became the Clippers owner on August 12, 2014; Microsoft co-founder [[Paul Allen]] was a fellow owner in the NBA, having owned the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] since 1988.\n\nHis [[Steve Ballmer#History with Microsoft|tenure and legacy as Microsoft CEO]] has received mixed reception, with the company tripling sales and doubling of profits, but losing its market dominance and missing out on [[21st century skills|21st-century technology trends]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/10/25/why-tim-cook-is-steve-ballmer/|title=Why Tim Cook is Steve Ballmer|date=October 26, 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/business/2012/08/microsoft-lost-mojo-steve-ballmer|title=How Microsoft Lost Its Mojo: Steve Ballmer and Corporate America's Most Spectacular Decline|first=Kurt|last=Eichenwald|website=The Hive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-microsoft-ballmer-newsmaker/steve-ballmer-ends-run-as-microsofts-relentless-salesman-idUSBRE97M0YV20130823|title=Steve Ballmer ends run as Microsoft's relentless salesman|first=Bill|last=Rigby|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBallmer was born in [[Detroit]]; he is the son of Beatrice Dworkin and Frederic Henry Ballmer (Fritz Hans Ballmer),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bernerzeitung.ch/basel/land/MicrosoftChef-Vorfahren-waren-Schweizer-die-in-Hoehlen-wohnten/story/20870798|title=Microsoft-Chef: Vorfahren waren Schweizer, \"die in H\u00f6hlen wohnten\"|date=October 12, 2009|website=Berner Zeitung|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401065424/http://www.bernerzeitung.ch/basel/land/MicrosoftChef-Vorfahren-waren-Schweizer-die-in-Hoehlen-wohnten/story/20870798|archivedate=April 1, 2015 |access-date=April 8, 2016}}</ref> a manager at the [[Ford Motor Company]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/internationaldir0000unse |url-access=registration |quote=Family: Son of Frederic Henry Ballmer (manager. |title=International directory of business biographies |authors=Neil Schlager, Vanessa Torrado-Caputo, Margaret Mazurkiewicz, and Schlager Group |publisher=St. James Press |date= |accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref> His father was a Swiss immigrant who predicted that his son, at eight years old, would attend Harvard. His mother was [[History of the Jews in Belarus|Belarusian Jewish]].<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Summary: Bad Boy Ballmer - Fredric Maxwell: The man who rules Microsoft|author=Publishing, B.N.|date=2013|publisher=Must Read Summaries|isbn=9782806224927|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qMmWzuB27uUC&pg=PT5|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>{{r|leibovich20001231}} Through his mother, Ballmer is a second cousin of actress and comedian [[Gilda Radner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19980125&slug=2730718|title=Business - Microsoft's Heir Apparent -- Steve Ballmer - Seattle Times Newspaper|publisher=}}</ref> Ballmer grew up in the affluent community of [[Farmington Hills, Michigan|Farmington Hills]], [[Michigan]]. Ballmer also lived in Brussels from 1964 to 1967, where he attended the [[International School of Brussels]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Ballmer lived in Brussels!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zvcPlwKrquM|accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> In 1973, he attended college prep and engineering classes at [[Lawrence Technological University]]. He graduated valedictorian from [[Detroit Country Day School]], a private [[university-preparatory school|college preparatory school]] in [[Beverly Hills, Michigan|Beverly Hills]], [[Michigan]], with a score of 800 on the mathematical section of the [[SAT]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.woopidoo.com/biography/steve-ballmer/index.htm |title=Steve Ballmer Biography - Microsoft CEO |publisher=Woopidoo.com |date=March 24, 1956 |accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/28/business/yourmoney/28ballmer.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | first=Steve | last=Lohr | title=Preaching From the Ballmer Pulpit | date=January 28, 2007}}</ref> and was a [[National Merit Scholarship Program|National Merit Scholar]].<ref name=\"nationalmerit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalmerit.org/s/1758/interior.aspx?sid=1758&gid=2&pgid=416 |title=National Merit Scholarship Corporation - Scholars You May Know |publisher=nationalmerit.org|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> He now sits on the school's [[board of directors]]. In 1977, he graduated ''[[magna cum laude]]'' from [[Harvard College|Harvard University]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[applied mathematics]] and [[economics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.woopidoo.com/biography/steve-ballmer/ |title=Steve Ballmer Biography - Microsoft CEO |publisher=Woopidoo.com |accessdate=June 14, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/04/08/us/steve-ballmer-fast-facts/|title=\nSteve Ballmer Fast Facts|date=April 2, 2017|work=CNN Library|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nAt college, Ballmer was a manager for the [[Harvard Crimson football]] team and a member of the [[Fox Club (Harvard)|Fox Club]], worked on ''[[The Harvard Crimson]]'' newspaper as well as the ''[[Harvard Advocate]]'', and lived down the hall from fellow sophomore [[Bill Gates]]. He scored highly in the [[William Lowell Putnam Mathematical Competition]], an exam sponsored by the [[Mathematical Association of America]], scoring higher than Bill Gates.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/28/business/yourmoney/28ballmer.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first=Steve | last=Lohr | title=Preaching From the Ballmer Pulpit | date=January 28, 2007}}</ref> He then worked as an assistant product manager at [[Procter & Gamble]] for two years, where he shared an office with [[Jeffrey R. Immelt]], who later became CEO of [[General Electric]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/companies/management/2007-04-29-ballmer-ceo-forum-usat_N.htm|work=[[USA Today]]|title=CEO Forum: Microsoft's Ballmer having a 'great time{{'-}}|author=David Lieberman|date=April 29, 2007|quote=First job: Assistant product manager for [[Duncan Hines]]' Moist & Easy cakes and brownies. His cubicle mate was Jeffrey Immelt, now CEO of General Electric.}}</ref> After briefly trying to write screenplays in Hollywood,<ref name=\"leibovich20001231\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/2000/12/31/alter-egos/91b267b0-858c-4d4e-a4bd-48f22e015f70/ |title=Alter Egos |last=Leibovich |first=Mark |date=December 31, 2000 |work=Washington Post |access-date=June 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225224631/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/2000/12/31/alter-egos/91b267b0-858c-4d4e-a4bd-48f22e015f70/ |archive-date=December 25, 2016 |issn=0190-8286 | url-access=subscription}}</ref> in 1980 Ballmer dropped out of the [[Stanford Graduate School of Business]] to join Microsoft.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/02_24/b3787001.htm|work=[[BusinessWeek]]|title=Ballmer's Microsoft|first1=Jay |last1=Greene |first2=Steve |last2=Hamm |first3=Jim |last3=Kerstetter |date=June 17, 2002|quote=After two years, Ballmer headed for Stanford University's MBA program for a better grounding in business. When the fledgling Microsoft ran into problems in 1980, Gates persuaded his friend to drop out and give him a hand.}}</ref>\n\n==History with Microsoft==\nBallmer joined [[Microsoft]] on June 11, 1980, and became Microsoft's 30th employee, the first business manager hired by Gates.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Ballmer: Chief Executive Officer|url=https://www.microsoft.com/presspass/exec/steve/default.aspx?tab=biography}}</ref>\n\nBallmer was offered a salary of $50,000 as well as 5-10% of the company.{{r|leibovich20001231}} When Microsoft was incorporated in 1981, Ballmer owned 8% of the company. In 2003, Ballmer sold 39.3 million Microsoft shares equating to approximately $955 million, thereby reducing his ownership to 4%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2003/may/28/1|title=Microsoft chief calms investors after selling shares|newspaper=The Guardian|date=May 28, 2003|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref> The same year, he replaced Microsoft's [[employee stock option]]s program.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/2003/07/08/cx_aw_0708msft.html|title=Microsoft Loses Its Options|work=Forbes|date=July 8, 2003|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the 20 years following his hire, Ballmer headed several Microsoft divisions, including operations, operating systems development, and sales and support. From February 1992 onwards, he was Executive Vice President, Sales, and Support. Ballmer led Microsoft's development of the [[.NET Framework]]. Ballmer was then promoted to President of Microsoft, a title that he held from July 1998 to February 2001, making him the de facto number two in the company to the chairman and CEO, Bill Gates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/microsoft/10262853/Microsoft-the-ups-and-downs-of-the-Ballmer-era.html |title=Microsoft: the ups and downs of the Ballmer era |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=August 23, 2013 |accessdate=January 17, 2014 |location=London |first=Sophie |last=Curtis}}</ref>\n\n===Chief Executive Officer (2000\u20132014)===\n[[File:Steve Ballmer MWC 2010.jpg|thumb|upright|Steve Ballmer at Mobile World Congress 2010]]\n\nOn January 13, 2000, Ballmer was officially named the chief executive officer.<ref name=\"ms bio\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/602708.stm|title=Steve Ballmer, friend of Bill|work=BBC News|date=January 13, 2000|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref> As CEO, Ballmer handled company finances and daily operations, but Gates remained chairman of the board and still retained control of the \"technological vision\" as chief software architect.<ref>{{cite web|last=Farber|first=Dan|date=August 26, 2013|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-10805_3-57600098-75/bill-gates-steve-ballmer-and-the-parting-of-the-ways/|title=Bill Gates, Steve Ballmer and the Parting of the Ways|website=CNET News|accessdate=September 4, 2013}}</ref> Gates relinquished day-to-day activities when he stepped down as chief software architect in 2006, while staying on as chairman, and that gave Ballmer the autonomy needed to make major management changes at Microsoft.<ref name=\"businessweek1\">{{cite news|last=Vance |first=Ashlee |url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/steve-ballmer-reboots-01122012.html |title=Steve Ballmer Reboots |work=Businessweek |date=January 12, 2012 |accessdate=June 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhen Ballmer took over as CEO, the company was fighting an antitrust lawsuit brought on by the U.S. government and 20 states, plus class-action lawsuits and complaints from rival companies. While it was said that Gates would have continued fighting the suit, Ballmer made it his priority to settle these saying: \"Being the object of a lawsuit, effectively, or a complaint from your government is a very awkward, uncomfortable position to be in. It just has all downside. People assume if the government brought a complaint that there's really a problem, and your ability to say we're a good, proper, moral place is tough. It's actually tough, even though you feel that way about yourselves.\"<ref name=\"tech.fortune.cnn.com\">{{cite news| url=http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2013/12/11/for-steve-ballmer-a-lasting-touch-on-microsoft/?iid=SF_F_River | work=CNN | title=For Steve Ballmer, a lasting touch on Microsoft}}</ref>\n\nUpon becoming CEO, Ballmer required detailed business justification in order to approve of new products, rather than allowing hundreds of products that sounded potentially interesting or trendy. In 2005, he recruited [[B. Kevin Turner]] from [[Walmart]], who was the President and CEO of [[Sam's Club]], to become Microsoft's Chief Operating Officer.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lohr|first1=Steve|title=Microsoft Shops at Wal-Mart for an Operating Chief|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/05/technology/microsoft-shops-at-walmart-for-an-operating-chief.html|website=The New York Times|date=August 5, 2005}}</ref> Turner was hired at Microsoft to lead the company's sales, marketing and services group and to instill more process and discipline in the company's operations and salesforce.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bass|first1=Dina|title=Microsoft's Nadella Reshapes Top Management as Turner Leaves|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-07/microsoft-s-nadella-reshapes-management-team-as-turner-leaves|website=Bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\nSince Bill Gates' retirement, Ballmer oversaw a \"dramatic shift away from the company's PC-first heritage\", replacing most major division heads in order to break down the \"talent-hoarding fiefdoms\", and ''[[Businessweek]]'' said that the company \"arguably now has the best product lineup in its history\". Ballmer was instrumental in driving Microsoft's connected computing strategy, with acquisitions such as [[Skype]].<ref name=\"businessweek1\" />\n\nUnder Ballmer's tenure as CEO, Microsoft's share price stagnated.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.businessinsider.com/ballmer-era-stock-price-2013-8 | title=Microsoft's Stock Chart Under The Ballmer Era}}</ref> The lackluster stock performance occurred despite Microsoft's financial success at that time. The company's annual revenue surged from $25&nbsp;billion to $70&nbsp;billion, while its net income increased 215% to $23&nbsp;billion, and its gross profit of 75 cents on every dollar in sales is double that of [[Google]] or [[IBM]].<ref name=\"wsj2\"/> In terms of leading the company's total annual profit growth, Ballmer's tenure at Microsoft (16.4%) surpassed the performances of other well-known CEOs such as [[General Electric]]'s [[Jack Welch]] (11.2%) and [[IBM]]'s [[Louis V. Gerstner Jr.]] (2%).<ref name=\"businessweek1\"/> These gains came from the existing Windows and Office franchises, with Ballmer maintaining their profitability, fending off threats from competitors such as GNU/Linux and other open-source operating systems and Google Docs.<ref name=\"newyorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/johncassidy/2013/08/microsoft-steve-ballmer-and-the-art-of-monopoly.html |title=Steve Ballmer and the Art of Managing a Monopoly - The New Yorker |publisher=newyorker.com|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref> Ballmer also built half a dozen new businesses,<ref name=\"wsj2\"/> such as the data centers division and the Xbox entertainment and devices division ($8.9&nbsp;billion),<ref>{{Cite news| url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-21/microsoft-unveils-new-xbox-in-widening-home-entertainment-battle.html |title= Microsoft Unveils New Xbox in Bid to Lead Home Entertainment|author1=Dina Bass |author2=Cliff Edwards |lastauthoramp=yes |publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] |date = May 21, 2013|url-access=subscription}}</ref> (which has prevented the Sony [[PlayStation]] and other gaming consoles from undermining Windows),<ref name=\"Fortune\">[http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2013/12/11/for-steve-ballmer-a-lasting-touch-on-microsoft/?iid=SF_F_River Fortune] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216195458/http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2013/12/11/for-steve-ballmer-a-lasting-touch-on-microsoft/?iid=SF_F_River |date=December 16, 2013 }}</ref> and oversaw the acquisition of [[Skype]]. Ballmer also constructed the company's $20&nbsp;billion Enterprise Business, consisting of new products and services such as Exchange, Windows Server, SQL Server, SharePoint, System Center, and Dynamics CRM, each of which initially faced an uphill battle for acceptance but have emerged as leading or dominant in each category.<ref name=\"Fortune\"/> This diversified product mix helped to offset the company's reliance on PCs and mobile computing devices as the company entered the [[Post-PC era]]; in reporting quarterly results during April 2013, while [[Windows Phone 8]] and [[Windows 8]] had not managed to increase their market share above single digits, the company increased its profit 19% over the previous quarter in 2012, as the Microsoft Business Division (including Office 365) and Server and Tools division (cloud services) are each larger than the Windows division.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bott |first=Ed |url=https://www.zdnet.com/apple-versus-microsoft-the-ticker-tape-tells-the-tale-7000014556/ |title=Apple versus Microsoft: the ticker tape tells the tale |work=ZDNet |date=April 26, 2013 |accessdate=June 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj2\">Ovide, Shira. (August 25, 2013) [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324906304579035141246779898 \"Next CEO's Biggest Job: Fixing Microsoft's Culture\"]. ''The Wall Street Journal''. Retrieved on September 4, 2013.</ref>\n\nBallmer attracted criticism for failing to capitalize on several new consumer technologies, forcing Microsoft to play catch-up in the areas of tablet computing, smartphones and music players with mixed results.<ref name=\"businessweek1\" /><ref name=\"wsj2\" /> Under Ballmer's watch, \"In many cases, Microsoft latched onto technologies like smartphones, touchscreens, 'smart' cars and wristwatches that read sports scores aloud long before Apple or Google did. But it repeatedly killed promising projects if they threatened its cash cows [Windows and Office].\"<ref name=\"wsj2\"/> Ballmer was even named one of the worst CEOs of 2013 by the BBC.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bbc.com/capital/story/20131212-the-worst-ceos-of-2013 | title=Worst CEOs of 2013}}</ref> As a result of these many criticisms, in May 2012, hedge fund manager [[David Einhorn (hedge fund manager)|David Einhorn]] called on Ballmer to step down as CEO of Microsoft. \"His continued presence is the biggest overhang on Microsoft's stock,\" Einhorn said in reference to Ballmer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hedge Fund Star Einhorn Calls for Microsoft's Ballmer to Go|agency=Reuters|publisher=Fox Business|url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/2011/05/26/hedge-fund-star-einhorn-calls-microsofts-ballmer/#ixzz27Bx2W6m5|accessdate=September 22, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116121416/http://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/2011/05/26/hedge-fund-star-einhorn-calls-microsofts-ballmer/#ixzz27Bx2W6m5|archivedate=January 16, 2013}}</ref> In a May 2012 column in ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine, Adam Hartung described Ballmer as \"the worst CEO of a large publicly traded American company\", saying he had \"steered Microsoft out of some of the fastest growing and most lucrative tech markets (mobile music, headsets and tablets)\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/adamhartung/2012/05/12/oops-5-ceos-that-should-have-already-been-fired-cisco-ge-walmart-sears-microsoft/3/ | work=Forbes | first=Adam | last=Hartung | title=Oops! Five CEOs Who Should Have Already Been Fired (Cisco, GE, WalMart, Sears, Microsoft) - Forbes}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, and for the first time since Bill Gates resigned from day-to-day management at Microsoft, Ballmer delivered the opening keynote at [[Consumer Electronics Show|CES]].<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2009/jan/08/steve-ballmer-ces-keynote |title=Ballmer unveils Windows 7 at CES |publisher=The Guardian |date=January 8, 2009 |accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Steve Ballmer - MIX 2008.jpg|thumb|Ballmer at MIX 08 in 2008]]\n\nAs part of his plans to expand on [[Computer hardware|hardware]], on June 19, 2012, Ballmer revealed Microsoft's first ever computer device, a tablet called [[Microsoft Surface (tablet)|Microsoft Surface]] at an event held in Hollywood, Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ericsavitz/2012/06/18/microsoft-live-from-hollywood | work=Forbes | first=Eric | last=Savitz | title=Microsoft: Live From Hollywood! Introducing Microsoft Surface Tablet (Updated)}}</ref> He followed this by announcing the company's purchase of [[Nokia]]'s mobile phone division in September 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.co.uk/information-technology/2017/06/microsoft-hardware-company-steve-ballmer/|title=Steve Ballmer: We should have turned Microsoft into a \"world-class hardware company\"|publisher=}}</ref> his last major acquisition for Microsoft as CEO.\n\nOn August 23, 2013, Microsoft announced that Ballmer would retire within the next 12 months. A special committee that included Bill Gates would decide on the next CEO.<ref>Chaudhuri, Saabira (August 23, 2013). [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324165204579030611858818656 \"Microsoft CEO Steve Ballmer to Retire Within 12 Months\"]. ''The Wall Street Journal''.</ref>\n\nThere was a list of potential successors to Ballmer as Microsoft CEO, but all had departed the company: [[Jim Allchin]], [[Brad Silverberg]], [[Paul Maritz]], [[Nathan Myhrvold]], [[Greg Maffei]], [[Pete Higgins (businessman)|Pete Higgins]], [[Jeff Raikes]], [[J. Allard]], [[Robbie Bach]], [[Bill Veghte]], [[Ray Ozzie]], [[Bob Muglia]] and [[Steven Sinofsky]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Woody|first=Leonhard|title=Microsoft's 13 worst missteps of all time|url=http://www.infoworld.com/d/microsoft-windows/microsofts-13-worst-missteps-of-all-time-210521|date=January 14, 2013 |work=InfoWorld|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Leonhard |first=Woody |url=http://www.infoworld.com/t/technology-business/game-of-thrones-the-men-who-would-be-ballmer-207313 |title=Game of thrones: The men who would be Ballmer|work=InfoWorld |date=November 19, 2012 |accessdate=June 14, 2013}}</ref> [[B. Kevin Turner]], Microsoft's [[Chief Operating Officer]] (COO), was considered by some to be a ''de facto'' number two to Ballmer, with Turner having a strong grasp of business and operations but lacking technological vision.<ref>Turner, Kevin. [http://money.cnn.com/gallery/technology/2013/08/26/microsoft-ceo-ballmer-replacements.fortune/6.html \"Who will succeed Steve Ballmer at Microsoft?\"] ''Fortune'' / CNN. Retrieved September 4, 2013.</ref> On February 4, 2014, [[Satya Nadella]] succeeded Ballmer as CEO.<ref name=nadella/>\n\n===Public image===\nAlthough as a child he was so shy that he would hyperventilate before [[Hebrew school]],<ref name=\"leibovich20001231\"/> Ballmer is known for his energetic and exuberant personality, which is meant to motivate employees and partners,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2009/09/11/ballmer_iphone_bing_win_7_ad|title=Ballmer garnishes Bing 2.0 with iPhone 'stomp': Return of the Kool-Aid kid|author=Gavin Clarke|year=2009|work=The Register|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> shouting so much that he needed surgery on his vocal cords.{{r|leibovich20001231}}\n\nBallmer's flamboyant stage appearances at Microsoft events are widely circulated on the Internet as [[viral video]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.onsoftware.com/the-best-and-worst-of-barmy-steve-balmer/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100603051704/http://en.onsoftware.com/the-best-and-worst-of-barmy-steve-balmer/|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 3, 2010|title=The best and worst of barmy Steve Balmer|author=Nicholas Mead|year=2010|accessdate=November 27, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/01/06/microsoft_slate|title=Ballmer readies slate PC for CES: Monkey boy to hurl spoiler at Apple?|author=John Oates|year=2010|work=The Register|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2385972,00.asp?kc=PCRSS03079TX1K0000585|title=Microsoft Needs to Check Itself|author=John C. Dvorak|work=PC Magazine|accessdate=June 12, 2011|date=May 26, 2011}}</ref> One of his earliest known viral videos was his promotion of [[Windows 1.0]] for a [[Crazy Eddie]] commercial in 1985, where he energetically shouts \"How much do YOU think this advanced operating environment is worth? WAIT just one minute before you answer\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.laptopmag.com/articles/steve-ballmers-9-craziest-moments|title=9 Craziest Steve Ballmer Moments|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/nov/15/microsoft-windows-system-apps|title=Has Microsoft's Windows had its day?|first=Charles|last=Arthur|date=November 15, 2010|website=the Guardian}}</ref> Ballmer and [[Brian Valentine]] repeated this in a spoof promotion of [[Windows XP]] later on.<ref>Avram Piltch, Laptop Mag; 9 Craziest Steve Ballmer Moments, https://www.laptopmag.com/articles/steve-ballmers-9-craziest-moments</ref>\n\nA widely circulated video was his entrance on stage at Microsoft's 25th anniversary event in September 2000,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wallstreetinsanity.com/steve-ballmers-top-11-craziest-moments/|title=Steve Ballmer's Top 11 Craziest Moments|website=wallstreetinsanity.com}}</ref> where he shouted and jumped across the stage, and saying \"I love this company\". It has been nicknamed 'monkey boy dance'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/microsoft/8041510/Who-is-Steve-Ballmer.html|title=Who is Steve Ballmer?|first=Claudine|last=Beaumont|date=October 5, 2010|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> Another well-known viral video was one captured at a [[Windows 2000]] developers' conference, featuring a perspiring Ballmer chanting the word \"[[software developer|developers]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Wakabayashi|first=Daisuke|title=Ballmer becomes lone voice at Microsoft's helm|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2008/06/29/us-microsoft-ballmer-idUSN2634300220080629|work=Reuters|accessdate=December 6, 2012|date=June 29, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2010/03/15/ballmers-visage-evoked-for-developers-developers-developers|title=Ballmer's visage evoked for 'developers, developers, developers' demo app on Windows Phone 7 Series|author=Chris Ziegler|year=2010|work=Engadget|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Relationship with Bill Gates===\nBallmer was Gates' [[best man]] at his wedding to [[Melinda French]], and the two men described their relationship as a marriage. They were so close for years that another Microsoft executive described it as a [[mind meld]]. Combative debates\u2014a part of Microsoft's corporate culture\u2014that many observers believed were personal arguments occurred within the relationship; while Gates was glad in 2000 that Ballmer was willing to become CEO so he could focus on technology,{{r|leibovich20001231}} the ''Wall Street Journal'' reported that there was tension surrounding the transition of authority. Things became so bitter that, on one occasion, Gates stormed out of a meeting in a huff after a shouting match in which Ballmer jumped to the defense of several colleagues, according to an individual present at the time. After the exchange, Ballmer seemed \"remorseful\", the person said. Once Gates leaves, \"I'm not going to need him for anything. That's the principle\", Ballmer said. \"Use him, yes, need him, no\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121261241035146237?mod=googlenews_wsj&apl=y&r=125394|title=Gates-Ballmer Clash Shaped Microsoft's Coming Handover|author=Robert A. Guth|work=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=June 5, 2008|date=June 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, a few months after Ballmer left his post at Microsoft, a ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' profile stated that Ballmer and Gates no longer talk to each other due to animosity over Ballmer's resignation.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=McLean|first1=Bethany|title=The Empire Reboots|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/business/2014/11/satya-nadella-bill-gates-steve-ballmer-microsoft#|magazine=Vanity Fair|accessdate=October 8, 2014}}</ref> In a November 2016 interview, Ballmer said he and Gates have \"drifted apart\" ever since, saying that they always had a \"brotherly relationship\" beforehand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/why-steve-ballmer-and-bill-gates-have-drifted-apart-2016-11|title=Steve Ballmer and Bill Gates have 'drifted apart' since Ballmer left Microsoft|publisher=}}</ref> He said that his push into the hardware business, specifically [[smartphone]]s, which Gates did not support, contributed to their relationship breakdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-11-04/steve-ballmer-says-smartphones-broke-his-relationship-with-bill-gates|title=Steve Ballmer Says Smartphones Strained His Relationship With Bill Gates|date=November 4, 2016|publisher=|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nAfter saying in 2008 that he intended to remain CEO for another decade, Ballmer announced his retirement in 2013, after losing billions of dollars in acquisitions and on the Surface tablet. Microsoft's stock price rebounded on the news.<ref>[https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/08/27/ballmer_time_to_go/ \"Why Teflon Ballmer had to go: He couldn't shift crud from Windows 8, Surface\"].</ref>\n\nBallmer says that he regretted the lack of focus on [[Windows Mobile]] in the early 2000s, leaving Microsoft a distant third in the current smartphone market.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-24178512 |title=Microsoft too slow on phones, admits boss Steve Ballmer |date=September 20, 2013 |work=BBC News|accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> Moreover, he attributed the success of the expensively-priced [[iPhone]]s to carrier subsidies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.recode.net/2016/11/7/13548032/steve-ballmer-apple-iphone-bloomberg|title=Steve Ballmer says Apple's iPhone succeeded because of carrier subsidies. He's wrong.|first=Ina|last=Fried|date=November 7, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> He went on to say,{{Quote|People like to point to this quote where I said iPhones will never sell, because the price at $600 or $700 was too high. And there was a business model innovation by Apple to get it essentially built into the monthly cellphone bill.}} He called the acquisition of the mobile phone division of [[Nokia]] as his \"toughest decision\" during his tenure, as it was overseeing the changing profile of Microsoft as it was expanding on hardware.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alphr.com/news/387415/ballmer-nokia-buy-was-hardest-decision-at-microsoft|title=Ballmer: Nokia buy was hardest decision at Microsoft|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nBallmer hosted his last company meeting in September 2013,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-24301733 |title=Microsoft boss Steve Ballmer dances at tearful send-off |date=September 27, 2013|work=BBC News|accessdate=September 27, 2013}}</ref> and stepped down from the company's board of directors, in August 2014.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alex |last=Wilhelm |title=Steve Ballmer Steps Down From Microsoft's Board |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/08/19/ballmer-steps-down-from-microsofts-board/?ncid=pushup |work=Techcrunch |date=August 19, 2014 |accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn December 24, 2014, the ''[[Seattle Times]]'' reported that the [[Microsoft v. Internal Revenue Service|IRS sued]] Ballmer, [[Craig Mundie]], [[Jeff Raikes]], [[Jim Allchin]], Orlando Ayala and David Guenther in an effort to compel them to testify in Microsoft's corporate tax audit. The IRS has been looking into how Microsoft and other companies deal with [[transfer pricing]].<ref name=\"seattletimes\">{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/businesstechnology/2025308578_microsoftirsxml.html|title=IRS demands Ballmer, other Microsoft leaders testify in corporate tax audit &#124; The Seattle Times|publisher=seattletimes.com|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Other positions==\nBallmer served as director of [[Accenture]] Ltd. and a general partner of Accenture SCA from 2001 to 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsroom.accenture.com/subjects/accenture-corporate/accenture-appoints-two-new-independent-directors-to-its-board.htm|title=Accenture Appoints Two New Independent Directors to Its Board|publisher=Accenture|date=February 2, 2006|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==On competing companies and software==\n\n===Apple===\nIn 2007, Ballmer said \"There's no chance that the <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> [[iPhone]] is going to get any significant market share. No chance.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/heres-what-steve-ballmer-thought-about-the-iphone-five-years-ago-2012-6#ixzz2gnjXZ4wo |title=Here's What Steve Ballmer Thought About The iPhone Five Years Ago |website=Business Insider |date=June 29, 2012 |accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking at a conference in NYC in 2009, Ballmer criticized Apple's pricing, saying, \"Now I think the tide has turned back the other direction (against Apple). The economy is helpful. Paying an extra $500 for a computer in this environment\u2014same piece of hardware\u2014paying $500 more to get a logo on it? I think that's a more challenging proposition for the average person than it used to be.\"<ref name=\"slashgear\">{{cite news|url=http://www.slashgear.com/ballmer-critiques-apple-500-more-to-get-a-logo-2038377|title=Apple is no more than a $500 logo|date=March 20, 2009|accessdate=August 3, 2009}} [[SlashGear]]</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Ballmer called Microsoft's decision to invest in Apple to save it from [[bankruptcy]] in 1997 as the \"craziest thing we ever did\". By 2015, Apple was the world's most valuable company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/microsofts-biggest-mistake-investing-apple-was-craziest-thing-we-ever-did-1525752|title=Microsoft's biggest mistake: Investing in Apple was the 'craziest thing we ever did'|first=James|last=Billington|date=October 26, 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Ballmer did an interview with Bloomberg where Ballmer added context to his [[iPhone]] statement, saying \"People like to point to this quote...but the reason I said that was the price of $600-$700 was too high\", he says he did not realize the business model innovation that Apple was going to deploy, using the carriers to subsidize the phones by building the cost into the customer's monthly bill.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qFe0S3F389w</ref>\n\n===Free and open source software===\nIn July 2000, Ballmer called the [[free software]] [[Linux kernel]] \"[[communism]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2000/07/31/ms_ballmer_linux_is_communism/|title=MS' Ballmer: Linux is communism|publisher=}}</ref> and further claimed that it infringed with Microsoft's intellectual property.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/ballmer-linux-infringes-our-intellectual-property/|title=Ballmer: Linux \"Infringes our intellectual property\" - ZDNet|first=Adrian|last=Kingsley-Hughes|publisher=}}</ref> In June 2001 he called Linux a \"cancer that attaches itself in an intellectual property sense to everything it touches\".<ref name=\"viral\">{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20011211130654/http://www.suntimes.com/output/tech/cst-fin-micro01.html |date=December 11, 2001 |title=Microsoft CEO takes launch break with the Sun-Times }}, ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', June 1, 2001; archived from the [http://www.suntimes.com/output/tech/cst-fin-micro01.html original] on December 11, 2001; retrieved December 18, 2009.</ref> Ballmer used the notion of [[viral license|\"viral\" licensing terms]] to express his concern over the fact that the [[GNU General Public License]] (GPL) employed by such software requires that all derivative software be under the GPL or a compatible license. In April 2003 he even interrupted his skiing holiday in [[Switzerland]] to personally plead with the mayor of [[Munich]] not to switch to GNU/Linux.<ref name=\"Munich1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/munich-breaks-with-windows-for-linux/|title=Munich breaks with Windows for Linux|newspaper=CNET|access-date=November 23, 2016}}</ref> But he did not succeed with this and Munich switched to [[LiMux]], despite his offering a 35% discount at his [[lobbying|lobbying visit]].<ref name=\"Munich2\">{{Cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/industries/technology/2003-07-13-microsoft-linux-munich_x.htm|title=Linux took on Microsoft, and won big in Munich|newspaper=USAtoday|access-date=November 28, 2016}}</ref> Munich has since backtracked on using LiMux; in November 2017, the Munich City Council resolved to reverse the migration and return to Microsoft Windows-based software by 2020.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Heath|first1=Nick|title=Linux pioneer Munich supports Windows 10 rollout from 2020 in key vote|url=https://www.techrepublic.com/article/linux-pioneer-munich-supports-windows-10-rollout-from-2020-in-key-vote/|website=TechRepublic|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=March 13, 2018|date=November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Ballmer changed his stance on Linux, saying that he supports his successor [[Satya Nadella]]'s [[Open-source model|open source]] commitments. He maintained that his comments in 2001 were right at the time but that times have changed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.informationweek.com/software/ballmer-linux-no-longer-a-cancer--/d/d-id/1324661|title=Ballmer: Linux No Longer A Cancer - InformationWeek|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.silicon.co.uk/software/open-source/steve-ballmer-linux-microsoft-187802?inf_by=5a088e9d671db8d83d8b4959|title=Steve Ballmer: Linux Is No Longer 'A Cancer'|date=March 11, 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Google===\nIn 2005, Microsoft sued Google for hiring one of its previous vice presidents, [[Kai-Fu Lee]], claiming it was in violation of his one-year non-compete clause in his contract. [[Mark Lucovsky]], who left for Google in 2004, alleged in a sworn statement to a Washington state court that Ballmer became enraged upon hearing that Lucovsky was about to leave Microsoft for [[Google]], picked up his chair, and threw it across his office, and that, referring to then Google Executive Chairman [[Eric Schmidt]] (who had previously worked for competitors Sun and Novell), Ballmer vowed to \"kill Google.\"<ref name=\"Heats up\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/4213466.stm | work=BBC News | title=Microsoft-Google battle heats up | date=September 4, 2005}}</ref> Lucovsky reports:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2005/09/05/chair_chucking/|title=Microsoft's Ballmer: Chair-tossing potty-mouth|work=The Register|author=John Oates|date=September 5, 2005|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|At some point in the conversation Mr. Ballmer said: \"Just tell me it's not Google.\" I told him it was Google. At that point, Mr. Ballmer picked up a chair and threw it across the room hitting a table in his office. Mr. Ballmer then said: \"Fucking Eric Schmidt is a fucking pussy. I'm going to fucking bury that guy, I have done it before, and I will do it again. I'm going to fucking kill Google.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/08/24/top_10_steve_ballmer_quotes_from_microsoft_history/|title=Top 10 Steve Ballmer quotes: '%#&@!!' and so much more|website=The Register|date=August 24, 2013|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nBallmer then resumed attempting to persuade Lucovsky to stay at Microsoft. Ballmer has described Lucovsky's account of the incident as a \"gross exaggeration of what actually took place\".<ref name=\"Heats up\" />\n\nDuring the 2011 [[Web 2.0 Summit]] in San Francisco, he said: \"You don't need to be a computer scientist to use a Windows Phone and you do to use an Android phone&nbsp;... It is hard for me to be excited about the Android phones.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://androidandme.com/2011/10/news/steve-ballmer-android-is-for-computer-science-geeks/ |title=Steve Ballmer: Android is for computer science geeks |publisher=Android and Me |date=October 19, 2011 |accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MTX1e-pMN6E |title=Microsoft's Ballmer mocks Android phone |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Ballmer said that Google was a \"[[monopoly]]\" that should be pressured from market competition authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/9/20/4751516/ballmer-calls-google-a-monopoly|title=Ballmer calls Google a 'monopoly' that authorities should control|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\nOn March 6, 2008, [[List of mayors of Seattle|Seattle mayor]] [[Greg Nickels]] announced that a local ownership group involving Ballmer made a \"game-changing\" commitment to invest $150&nbsp;million in cash toward a proposed $300&nbsp;million renovation of [[KeyArena]] and were ready to purchase the [[Seattle SuperSonics]] from the [[Professional Basketball Club LLC]] in order to keep the team in Seattle. However, this initiative failed, and the SuperSonics [[Seattle SuperSonics relocation to Oklahoma City|relocated]] to [[Oklahoma City]], [[Oklahoma]], where they now play as the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.seattle.gov/news/detail.asp?ID=8243&dept=40 |title=Mayor Nickels announces local effort to buy Sonics, renovate KeyArena |publisher=Seattle.gov |date= |accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, Ballmer was an investor in [[Chris R. Hansen]]'s [[Sonics Arena|proposal to build a new arena]] in the [[SoDo, Seattle|SoDo neighborhood]] of Seattle and bring the SuperSonics back to Seattle.<ref>{{cite news | last = Thompson | first = Lynn and Young, Bob | title = Ballmer, Nordstroms part of Seattle arena investor group | pages = | newspaper = The Seattle Times | date = June 13, 2012 | url = http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2018421214_arena14m.html}}</ref> On January 9, 2013, Ballmer and Hansen led a group of investors in an attempt to purchase the [[Sacramento Kings]] from the [[Maloof family]] and [[Failed Relocation of the Sacramento Kings#Seattle|relocate]] them to Seattle for an estimated $650&nbsp;million. However, this attempt also fell through.<ref>espn.com, [http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/11005695/seattle-bid-nba-team-dealt-blow-steve-ballmer-agrees-purchase-los-angeles-clippers Clippers name has to go with Sterling], accessed May 30, 2014.</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Donald Sterling#Racial remarks and lifetime ban|Donald Sterling scandal]] in May 2014, Ballmer was the highest bidder in an attempt to purchase the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] for a reported price of $2&nbsp;billion, which is the second highest bid for a sports franchise in North American sports history (after the $2.15&nbsp;billion sale of the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] in 2012). After a California court confirmed the authority of [[Shelly Sterling]] to sell the team, it was officially announced on August 12, 2014, that Ballmer would become the Los Angeles Clippers owner.<ref name=\"nbcnews\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/sports/steve-ballmer-takes-over-ownership-los-angeles-clippers-n178761 |title=Steve Ballmer Takes Over Ownership of Los Angeles Clippers - NBC News |publisher=nbcnews.com|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2014, Ballmer said he would bar the team from using [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] products such as [[iPad]]s, and replace them with Microsoft products.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/nba/2014/9/25/6844451/steve-ballmer-clippers-apple-ban-policy-microsoft-nba-2014|title=Ballmer wants Clippers to ban Apple products|publisher=}}</ref> It has been reported that he had previously also barred his family from using iPhones.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Maddaus |first1=Gene |title=Steve Ballmer To Ban L.A. Clippers From Using Apple Products |url=https://www.laweekly.com/steve-ballmer-to-ban-l-a-clippers-from-using-apple-products/ |website=LA Weekly |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |date=September 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Ballmer agreed to buy [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]] in [[Inglewood, California]].<ref name=\"The Forum\">{{cite web |last1=Greif |first1=Andrew |title=Clippers buy Forum for $400 million, clearing way for new arena construction |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/clippers/story/2020-03-24/ballmer-clippers-buy-forum-from-msg-for-400-million-dollars |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=April 4, 2020 |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The purchase would allow him to build a new arena for the Clippers in the nearby area since plans for a new Clippers' arena were opposed by the former owners of The Forum.<ref name=\"The Forum\" />\n\n==Wealth==\nBallmer was the second person after [[Roberto Goizueta]] to become a [[billionaire]] in U.S. dollars based on [[employee stock option|stock options]] received as an employee of a [[corporation]] in which he was neither a founder nor a relative of a founder. {{as of|2017|12|11|df=US}}, his personal wealth is estimated at US$37.1&nbsp;billion.<ref name=FSB /> While CEO of Microsoft in 2009, Ballmer earned a total compensation of $1,276,627, which included a base salary of $665,833, a cash bonus of $600,000, no stock or options, and other compensation of $10,794.\n\n==Philanthropy==\nOn November 12, 2014, it was announced that Ballmer and his wife Connie donated $50&nbsp;million to the [[University of Oregon]]. Connie Ballmer is a University of Oregon alumna and serves on the institution's [[Board of Trustees of the University of Oregon|board of trustees]]. The funds will go towards the university's $2&nbsp;billion fundraising effort, and will focus towards scholarships, public health research and advocacy, and external branding/communications.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Klinger|first1=Tobin|title=UO announces $50 million gift to fundraising campaign|url=http://around.uoregon.edu/content/uo-announces-50-million-gift-fundraising-campaign|publisher=AroundtheO|accessdate=November 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn November 13, 2014, it was announced that Ballmer would provide a gift, estimated at $60 million, to Harvard University's computer science department. The gift would allow the department to hire new faculty, and hopefully increase the national stature of the program. Ballmer previously donated $10 million to the same department in 1994, in a joint-gift with [[Bill Gates]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shu|first1=Catherine|title=Steve Ballmer's Harvard Donation Will Allow It To Add 12 New Computer Science PROFESSORS PROFESSORS PROFESSORS|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/11/12/steve-ballmer-harvard/|accessdate=November 14, 2014|work=TechCrunch}}</ref>\n\nBallmer serves on the World Chairman's Council of the [[Jewish National Fund]], which means he has donated US$1 million or more to the JNF.<ref name=\"jnfworldschairmancouncil\">{{cite web|title=World's Chairman Council|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912093518/http://www.jnf.org/assets/pdf/world-chairman-s-council-ad.pdf |website=Jewish National Fund}}</ref>\n\n==USAFacts==\nBallmer launched [[USAFacts.org]] in 2017, a non-profit organization whose goal is to allow people to understand US government revenue, spending and societal impact. He is reported to have contributed $10 million to fund teams of researchers who populated the website's database with official data.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/steve-ballmers-usafacts-site-surfaces-government-spending/|title=Steve Ballmer's USAFacts Site Surfaces Government Spending|last=Goldman|first=Joshua|website=CNet|accessdate=April 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/21/we-need-more-projects-like-usafacts/|title=Steve Ballmer's US data trove isn't the first, but may be the best|work=Engadget|access-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/editorials/sd-steve-ballmer-website-usafacts-20170808-story.html|title=Steve Ballmer has a website that could change government|last=Board|first=The San Diego Union-Tribune Editorial|work=sandiegouniontribune.com|access-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1990, Ballmer married Connie Snyder;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailyentertainmentnews.com/?p=14842|title=Steve Ballmer and wife Connie Ballmer|publisher=Daily Entertainment News|date=March 1, 2013}}</ref> they have three sons.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/jun/27/microsoft.microsoft The Guardian: \"Loyalty is his number one strength. He still drives Ford cars because his father used to work for the company\" by Bobbie Johnson] June 28, 2008</ref>\n\nThe Ballmers live in [[Hunts Point, Washington]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/102032526#|title=Former Microsoft CEO and LA Clippers Owner Steve Ballmer Speaks with CNBC's Josh Lipton Today | first=Josh | last=Lipton | publisher=[[CNBC]] | date=September 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/exec/steve/default.aspx Corporate biography]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7lhlKF6MECs, CS50 Lecture by Steve Ballmer at [[Harvard University]], November 2014]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110430024247/http://streaming.scmp.com/podcasting/upload/tech_may24.mp3 South China Morning Post audio interview]\n* [http://web.mit.edu/echemi/www/ballmer.html Steve Ballmer Playlist] Appearance on WMBR's ''[http://web.mit.edu/echemi/www/index.html Dinnertime Sampler]'' radio show February 23, 2005\n* [https://www.forbes.com/profile/steve-ballmer/ Forbes Profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Bill Gates]] | title = Chief Executive Officer of [[Microsoft]] | years = 2000\u20132014 | after = [[Satya Nadella]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Microsoft}}\n{{Los Angeles Clippers}}\n{{NBAOwners}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Sports}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ballmer, Steve}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American chief operating officers]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American Internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:American people of Belarusian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Swiss descent]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Seattle]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Detroit Country Day School alumni]]\n[[Category:Directors of Microsoft]]\n[[Category:Harvard Crimson alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Advocate alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Clippers owners]]\n[[Category:Microsoft employees]]\n[[Category:People from Farmington Hills, Michigan]]\n[[Category:People from Hunts Point, Washington]]\n[[Category:Stanford University students]]\n", "name_user": "Dellson", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Ballmer"}
{"title_page": "Cam Malfroy", "text_new": "{{Use New Zealand English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name                             = Cam Malfroy\n|image                             =Cam Malfroy 1935.jpg\n| image_size = 235px\n|caption                           = Malfroy in 1935\n|fullname                          = Camille Enright Malfroy\n|country                           = {{NZL}}\n|residence                         =\n|birth_date                         = {{Birth date|1909|01|21|df=y}}<ref name=\"aceshigh1994\"/>\n|birth_place                        = [[Hokitika]], New Zealand\n|death_date                         = {{Death date and age|1966|5|8|1909|01|21|df=y}}<ref name=\"aceshigh1994\"/>\n|death_place                        =\n|height                            = <!-- {{convert|HEIGHT IN METRES|m|abbr=on}} or {{convert|FEET|ft|INCHES|in|abbr=on}} -->\n|weight                            = <!-- {{convert|WEIGHT IN KILOS|kg|abbr=on}} or {{convert|WEIGHT IN POUNDS|lb|abbr=on}} -->\n|college                           =\n|turnedpro                         =\n|retired                           =\n|plays                             =\n|careerprizemoney                  =\n|singlesrecord                     =\n|singlestitles                     =\n|highestsinglesranking             =\n|AustralianOpenresult              = 2R ([[1934 Australian Championships - Men's Singles|1934]])\n|AustralianOpenjuniorresult        =\n|AustralianOpenseniorresult        =\n|FrenchOpenresult                  = 2R ([[1934 French Championships - Men's Singles|1934]])\n|FrenchOpenjuniorresult            =\n|FrenchOpenseniorresult            =\n|Wimbledonresult                   = 4R ([[1931 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|1931]], [[1936 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|1936]])\n|Wimbledonjuniorresult             =\n|Wimbledonseniorresult             =\n|USOpenresult                      =\n|USOpenjuniorresult                =\n|USOpenseniorresult                =\n|Othertournaments                  = <!-- adds a \"Major tournaments\" title -->\n|MastersCupresult                  =\n|WTAChampionshipsresult            =\n|Olympicsresult                    =\n|doublesrecord                     =\n|doublestitles                     =\n|highestdoublesranking             =\n|currentdoublesranking             =\n|grandslamsdoublesresults          =\n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult       =\n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult           =\n|WimbledonDoublesresult            =\n|USOpenDoublesresult               =\n|OthertournamentsDoubles           = <!-- adds a \"Major doubles tournaments\" title -->\n|MastersCupDoublesresult           =\n|OlympicsDoublesresult             =\n|Mixed                             = <!-- adds mixed information-->\n|mixedrecord                       =\n|mixedtitles                       =\n|AustralianOpenMixedresult         =\n|FrenchOpenMixedresult             =\n|WimbledonMixedresult              =\n|USOpenMixedresult                 =\n|Team = yes\n|DavisCupresult = QF<sup>Eu</sup> ([[1934 International Lawn Tennis Challenge|1934]])\n}}\n'''Camille Enright Malfroy''', {{postnominals|country=NZL|size=100%|DFC}} (21 January 1909 \u2013 8 May 1966)<ref name=\"Tennis\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20120310075920/http://www.tennisarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=2571 Cam Malfroy]. Tennis Archives</ref> was a prominent New Zealand [[tennis]] player of the 1930s and 1940s, competing in numerous grand slam championships of the era, and a fighter pilot and [[flying ace]] of the [[Second World War]].<ref name=\"NZ\"/>\n\n==Early and personal life==\nCamille Enright Malfroy was born in [[Hokitika]] on 21 January 1909 the son of Camille M. Malfroy, of the [[State Forest Department]], [[Wellington]] and younger brother of the rugby player [[Jules Malfroy]]. The Malfroy family in New Zealand was descended from Jean Baptiste Malfroy, originally from [[Macornay]], [[Lons-le-Saunier]], France, a miller, and his wife, Josephine Pricarde. Jean Baptiste along with two of his sons, [[Jean Michel Camille Malfroy]], usually known as Camille, and Jules C\u00e9zar Malfroy (the eldest of the three brothers), joined the rush to the Victorian goldfields in the 1850s and arrived in New Zealand in the early 1860s.<ref>Philip Andrews (1993). [http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/2m28/1 Malfroy, Jean Michel Camille]. ''Dictionary of New Zealand Biography''.</ref>\n\nMalfroy, like his older brother Jules, attended [[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]], where he studied Economics.<ref>[http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=EP19301224.2.12 STUDENT WORLD]. ''Evening Post'', Volume CX, Issue 151, 24 December 1930, Page 3.</ref> At Cambridge he received his Blue for tennis and was also a noted rugby player.\n\n[[File:Cam Malfroy with family 1951.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Malfroy with family in 1951]]\nIn 1939 Malfroy married Sybil Gordon. They divorced in the 1940s. Malfroy remarried in 1948.<ref>[https://natlib.govt.nz/records/17161223 Mr. C.E. Malfroy, the well-known New Zealand Davis Cup tennis player, and Miss Sybil Gordon, to whom he is engaged. The bride-to-be is the daughter of Mr. and Mrs. CW. Gordon, of Bordersmead, Loughton]. ''Evening Post'' (17 October 1939)</ref><ref>[https://www.myheritage.com/names/camille_malfroy Camille Malfroy]. myheritage.com</ref>\n\n==Tennis career==\nIn the 1930s Cam Malfroy was a well-known tennis player and represented [[New Zealand Davis Cup team|New Zealand]] in the [[Davis Cup]].<ref name=\"Tennis\"/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160303183749/http://www.daviscup.com/en/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=10003955 Cam Malfroy]. Davis Cup profile.</ref> He played 12 matches for New Zealand between 1934 and 1939. In singles he won two matches and lost five, and in doubles he won three matches and lost two. Away from the [[Davis Cup]], he was in the final of the New Zealand tennis championships in 1932 and 1933, winning the title in 1933 after a five-set victory in the final against [[Clifford Sproule]].<ref>{{cite news |title=N.Z. Tennis Championships |url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/WHDT19340109.2.19?end_date=31-12-1935&items_per_page=50 |work=[[Waihi Daily Telegraph]] |date=9 January 1934|via=[[PapersPast]]}}</ref> He also competed in a number of Grand Slam tournaments, nine times at Wimbledon, and once each in the France and Australian Opens. The furthest he progressed in any of these was to the fourth round of the 1931 Wimbledon championships. After his 1934, the year of his final triumph in the New Zealand championships, he moved to [[England]] and thereafter only competed in Europe, notably at Wimbledon, but also a number of other minor tournaments. As a doubles player he also won the Men's title twice (once in 1929\u201330 partnering D. G. France and a second time in 1932\u201333 partnering I. A. Seay) and won the Mixed Doubles in 1932\u201333 partnering Miss M. Macfarlane.<ref>[http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/1966/tennis-lawn/4 Tennis, Lawn, New Zealand Championships]. Teara.govt.nz (2009-04-22). Retrieved on 2018-07-13.</ref>\n\n===Performance timeline===\n{{performance key|active=no|short=yes}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! Tournament !! 1927 !! 1928 !! 1929 !! 1930 !! 1931 !! 1932 !! 1933 !! 1934 !! 1935 !! 1936 !! 1937 !! 1938 !! 1939 !! 1946 !! 1947 \n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"|[[Australian Open]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1934 Australian Championships - Men's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"|[[French Open]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1934 French Championships - Men's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"|[[Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1930 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|2R]]\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1931 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|4R]]\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1932 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1934 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|3R]]\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1935 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|2R]]\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1936 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1938 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|2R]]\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1939 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[1947 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|1R]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"|[[U.S. Open (tennis)|U.S. Open]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"|Grand Slam Win-Loss\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20131\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\u20131\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20131\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\u20133\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20131\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\u20131\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20131\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\u20131\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20131\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"|[[Sport in New Zealand#Tennis|New Zealand tennis championships]]\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|2R\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|4R\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:yellow;\"|SF\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:thistle;\"|F\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#0f0;\"|'''W'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"|[[Sport in New Zealand#Tennis|Auckland championships]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:thistle;\"|F\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"|[[Sport in New Zealand#Tennis|North Island championships]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:#0f0;\"|'''W'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"|[[Sport in New Zealand#Tennis|Canterbury championships]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:thistle;\"|F\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"|[[Villa d'Este]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|A\n| style=\"t